<FIRST>u w AM-Obey-NorthDocuments     05-04 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obey-North Documents,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Obey Holds Up Central American Money Over Honduran Aid Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman vowed Wednesday
to hold up the release of more than $700 million in foreign aid for
Central America until the State Department answers new questions
about a secret quid pro quo deal between the Reagan White House and
Honduras.
   ``I don't expect to recommend any money for Central America
until we have some questions answered,'' Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.,
chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee on foreign
operations, said in a telephone interview.
   ``I am not trying to suggest that I would withhold aid for
Central America if the answers we get are answers I don't like,''
Obey added. ``But I do have an obligation to get those answers
before we provide any additional assistance to the same countries.''
   Documents released at the trial of former White House aide
Oliver L. North show that on Feb. 19, 1985, then-President Ronald
Reagan approved a plan to give Honduras ``incentives'' to support
the Nicaraguan contras after Congress stopped all U.S. military
assistance to the rebels. Major elements of the plan were carried
out, documents showed.
   A jury is deliberating North's guilt or innocence on 12 criminal
charges, including lying to Congress and the attorney general about
the Iran-Contra affair, misappropriating money, and conspiring to
defraud the Treasury.
   ``The North documents would seem to lead to some very troubling
conclusions about the use of foreign aid to persuade aid recipients
to provide foreign aid to the contras at a time when providing aid
to the contras was against official American government policy,''
Obey said.
   The congressman said he hoped to get answers from the State
Department ``anytime over the next two to three weeks.''
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee sources told The Washington
Post Wednesday that the committee probably would delay voting on
the nomination of John Negroponte as U.S. ambassador to Mexico
until questions raised by the North trial were resolved.
   Negroponte, who was U.S. ambassador to Honduras in 1985,
delivered a message from Reagan to Honduran President Roberto Suazo
Cordova that was part of the incentive plan. Negroponte also
attended a March 1985 meeting between then-Vice President Bush and
Suazo that White House documents described as part of the plan.
   The Post reported in its Thursday editions that Senate sources
said they doubted Negroponte's nomination was in danger, but said
Democrats on the panel agreed to informally postpone the vote to
elicit the administration's cooperation shedding light on the
Honduran deal.
</TEXT>
