<FIRST>r i PM-Guyana-Walesa     05-04 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guyana-Walesa,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoyte Rejects Allegations by Solidarity Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERT WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Desmond Hoyte has rejected
allegations by Poland's Lech Walesa that his socialist government
has persecuted union leaders and clergy during a strike called to
protest austerity measures.
   Hoyte said in a telegram to Walesa that the Solidarity trade
union leader had been ``the victim of a cruel hoax or serious
misrepresentation'' about the bitter, monthlong strike by workers
in this South American nation's state-run sugar and bauxite
industries.
   ``I find your telex very puzzling. Government is not aware of
any trade union leaders or priests being repressed in this
country,'' Hoyte said in Tuesday's message.
   He asked Walesa, the 1983 Nobel Peace laureate, for more
information about his allegations.
   Walesa had sent Hoyte a telex Friday calling for negotiations
with the strikers and asking him to ``stop the repression against
the union leaders and the priests who are with them.''
   The strike is to protest austerity measures adopted under
provisions of a $115 million aid package from the International
Monetary Fund.
   Protesters have burned government buildings and firebombed a
school and two rural courts during nationwide demonstrations in
which police have arrested about 100 people.
   Hoyte said in a May Day speech that he doubted if Walesa
understood English, the language spoken in Guyan, or could find the
country on a map.
</TEXT>
