<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Philippines-Evacuations     05-04 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Philippines-Evacuations,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Uprising Drove 130,000 Filipinos From Homes In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 130,000 civilians fled their
homes in the countryside last year to escape fighting between the
military and Communist guerrillas, the International Committee of
the Red Cross says.
   Thierry Tribolet, Red Cross relief department chief, said
Wednesday that his organization helped 24,000 families in at least
12 of country's 73 provinces last year.
   He said Mindanao, the archipelago nation's second largest
island, accounted for about 100,000 evacuees, with the rest on
Luzon and in the central Visayas island chain.
   Field reports indicate most of the civilians flee when the
military launches operations to flush out communist New People's
Army guerrillas, Tribolet said.
   The military often forces civilians to move out to prevent them
from feeding and sheltering insurgents and to isolate the rebels
from the rural population, their main source of support and
recruits.
</TEXT>
