<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Khashoggi-Trustees     05-04 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khashoggi-Trustees,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financier Dropped From College Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International financier Adnan M. Khashoggi is
being dropped as a trustee of The American University in
Washington, D.C., according to university president Dr. Richard
Berendzen.
   Khashoggi, who is jailed in Switzerland for extradition to the
United States, pledged $5 million in 1984 to build the university's
new sports and convocation center, which was named in his honor.
   But Khashoggi's failure to attend board meetings, rather than
the arrest, which caused the board to decide to drop him, Berendzen
said.
   Khashoggi had only attended one trustees' meeting since being
named to the board in 1983, and stayed a total of about 30 minutes,
he said.
   ``He may not even be aware he is on the board,'' Berendzen said.
``I wouldn't be surprised about that.''
   He said the board's executive committee decided early last month
not to nominate Khashoggi for a third term.
   ``We have no address for him,'' Berendzen said. ``We can't send
him any material. We can't even tell him when the meetings are.''
   Khashoggi, a native of Saudi Arabia, was indicted on charges of
fraud and obstruction of justice by a New York City grand jury. He
is charged with helping former Phillippine President Ferdinand
Marcos illegally remove millions of dollars from the Phillippines
to buy paintings and real estate in New York.
</TEXT>
