<FIRST>r w PM-PayRaise Bjt   05-04 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise, Bjt,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some In Congress Look To Judges To Provide Cover For Pay Raises</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some members of Congress are clearly curious
whether providing a pay raise for federal judges will supply enough
political cover to vote one for themselves as well.
   That was the one clear lesson on Wednesday when William H.
Rehnquist became the first chief justice to testify before Congress
in 50 years. Rehnquist, who makes $115,000 a year, appealed for 30
percent pay raises and annual cost-of-living increases for himself
and all federal judges.
   He appeared before a veritable hotbed of support for the
controversial idea of boosting top federal pay: the House Committee
on Post Office and Civil Service.
   Among members of the committee, the 51 percent pay raise lost by
just 12-9 on Feb. 7. In the House as a whole that day, that
increase _ for Congress, the judges and top executive branch
officials _ was defeated 380-48.
   ``We've felt very lonely on this issue,'' said Rep. Gary
Ackerman, D-N.Y., who voted for the pay raise. ``Those of us in
this branch are taking all the heat.''
   Chairman William Ford, D-Mich., who also voted for the pay
raise, ended the session with special thanks to Rehnquist. ``You
give us credibility in a way that almost no one else could,'' Ford
said.
   Before then, four members _ Ackerman and three who voted against
the raise, Connie Morella, R-Md.; Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo.,; and
Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio _ all asked whether, in proposing a judges'
raise, Rehnquist was advocating that the judges be treated
differently from their traditional pay equals in Congress and the
top executive offices.
   First, the chief justice said he had no position.
   But by the time the question was asked a fourth time, Rehnquist
said that just as good a case had been made for raises in Congress
and the executive as for judges. He said it was well within the
bounds of propriety for them to get 30 percent raises as well.
   It fell to Ackerman to make the point explicitly: ``The feeling
here is that if there's ever going to be a pay raise for the
legislative branch, we have to stay coupled with the judiciary.''
   So they threw him every argument against the raise that they had
heard to see how good his defenses sounded.
   What about voters who say that officials sought their offices
voluntarily knowing the salary in advance?
   Rehnquist: yes, but we didn't know that inflation would eat away
at our purchasing power.
   Judicial leaders predicted judges would quit if the raise was
defeated but they haven't; is that danger real?
   Rehnquist: more and more have quit in recent years, but ``even
now not a major or even a large minor percentage of the judges.''
   And the big one, as stated by Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., one of
several who made this point:
   ``A $10,000-a-year job or a $12,000-a-year job in Morgan County,
Ind., would be considered the job of a lifetime. The people there
who make those salaries can't understand how you can't get by on
$89,500.'' That is the salary of a federal district judge.
   Rehnquist replied, ``I have no good answer.'' But he added, ``I
never felt I wanted to go to a doctor who made no more than I did,
I wanted to go to a good doctor.''
   Other committee members kept touching on this argument. At
another point, Rehnquist responded: ``You want the best doctor,
don't you want the best judge?''
   Rehnquist said he worried that partners in big city law firms _
the highest paid lawyers in America _ were no longer coming onto
the bench. But then he added this observation:
   ``There's always going to be a large number of partners in big
city law firm who don't want to be federal judges, because they
don't want to make the financial sacrifices. If you're interested
in money and you now make $250,000, if the district judge's pay
goes from $89,500 to $115,000, it isn't going to influence you in
the least,'' Rehnquist said. ``Our pay raise is not going to affect
that.
   ``To get the very best, you have to offer not salaries that are
competitive with private practice but something that lets them live
a reasonably comfortable life and educate their kids.''
   But Rehnquist acknowledged getting mail on that point, including
a letter ``from someone earning $25,000 to $30,000 with a mortgage
who wanted to educate their kids too and wanted to know why I
wanted $150,000.''
   At the end, it was anybody's guess how many members thought
Rehnquist's explanations would satisfy their constituents and
provide political cover for a congressional raise.
   But all morning, no one mentioned an argument available to
members of Congress: unlike judges, who get the same pay, they have
to maintain two homes and commute between them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Michael J. Sniffen has covered legal issues in
Washington for 15 years.

</TEXT>
