<FIRST>r w PM-GingrichBook     05-04 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich Book,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Common Cause Asks Independent Counsel to Investigate Gingrich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The public affairs lobbying group that joined
Rep. Newt Gingrich last year in asking the House ethics committee
to investigate Speaker Jim Wright now is asking for an outside
counsel to investigate Gingrich.
   Fred Wertheimer, president of the lobbying group Common Cause,
made the request for an independent counsel in a letter Wednesday
to Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., chairman of the committee.
   ``The use of outside counsel helps ensure that the results of an
inquiry are credible to, and accepted by, the public,'' Wertheimer
said.
   Gingrich, R-Ga., charged that Common Cause, usually associated
with liberal causes, is trying to get back in the good graces of
Democrats who were upset when the group helped bring about
investigation of Wright, D-Texas.
   ``There are 15 to 20 members who have had pretty powerful
allegations of real scandals made against them in the press and I'm
in the middle of being smeared,'' Gingrich said. ``I find it
bizarre that Common Cause would jump past those scandals and ask
for an investigation of the guy who's being smeared, the
whistleblower.''
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., filed a formal complaint with the
committee last month accusing Gingrich of 10 apparent violations of
House rules in the operation of a limited partnership set up to
promote ``Window of Opportunity,'' a book written in 1984 by
Gingrich, his wife, Marianne Gingrich, and David Drake.
   According to the allegations, the 21 partners who put up $5,000
each in the book ended up with a tax writeoff because the publisher
lost money.
   Mrs. Gingrich was paid $11,500 for her work as the controlling
general partner. She also was given a 2 percent ownership interest
in the organization, although she did not invest any of her own
money.
   While he had no direct financial stake in the partnership,
Gingrich was paid $1,320 in expenses by the partnership when he
traveled to promote the book, and he and his wife each have
received $12,018 in royalties.
</TEXT>
