<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-America'sCup     05-04 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-America's Cup,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Diegans Appeal America's Cup Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Diego Yacht Club asked a state appeals
court Wednesday to overturn a judge's ruling that awarded the
America's Cup to a New Zealand boating club after September's
mismatched yacht race off San Diego.
   The West Coast sailors said that the ruling March 28 by state
Supreme Court Justice Carmen Ciparick was improper because the
judge invented a rule that didn't exist and illegally ordered the
cup forfeited.
   The judge said the San Diego Yacht Club had ``violated the
spirit'' of the race by using a 60-foot catamaran to defend the cup
against the Mercury Bay Boating Club's single-hulled yacht, which
is about 90 feet long at the waterline.
   The judge called the contest, which the San Diegans won, ``a
gross mismatch'' and ordered the 138-year-old silver cup turned
over to the New Zealanders.
   Oral arguments before the state Supreme Court's appellate
division have not been scheduled yet. In their filing Wednesday,
the San Diegans pointed to Ciparick's phrase saying the boats
should be ``somewhat evenly matched.''
   They said there was no such provision in the ``Deed of Gift,'' a
document that sets the rules for America's Cup races.
   The San Diego club argued that the forfeiture was ``drastic and
unfair'' and asked the appeals court to reverse it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
