<DOCNO> AP890504-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-StudentMarchers Bjt   05-04 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Student Marchers, Bjt,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chants, Banners, Shoving And Lost Shoes On The Road To Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They come by the thousands, carrying red and
white banners, bullhorns, leaflets and a fatalism leading many to
sew their names inside their clothes for identification in case
they are hurt.
   They confront unarmed police, young men fresh from the
countryside, many of whom still wear the black cloth slippers of
China's peasantry.
   On their way, they meet the people of Beijing, who line the
streets and pile on top of walls to watch and cheer.
   Five times in the last two weeks, Chinese students demanding
democracy and a free press have set out from their universities on
the 10-mile march to the center of the city.
   Today, they did it again, protesting the government's refusal to
recognize and open a dialogue with their independent student
association.
   _ Just east of Communist Party headquarters, April 20, 3:30 a.m.:
   A thousand students are conducting a sit-in demonstration,
blocking predawn truck traffic on Beijing's biggest boulevard,
Changan Avenue.
   ``One-two, sit down, one-two sit down,'' the students yell at
their standing classmates surrounding them.
   A man sits on a three-wheeled cart doing a fast business selling
orange soda pop. Hundreds more onlookers on bicycles stretch off
into the distance. Some demonstrators doze against a tree.
   Two lines of about 300 police block access to the party
headquarters at Zhongnanhai, where several hundred other students
also are sitting in.
   A police loudspeaker broadcasts a warning but cannot cut through
the students' din.
   ``Rise, ye who refuse to be slaves,'' the students bellow,
singing their national anthem. The students pass cigarettes to each
other. One has some dumplings that he shares.
   Police reinforcements arrive. Another warning is broadcast.
   With war whoops and battle cries the security forces rush the
crowd, sending it fleeing down the boulevard. A dawdling female
student is set upon by several officers, who slap her with open
hands. One student's bicycle wheel apparently gets stuck. He is
kicked to the ground and beaten.
   ``Police don't hit students,'' the crowd chants. The lights of
the boulevard cast a pale shadow over the protesters faces. Eyes
widen with fear.
   _ The intersection of New Street and South Institute Road, April
21, midnight:
   ``Long live freedom, long live democracy,'' roars a crowd of
tens of thousands as it moves south, banners flapping in the
late-night wind. Eight miles to go to Tiananmen Square, the
symbolic political center of China.
   Five buses, packed with passengers, wait, cemented in place by
the wall-to-wall crowd.
   ``Students, we love you,'' a young man with the beginnings of a
beard yells from one bus window.
   Students from dozens of colleges file by, school flag presented
in the front. Departments also carry their own flags.
   The students hold hands as they walk, girls with girls and boys
with boys. A ring of young men, student activists, surrounds the
group, preventing outsiders from entering their ranks.
   ``We are afraid of plainclothes police,'' says a student. ``They
are the ones who cause trouble and push.''
   _ Beijing University, April 27, 9 a.m.:
   The young men with the red arm bands are worried. Students from
Qinghua University, a major science center up the road, have
apparently dropped out of the protest set to begin in minutes.
   ``We can't stop it now,'' says one of the organizers.
   Thousands of their classmates line the entrance of the
university.
   ``Open the road,'' yells one leader.
   Moving neatly into line, the crowd rolls through the gates.
Hundreds of local residents pack the street. Others hang from their
windows or squat on roofs, clapping and flashing the V-for-victory
sign.
   At the first intersection, the crowd roars. Qinghua has arrived,
led by a banner: Qinghua Ren (Men).
   _ The Xidan Intersection, central Beijing. April 27, 4:15 p.m.:
   The intersection, one of the busiest in the city, swarms with
people. Some balance on top of a movie billboard advertising the
film ``Crazy Love.'' Others sit in the trees. Still more gather on
the avenue, licking popsicles and leaning slightly on their
neighbors.
   Another line of police forms to stop the marchers.
   Workers appear in the crowd _ older men with harder features,
stronger, dressed in the blue cotton of the Chinese working class.
   ``Clear the way, police,'' chants one part of the crowd as it
surges toward the officers, who stand arm-in-arm blocking the way.
   Another part of the crowd picks up the chant; it too surges
forward. One woman is pushed to the ground and screams.
   The banners loom closer, further compressing the pack.
   A late afternoon sun bathes the crowd in white light.
   The smell of sweat and garlic whirl together. The crowd pushes
again and breaks through the police lines, sending the officers
scattering to the side.
   ``My shoes, my shoes,'' yells one policeman, hobbling around in
his black nylon socks.
   An elderly lady returns one shoe. The second is found by a
marching student.
   Red and white banners, for democracy and a freer China, flap by.
</TEXT>
