<DOCNO> AP890504-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett     05-04 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Punishment Must Be Certain Rather than Long, Drug Czar Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Certainty of punishment is more important than
severity of punishment in dealing with drug offenders, drug czar
William J. Bennett says.
   ``I am for severe penalties, particularly when a drug crime is
severe, but what you have to have is certain punishment,'' Bennett
said Wednesday. ``You shouldn't make certain punishment hostage to
severe punishment.
   ``It would be better in many situations to have everyone that's
convicted of drug use to go to jail for a week ... than to just get
a third of them going for six months,'' he said.
   Bennett made his comments to reporters after telling several
hundred members of the Washington Metropolitan Area Interreligious
Coalition that ``those guilty of drug offenses must believe that
punishment is inevitable.''
   ``As long as they don't, the deterrent effect of incarceration
is neutralized,'' he said.
   The trend in recent years has been toward longer sentences for
crimes, and Bennett denied later that he was calling for reduced
sentences for drug offenders, including what he termed so-called
casual users.
   But he cited the practice in Phoenix as an example of where
short sentences have the desired impact on those who break the law.
   In that city, police are arresting drug users, many of them
middle-class, and putting them ``in jail for a weekend, that's all,
just a weekend,'' he said. ``For a lot of middle-class users, that
is plenty of time. ... They are cured after one weekend in the
slammer.''
   Bennett's speech, an overview of his thinking as he compiles his
national drug control strategy _ a report on which is due in early
September _ also called for parents to be made more responsible,
legally, for their children's transgressions.
   He cited in this case the example of Toledo, Ohio, where
``parents are brought before the juvenile-justice court and made to
answer for the actions of their children through civil penalties.''
   ``This policy establishes the principle that parents ... must
bear responsibility for the behavior and the activities of minors
in their charge,'' Bennett said. ``Minors who are non-addicted
users must be taught early on that they cannot behave with
impunity, and parents who have effectively turned them loose must
learn why the social contract demands that they oversee and control
the implses of their children.''
   Asked later if that included jailing parents for offenses
committed by their children, Bennett said that should occur only in
``extreme cases.''
   Bennett acknowledged that the federal government was unlikely to
get involved in imposing such regulations as the weekend jailings
and the arrests of parents and said such actions would be for the
state and local governments to carry out.
   The issues were raised, he said, because local officials have
asked him repeatedly to disseminate whatever good ideas are being
tried out around the country to combat illegal drugs.
   Bennett's speech, made only hours after his wife gave birth to
their second son, also addressed rehabilitation of drug users and
offenders.
   ``We don't know as much as we'd like to about how to treat drug
use, and sadly, many of our profoundly good-spirited efforts at
treatment have failed to pan out,'' he said. ``But what we do know
is this: successful programs and treatment almost always force the
addict to confront and internalize the fact of his addiction.''
   Bennett said it may take confrontation, primarily from the
family, for a drug user to recognize that ``there will be dire
consequences for him'' if he fails to end his addiction.
   But he said he realizes that ``rehabilitation is the wrong term
to use'' for many drug offenders, because the addict never had a
normal home life to begin with, and good habits must be instilled
for the first time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
