<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0317EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StudentAppeal     05-04 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Student Appeal,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>18-Year-Old Argues Before the State's highest Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plaintiff serving as his own counsel before
the state Supreme Judicial Court was younger than most attorneys:
He's 18.
   Harvard freshman Josh Gerstein, believed to be the youngest
person to argue before the state's highest court, appeared
Wednesday to protest what he says was a violation of the state's
Open Meeting Law.
   Gerstein contended the Weston School Committee violated the law
when it hired a superintendent in 1988.
   Gerstein said he spent more than 100 hours preparing for the
case. He submitted a 20-page brief. His arguments before five
jurists took only five minutes, but he said he was ``a lot more
nervous'' than when he argued the case before a lower court last
year.
   ``It's an interesting issue _ it's dealing with how much access
the public has to government,'' Gerstein told reporters after the
hearing.
   He said he was forced to skip Russian class.
   After Gerstein filed his complaint in 1988, he was joined by the
Middlesex County district attorney's office. An attorney from the
office also argued on behalf of the complaint Wednesday.
   Gerstein was a senior at Weston High School when he first
protested what he saw as insufficient student input in the
selection of a superintendent.
   Weston school officials contend they were entitled to close
three rounds of screening, including interviews, to the public.
   Gerstein and the district attorney say the law only allows the
first round of interviews to be closed.
   Gerstein said he has nothing against the superintendent chosen
by the committee, Meredith Jones. But he said he did not know if
she was more or less qualified than the other 100 original
candidates since students were excluded.
   A ruling is expected within four months.
   Despite his performance Wednesday, Gerstein said he does not
plan a career in law. He is majoring in government and wants to be
a journalist.
</TEXT>
