<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PesticideDangers     05-04 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pesticide Dangers,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA: No Assurance Imported Food is Pesticide-Free</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says it
can't assure that pesticides banned in the United States won't show
up on imported food.
   The head of EPA's division on pesticides and toxic substances
said Wednesday that pesticide residue on imported food could be a
huge problem.
   ``There is no simple way of finding out the pesticide usage of
countries exporting food to the United States,'' said Victor Kim.
   Kim's comments came during a hearing of the House subcommittee
on environment, energy and natural resources which has jurisdiction
over the EPA.
   Rep. Mike Synar, R-Okla., chairman of the subcommittee, blasted
the EPA for not having a better system for informing foreign
countries about the dangers of pesticides they buy from American
companies.
   ``The United States carries an environmental responsibility and
a moral obligation to ensure that foreign governments through the
world are provided with the best information on, assistance with
and, if necessary, protection from unsafe pesticides,'' said Synar.
   ``To date, the EPA has failed miserably in fulfilling this
responsibility.''
   He said the agency also has failed to do its job in protecting
the American food supply by informing agencies like the Agriculture
Department that countries selling food to the United States use
pesticides banned here.
   Synar displayed memos from Agriculture Department inspectors
about two shipments of Honduran beef that were contaminated with
chlordane, a chemical believed to cause cancer.
   ``Our reports show that chlordane is made only in the United
States,'' said Synar, noting, however, that it is not allowed to be
sold here as pesticide.
   Most of the beef in the shipments was sold to grocery stores,
ground up and purchased by consumers before it was discovered.
   Under questioning from Synar, EPA officials admitted that they
haven't followed their own suggestions for helping other countries
understand better the dangers of pesticides made in the United
States.
   Linda Fisher, EPA assistant administrator for policy, planning
and evaluation, said the agency was aware that more had to be done.
   But when presented with an internal EPA memo dated April 17,
1987 outlining improvements that should be made, she said none of
the recommendations had been followed.
   She assured Synar the EPA would act soon on the recommendations
and those of international negotiators trying to establish a
worldwide policy for pesticide use.
   According to a report from the General Accounting Office, an
investigative arm of Congress, the EPA doesn't have any procedures
for deciding when to notify foreign countries about pesticides that
the United States has decided are dangerous to human health.
   The report also said EPA doesn't have any standards for
determining when actions taken against pesticides in this country
are significant enough to warn another nation.
   ``The agency is considering improvements to its present
procedures, including those recommended by GAO,'' said Fisher.
   Under U.S. law, pesticides that are banned or unregistered
domestically can be sold abroad if foreign buyers provide a
statement saying they understand that the product is outlawed in
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
