<DOCNO> AP890504-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-SouthAfrica     05-04 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-South Africa,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran State Official Says Reagan-Era Bush Declaration was Wrong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late in the Reagan administration a task force
headed by Vice President George Bush branded 52 groups around the
world as practitioners of terrorism, among them the African
National Congress in white-ruled South Africa.
   Now, the veteran Foreign Service officer nominated by President
Bush to be assistant secretary of state for African affairs says
that was a mistake.
   At his confirmation hearing Wednesday before the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, the nominee, Herman J. Cohen, testified that
the black-nationalist organization is too important to be ignored
as the United States seeks a peaceful, negotiated end to South
Africa's system of racial apartheid.
   Cohen was asked by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., about the listing
of the ANC as a terrorist organization and about testimony from
Secretary of State James A. Baker III that it would be
``reasonable'' for the United States to shun such a group unless it
renounced terrorist tactics.
   Cohen took the opposite view.
   ``Sir, I think the designation of the ANC as a terrorist
organization was not correct,'' Cohen said.
   ``Wow!'' Helms exclaimed.
   Cohen said the ANC is a large and active organization and
conceded that the group's military wing has engaged in terrorist
acts.
   ``But I don't think we can designate the entire organization as
a terrorist organization because of one activity by one of their
wings,'' he said.
   ``In our discussions with them we have said we denounce such
violence and that our relations with them have to be very minimal
because of that.
   ``But since they are such an important organization and have
such a great influence in what goes on in South Africa, I don't
think it would be in our interest not to deal with them, not to
talk to them,'' Cohen said.
   Responding to further questions from Helms, Cohen said he
believes the military wing of the ANC has abandoned the practice of
``necklacing'' in which tires were placed around the necks of
opponents, filled with gasoline and set afire.
   He added that he would recommend that Baker meet with Oliver
Tambo, the ANC's president, if he visits Washington. He said a
meeting between Tambo and President Bush would depend on the
outcome of Tambo's discussions with Baker.
   Overall, Cohen said he sees a new realism emerging in South
Africa on both sides of the apartheid battle with the government
recognizing that it cannot impose changes on the black majority
without their consent and the majority recognizing it cannot cause
the collapse of the white power structure by direct frontal
assaults.
   ``It is increasingly clear to the black leadership, in my view,
that constitutional change will have to come through a process of
negotiation in which there will be no losers,'' the nominee said.
   Cohen, 57, a career Foreign Service officer since 1953, has
served as U.S. ambassador to the republics of Senegal and Gambia.
For the last two years he was the National Security Council's
senior director for Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
