<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-MedicareSurcharge     05-04 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare Surcharge,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medicare Surtax to Be Subject of Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee is arranging a
hearing this month to examine the financial underpinning of the new
catastrophic illness insurance program _ specifically whether the
surtax imposed on better-off Medicare recipients is too high.
   The hearing is a direct outgrowth of the outcry from elderly
Medicare beneficiaries who will be hit with an income tax surcharge
that can range up to $800 this year for about 5 percent of them in
upper income ranges.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, the committee chairman and a major
architect of the landmark legislation that took effect Jan. 1,
recently raised the prospect that the maximum surcharge could be
reduced. He said new revenue estimates show the tax surcharge will
generate more money than originally contemplated.
   Ironically, those revised estimates suggest elderly Americans as
a group are better off financially than calculated last summer when
Congress was deciding to finance a major part of the program with a
progressive surtax, or ``supplemental premium,'' applied only to
Medicare enrollees.
   President Bush has taken the position that even though more
money than anticipated is flowing into the Medicare catastrophic
illness coverage fund, it still will not be enough to cover costs
over the long term.
   By publicly asking Bush for his thoughts on reducing the surtax,
Bentsen has cast the White House in the role of opposing a tax
reduction for elderly Americans.
   However, Bentsen had predicted in January that much of the
political support for reducing the tax surcharge would evaporate
after it became clear from hearings that nearly two-thirds of
Medicare beneficiaries _ or about 21 million people _ would pay
only $48 a year in additional fees in 1989 _ the flat $4 a month
increase imposed on everyone.
   For the remaining 12 million beneficiaries _ those with enough
taxable income to have to pay at least $150 a year in tax _ the
surcharge is determined by adding $22.50 per person to each $150 of
income tax liability.
   That means the surtax can be as little as $45 for a couple, or
as much as $1,600 and will show up first on tax returns filed after
Jan. 1, 1990 covering the current year.
   Medicare beneficiaries in lower income ranges tend to have lower
tax liabilities than wage-earners with a comparable gross income
because their Social Security benefits are not subject to taxes.
   Although individual circumstances vary widely, Congress' Joint
Committee on Taxation estimates a typical couple on Medicare would
have to have an income of at least $20,000 a year before having to
pay a surcharge and that, on average, it would amount to about $50
for a couple in the $20,000-$25,000 income range.
   The committee estimates about 1.6 million of the 33 million
people covered by Medicare would be hit by the maximum surcharge
this year _ and a comparable percentage in subsequent years as both
benefits and costs increase.
   Both the basic monthly fee and the ``supplemental premium''
rise, reaching $10.20 a month and $42 per $150 tax liability in
1993 when the expansion _ including a new prescription drug benefit
_ is fully implemented.
   That translates to a maximum 1993 surtax of $1,050 per
individual, or $2,100 for a couple.
   Using those actual 1993 fees and surcharges, the Joint Taxation
Committee estimates 11.1 percent of the program's total cost will
be born by those in the $75,000 to $200,000 income range, that
taxpayers in that category account for 12.9 percent of all reported
income and that their average return will be $112,538, in 1988
dollars.
   It does not break down its distribution estimates to the
$75,000-$100,000 range _ the lowest category where the maximum
surtax would start taking effect _ but says the average return in
that category will be $87,371 for a couple, again in 1988 dollars.
   Because the surtax is capped, those with incomes above $200,000
will pay 3.2 percent of the program costs in 1993. They account for
19.3 percent of income reported on tax returns.
   By contrast, the committee estimates 23.9 percent of 1993
program costs will fall on those in the $20,000 to $30,000 income
range, again in 1988 dollars, even though they account for 18.2
percent of total income, and that 25.1 percent of the costs will be
borne by those in the $30,000 to $50,000 range, who account for
16.3 percent of all income.
   It projects the 1993 tax surcharge for a middle-class retired
couple with $20,000 to $25,000 income at about $90, rising to about
$240 for a couple with a $30,000 to $35,000 income.
   For the current year, the committee projects the supplemental
premium for a $20,000 to $25,000 a year couple will average about
$50, rising to about $150 for a couple in the $30,000-$35,000 range.
   The committee estimates the maximum 1989 surtax for a couple
will kick in at the $75,000 to $100,000 level and that the average
joint return in that category will be $85,751.
   It estimates the average return in the $100,000-$200,000 level
will be $136,304.
   For joint returns above $200,000, the average jumps to $677,495
per return.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
