<NOTE>End Urged to Ideological Limits on Travel</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writers and teachers urged Congress to rescind
laws that allow the government to keep foreigners out of the United
States because of their ideological beliefs.
   They testified Wednesday on a bill by Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass., that would gut the McCarran-Walter immigration law and
other laws that allow the federal government to restrict foreign
travel by Americans through limits on the way the dollar can be
spent.
   Novelist Larry McMurtry told the House Judiciary Committee's
subcommittee on courts, intellectual property and the
administration of justice the McCarran-Walter act ``abridges the
rights of Americans to engage in face-to-face discussions and
debate with foreign colleagues.''
   Choichiro Yatani, a Japanese who teaches psychology in the State
University of New York at Stony Brook, said he was jailed for 44
days and threatened with deportation over suspicions he was a
communist. He said his status in the country ``remains tenuous and
my name remains on the immigration `lookout list.'''
