<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Assailant     05-04 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Assailant,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Recounts How Wright Aide Once Nearly Killed Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pamela Small says she avoids business visits
to the Capitol because she could encounter the man who savagely
attacked her with a knife and hammer 16 years ago and now is a top
aide to House Speaker Jim Wright.
   But anger more than fear is what deters Small, an executive with
the Washington office of a major corporation. Anger that John Paul
Mack, 35, is one of the most powerful staff members on Capitol
Hill, earning about $89,500 a year as Wright's closest aide.
   Mack wouldn't have the job ``if he hadn't tried to kill me,''
Small told The Washington Post in an interview published today. She
described the unprovoked attack that required her to have seven
hours of emergency surgery and more than a year of plastic surgery
and hair transplants.
   ``Obviously, I would rather he still be in prison,'' she said.
``If he's not, I'm not sure what I would want him doing. But
playing a major part in running the government and making a lot of
money off my taxes isn't it.
   ``This guy has gotten special treatment from the beginning. All
the victim ever gets is a ride to the hospital.''
   Mack, whose brother was married to Wright's daughter at the
time, served just 27 months of a 15-year prison sentence for
malicious wounding before making parole, according to the Post. A
job offer from Wright helped make Mack's release possible, the
story said.
   The Post also reported that Mack served his sentence in the
Fairfax County, Va., Jail, rather than the state penitentiary.
   The attack happened in a discount store in the Washington suburb
of Annandale, Va., in 1973. Small was a 20-year-old college student
living with her parents but getting ready to move into her first
apartment.
   Mack was a clerk at the store, where Small went to buy blinds.
Unsuspectingly, Small followed Mack into a storeroom when the only
blinds on display turned out to be flawed. The attack began when
she refused to lie down as he had ordered.
   He pounded her once in the head with a hammer, knocking her
unconscious immediately, and then struck her four more times,
exposing her skull in five places, according to the Post.
   ``He just reached out with his arm and the next thing I knew ...
was the sound of the blow,'' she said. ``It was like when you dive
into water ... that sound. The sound and pain together were unreal
... like my brain was being squeezed into a tiny black dot.''
   He then stabbed her five times and slashed at her throat with a
steak knife.
   When she awoke some eight hours later, she was in her compact
car that Mack had driven to an alley. Despite her wounds, she drove
one mile to a service station for help.
   Although she knew as far back as 1977 that Mack was working on
the Hill _ she learned through an acquaintance who was dating him _
she didn't realize how prestigious a job he held.
   As executive director of the Congressional Democratic Steering
and Policy Committee, Mack decides which legislation to put on the
agenda, and which to keep off.
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif, called Mack one of the
``top five staffers on the Hill in terms of competence.''
   ``This society believes in forgiveness,'' Coelho said.
   Mack, when contacted by the Post, said: ``When I was 19, I made
a terrible, tragic mistake. I regret it every day. I accepted the
judgment of society then and I accept it now. I have to put that
behind me.
   ``All I ask is that I be judged by what I've done since in terms
of trustworthiness, loyalty to my country, my family, and those who
depend on me.''
   Wright refused to comment for the story.
</TEXT>
