<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Dissidents     05-04 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dissidents,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Leaders Say They Are Refused Entry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Chinese dissidents were stopped in Tokyo from
boarding a flight for Beijing today because the Chinese government
told airlines not to accept them, they said.
   Wang Bingzhang and Tang Guangzhang, leaders of the Chinese
Alliance of Democracy, said they were not allowed to get on Japan
Airlines Flight 5.
   The men said they wanted to come to Beijing to ``investigate''
the student pro-democracy movement, the biggest ever in Communist
China's 40-year history.
   A spokesman at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs declined to
comment on the dissidents' allegations because, he said, they did
not constitute a question of foreign affairs. He declined to say
which ministry handled the affair.
   Wang, a native of China who has become an American citizen, said
he had no visa to enter China. He said he had planned to stay in
China for several days ``on transit'' and then head to Thailand.
   Tang, a Chinese citizen and chemistry student at Utah State
University, said he did not understand why he had been denied the
right to board a plane to his homeland.
   He was thrown out of China on Jan. 9 after he was apprehended in
Shanghai with copies of China Spring. The magazine is published by
the Chinese Alliance of Democracy, based in New York City. Wang set
up the dissident group in 1983 to promote democracy in China.
   Chinese officials have declared the alliance and its magazine
illegal and reactionary.
   Earlier this week, the government implied the group had been
supporting the student movement.
   Wang said that although his group agrees with the students'
demands for a more democratic country, his organization had not
contacted the movement.
   But he said he was determined to enter China and do so.
   ``We have made up our minds to use any possible methods to
return, including sneaking into the country,'' Wang said.
   Tang said he didn't think his activities would hurt the movement
by giving the Chinese government an excuse to crack down on student
protesters.
   ``Democracy is a common desire of all peoples, both overseas and
inside China,'' he said. ``It doesn't make a difference where you
are.''
   Both men said they would return to the United States to consider
their next move.
</TEXT>
