<FIRST>r a PM-ReportCard-Mississippi     05-04 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Report Card-Mississippi,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Officials: Report Card Has Good News, Bad News For Mississippi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Suggested for side-by-side display with PM-Report Card-Minnesota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State education officials said there was
good news and bad news in a national report that ranked Mississippi
at or near the bottom in college entrance test scores and
graduation rates.
   ``The good news is we continue to make progress. The bad news is
that progress comes slowly and even though we're beginning to pass
states by, we continue to rank down near the bottom,'' said state
Superintendent of Education Richard Boyd.
   The U.S. Education Department's ``State Education Performance
Chart'' released Wednesday showed Mississippi had made some gains,
but fared poorly compared to the rest of the nation.
   Mississippi ranked last among the 28 states where the American
College Testing Program, or ACT, is the predominant college
entrance examination.
   But state Department of Education spokesman Andy Mullins said
the average Mississippi ACT score was up 0.7 point to 16.2 in 1988
over 1987. The test is scored on a scale of 1 to 36. Nationwide,
the average score was up 0.1 point to 18.8, and 11 states showed a
decline in scores.
   ``There's a good news scenario unfolding which shows that
Mississippi is one of five states showing the greatest movement in
ACT scores over the period 1982 through 1988,'' said Olon Ray,
education assistant to Gov. Ray Mabus.
   Ray said it was ``interesting and also significant that (the
improvement in Mississippi) parallels the life of the education
reform movement in the state.''
   The Legislature in 1982 followed the urging of then-Gov. William
Winter and apporved the Education Reform Act, which made sweeping
changes in Mississippi's education system. Mabus has promised to
propose an ``Education Reform II'' package this year.
   But state Rep. Jim Simpson, chairman of the House Education
Committee, said the new report ``points up that education reform is
not something you enact and look next year to see if the problem is
gone.
   ``We are not through with education,'' said Simpson. ``I'm
afraid people want an overnight cure.''
   Mississippi ranked 43rd in the amount spent per student as a
percentage of the state's per capita income. Mississippi school
districts spent an average $2,350 per student in 1987, about 22.8
percent of the state's per capita income of $10,292.
   The report also ranked the state 44th in 1987 in the number of
students who enter first grade and eventually receive high school
diplomas. The state's graduation rate was 64.8 percent.
   The state was in 41st place in 1988 in the teacher-student
ratio, with 18.8 pupils for every teacher. The national average was
17.6.
   ``We're encouraged by the fact that we're doing much better in
some very important areas,'' Ray said. ``We also understand that in
order to be competitive, we're going to have to do much better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
