<FIRST>r a PM-ReportCard-Minnesota     05-04 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Report Card-Minnesota,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesota Gets High Marks In High School Graduation, ACT Scores</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Suggested for side-by-side display with PM-Report Card-Mississippi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAM SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Innovative programs, school evaluations and
committed teachers, lawmakers and parents have helped Minnesota
lead the nation in the percentage of students graduating from high
school, state officials said.
   ``We're delighted that we continue to hold that ranking,''
Minnesota Education Commissioner Ruth Randall said Wednesday,
noting the state has had the No. 1 high school graduation rate
since 1982 in the U.S. Education Department's ``State Education
Performance Chart.''
   Minnesota students also tied for third with Montana for highest
American College Testing Program (ACT) scores among the 28 states
that rely upon that test as a benchmark for college preparedness,
with an average score of 19.9 out of 36. The national mean for 1988
was 18.8.
   Randall said teachers, students and lawmakers deserved credit
for the state's 90.6 percent graduation rate. In particular, she
cited a program passed by state legislators in 1987 that kept 2,500
pregnant minors and mothers in high school by offering them
transportation, day care and counseling.
   ``We do care about our schools in Minnesota. There's that
climate here,'' she said.
   ``It's Minnesota's culture. The neat part about Minnesota is
that there's always been a emphasis on learning, exploring,
discovering,'' Senate Education Committee Chairman James Pehler
said.
   He attributed part of the success to annual performance
evaluations of schools conducted with community participation and
the creation of area learning centers or alternative high schools
for students likely to drop out.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich, who likes to refer to himself as the
``education governor,'' said he could not comment on the report
until he reads it.
   Perpich has led the fight for two major education innovations
that have attracted national attention.
   A post-secondary enrollment options program allows Minnesota
high school juniors and seniors to take college courses. And an
open enrollment program allows students to attend the public school
of their choice.
   The open enrollment program has been widely hailed by President
Bush as a model for choice in education.
   Judy Schaubach, secretary-treasurer of the Minnesota Education
Association, said the state's teachers have played a major part in
Minnesota's high rankings.
   ``It shows that the programs we do offer are quality programs,''
she said. ``The teachers aren't just keeping the students in the
classrooms. They're doing something constructive with them.''
   Minnesota pays its teachers an average $29,900 salary, 11th
highest in the nation, according to the U.S. Education Department.
That compares with a national average of $28,000.
   In 1987, the state ranked 17th with $4,180 spent per student.
The national average was $3,977 that year.
   Minnesota had 17.1 students for every teacher in 1988, giving it
a 24th place ranking nationally. The national average is 17.6
students to each teacher.
</TEXT>
