<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Ochab     05-04 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Ochab,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Communist Party Leader Edward Ochab Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Ochab, a prominent Communist
official over three decades who briefly served as party first
secretary during the 1956 post-Stalinist thaw, has died, the
government reported. He was 82.
   The official PAP news agency said Ochab had died Monday.
   Ochab joined the prewar Polish Communist Party in 1929.
   He helped defend Warsaw after the Nazis attacked in 1939 and
later escaped to the Soviet Union, where he helped organize the
Union of Polish Patriots that was a precursor of the
Moscow-installed postwar communist government.
   After Moscow-sponsored communists won out in a postwar power
struggle with communists who spent the war fighting inside Poland,
Ochab succeeded to a number of prominent party and government posts.
   When party leader Boleslaw Bierut died during a visit to Moscow
in March 1956, Ochab briefly served as party leader. But labor
turmoil in June of that year and popular resentment of Soviet
influences led him to relinquish leadership in October 1956 to
Wladyslaw Gomulka.
   Gomulka represented the ``national communist'' wing of the party
that had been suppressed by the Moscow faction after the war.
   Ochab remained a party secretary and served as president of the
Council of State from 1964 until 1968, when he quit all his posts.
   In a 1981 interview, he said he had resigned to protest the
``anti-Zionist'' party purge in 1968 directed against Jews and
intellectuals.
</TEXT>
