<FIRST>r p PM-TexasMayorals     05-04 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Mayorals,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Antonio, Dallas, El Paso To Choose Mayors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who preceded Henry Cisneros as
mayor of the nation's ninth-largest city is looking to replace him
come Saturday, when voters in El Paso and Dallas also go to the
polls to elect mayors.
   Former San Antonio Mayor Lila Cockrell is vying to succeed
Cisneros, the popular 41-year-old Hispanic mayor who will enter an
asset management partnership after 14 years of public service,
including eight as mayor.
   Dallas Mayor Annette Strauss, whose city has been rocked by
police shootings, has lost some minority endorsements she received
in her initial race two years ago. This time, though, the business
community is supporting her re-election bid.
   In El Paso, six candidates vying to replace Mayor Jonathan
Rogers _ who by law cannot seek a fifth, two-year term _ say they
want to reduce crime and promote economic development in the border
town.
   But the seven-candidate San Antonio mayor's race seems to be
drawing a great deal of attention around the state because of
Cisneros' departure.
   The 67-year-old Ms. Cockrell, who was mayor from 1975 to 1981,
has said she laid some of the groundwork for Cisneros and now wants
to concentrate on his economic development efforts.
   ``I'm not a spectacular mayor like Henry is, but I have
confidence in myself that I will be a good mayor and that I will
keep the city moving,'' said Ms. Cockrell, who has spent about
$137,000 in her campaign.
   Beset by a troubled marriage and his son's ill health, Cisneros
decided last year against a fifth term.
   He reconsidered his mayoral re-election decision in January
after voters overwhelmingly approved a public transportation tax to
pay for construction of a domed stadium that he supported. But he
decided against running after Ms. Cockrell's supporters said they
would stay behind her.
   The city charter gives the mayor and city council members equal
stature, but because of his personality and leadership skill,
Cisneros turned it into a powerful position as he promoted the city
and rose to national prominence.
   San Antonio, unlike other major Texas cities, was the only
metropolitan area that experienced job growth during the last five
years, although many of those jobs were low-paying, analysts said.
   Also running for mayor here is Carl Mauthe, a 52-year-old
insurance executive who says he offers voters strong management
experience and a choice to a ``recycled mayor.''
   ``I have no baggage. I have no obligations to any group and I'm
not going to bring stale ideas about city government with me and
I'm not going to rubber-stamp everything,'' said Mauthe, who has
raised less than $20,000.
   In Dallas, Mrs. Strauss lost the support of some minority
groups, who have complained of strained relations with city
government and now support one of her three opponents, criminal
defense attorney Peter Lesser.
   Mrs. Strauss, 65, has raised $300,000, compared with the $16,000
raised by Lesser, who discounts the clout of contributions.
   ``Money is not going to win this election. A poor person's vote
counts the same as a millionare's vote,'' said the 41-year-old
Lesser.
   But a poll taken last week by The Dallas Morning News found Mrs.
Strauss was favored by 53 percent of those surveyed in the nation's
eighth-largest city. Lesser was next with 6 percent. Thirty-seven
percent were undecided.
   Two years ago, Mrs. Strauss said promoting economic development
and expanding the police force were her priorities. While the
economy seemed to stabilize during her tenure, the crime rate
escalated, police-related shootings increased and police morale
plummeted.
   ``Dallas has been through some tough times,'' Mrs. Strauss said
recently. ``But we've stood tall and made progress. We are
recapturing the momentum of the '60s, '70s and early '80s and I
want to finish the job I started.''
   The Dallas mayor's post, like the San Antonio job, is mostly
ceremonial. Both pay $50 per weekly council meeting.
   In El Paso, the mayor has more power because there's no city
manager.
   The race has attracted six candidates, including City Council
members Suzie Azar and Ed Elsey and state Rep. Paul Moreno, all
Democrats in the non-partisan election.
   Observers believe Moreno, the only Hispanic running in a city
with a population that's 63 percent Hispanic, will make it to the
May 27 runoff with either Elsey or Ms. Azar. Ms. Azar won
endorsements from both daily newspapers.
   ``El Paso has to get away from the image of the sleepy Mexican
town with low wages,'' said Moreno, who wants to attract state and
federal grants to help small businesses. ``We can't continue to
draw business here by saying they can pay the minimum wage.''
   Ms. Azar, who favors tax abatements, is optimistic the city can
attract more high-tech businesses.
   Elsey, whose economic development plan is similar to Ms. Azar's,
points to two new plants as signs that the city is attracting new
businesses.
</TEXT>
