<FIRST>r a PM-DeerHunterTrial     05-04 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deer Hunter Trial,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Murder Trial Brings Guilty Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deer hunter on trial for the third time
in the shooting death of a wildlife officer during a struggle in
the woods was convicted of a lesser charge of third-degree murder.
   Steve Strange, 26, of Mossy Head, had been charged with
first-degree murder, which could have brought the death penalty or
life behind bars.
   But the jury deliberated six hours Wednesday before returning
the conviction on third-degree murder, which is a death that
results from violently resisting arrest. Strange faces three to 30
years in prison. Sentencing was scheduled for today.
   ``Our judicial system stinks,'' said Ray Barnes, father of the
victim, Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission officer Ray
Lynn Barnes. Strange shot Barnes with officer's own revolver during
a nighttime struggle Nov. 21, 1987.
   The first jury's guilty verdict in Walton County, where the
shooting took place, was thrown out last September because a judge
allowed the panel to use a dictionary while deliberating.
   The case was moved here because of extensive publicity, but a
mistrial was declared in February after a second jury deadlocked.
   Strange did not react when the jury's verdict was read.
   The jury also found Strange guilty of grand theft in taking the
officer's service revolver, possession of firearm during commission
of a felony and hunting without a license.
   In his closing argument, Assistant State Attorney Drew Pinkerton
quoted testimony by Strange's companion, Kenneth Collars, who said
he was hunting near the spot where the defendant struggled with the
state Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission officer but didn't see
it.
   Collars testified Tuesday that Strange told him he had
``murdered a man.''
   ``He confessed at that time to one of the highest courts in the
world, his own conscience,'' Pinkerton told the jury.
   The defense contended Strange was only trying to defend himself
after the officer grabbed his shotgun to take it away.
   The prosecution said Barnes was trying to arrest Strange for
hunting without a license. The officer initially suffered a
non-fatal leg wound when Strange's shotgun barrel exploded, the
muzzle blocked by dirt. He subsequently was shot in the chest and
head with his service revolver.
   Loveless contended Strange didn't realize Barnes was a wildlife
officer because he was wearing a camouflage jacket that hid his
uniform shirt.
   Unlike the first two trials, Strange did not testify. A tape
recording of his police interrogation was played for the jury.
   He contended Barnes' gun went off as they struggled. Strange
also left the impression that he realized Barnes was an officer
because of the broad stripes on his trousers.
</TEXT>
