<DOCNO> AP890504-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Press 2ndLd-Writethru a0441 05-04 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Press, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0441,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tabloid To Be `First Independent Daily Between Elbe and Pacific'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with paper appearing Monday at the earliest, SUB 3rd
graf, `The paper ... a staff.' Picks up 4th, `Deputy editor ...' ^An AP
Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in more than 40 years
Poles are going to be able to pick up a daily newspaper not
controlled by the government, and the editors promise to separate
fact from opinion.
   There even will be sports in the Gazeta Wyborcza tabloid, to be
published by the country's Solidarity-led opposition.
   The paper, whose name means ``the election newspaper,'' hopes to
make its debut Monday after a frantic search for offices and the
quick assembly of a staff.
   Deputy editor Ernest Skalski describes it as ``the first
independent daily between the Elbe and the Pacific.''
   Although the paper will have a government censor in the office,
editors say they'll be able to maintain an independent voice.
   Compared to the gray, propaganda-laden dailies put out by the
Communist Party, the government and various official organizations,
Gazeta Wyborcza intends to be lively with short articles and more
foreign news.
   ``Polish dailies are in my opinion very bad. ... They make even
good news look so boring,'' said Helena Luczywo, a deputy editor
who for seven years put out the leading underground weekly,
Tygodnik Mazowsze. ``Even if there is something interesting they
tend to put in all kinds of official visits, statements and
speeches, and three-quarters of the paper is this.''
   ``We really hope to put the interesting and hot news where it
can be seen by everyone. Besides, I think the selection of news is
going to be totally different,'' she said.
   The eight-page newspaper will start out by reporting on the June
parliamentary elections, and continue as a daily with an opposition
editorial viewpoint.
   But it plans to make a clear distinction between straight
information and editorializing, Ms. Luczywo said.
   Although Poland has had a vibrant underground press for more
than a decade, editions were put out at best only weekly and with
limited press runs of 20,000 to 30,000 copies.
   Under an agreement reached in April between the government and
Solidarity, the opposition will be allowed to publish a
500,000-circulation daily. The newspaper will be printed on state
presses and sold in state-owned kiosks.
   Access to the mass media was one of the opposition's conditions
for joining in the agreement, which calls for the opposition to
participate in the parliament elections. It also legalized
Solidarity, the independent trade union movement, after a
seven-year ban.
   ``Our paper is not the Solidarity trade union's paper but it
aspires to be the paper of the whole opposition,'' said Skalski.
   Skalski said the last time Poland had a daily newspaper
independent of Communist Party control was before the party
consolidated power in 1947.
   The editor-in-chief is to be Adam Michnik, an essayist and
historian who is one of the leading theoreticians of the
opposition. He was assigned the task by Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa.
   The staff will number about 50 and include people from the now
liquidated Tygodnik Mazowsze, which means weekly of the Mazowsze
region that includes Warsaw. Also on the staff are students and
recent graduates of Warsaw University's journalism school.
   Many of the country's best-known independent journalists also
will contribute articles from time to time, said Ms. Luczywo.
   The newspaper is also to have a section that will contain news
about a faction of the opposition that is against compromise with
the authorities _ in other words, the political rivals of Walesa
and the paper's editors.
   Ms. Luczywo said the section ``most likely to be censored'' will
contain foreign news, which will concentrate on changes in the East
bloc.
   Preparations for publishing began the day Solidarity and the
government signed their agreement.
   After several false starts, the paper finally received offices
from authorities Tuesday in a vacant children's nursery in southern
Warsaw.
   At midweek, it was still waiting for phone and telex
connections, Ms. Luczywo said.
   Technically, the paper is the property of a company set up with
three shareholders: Warsaw Solidarity leader Zbigniew Bujak,
filmmaker Andrzej Wajda and Aleksander Paszysnski, founder of the
pro-private enterprise Economic Society. Initial financing is
coming from a bank loan and the newspaper hopes later to accept
advertising.
   For Ms. Luczywo, leaving the underground press for Gazeta
Wyborcza has meant the freedom to use the telephone instead of
couriers.
   But she is having trouble picturing a censor at her elbow while
she edits.
   ``I've never seen a censor in my life,'' she said, laughing at
the thought. ``I've been working for the uncensored press since
1977, for 12 years. So now I'm kind of losing my virginity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
