<HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Plains, Cold In North Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain showers and scattered thunderstorms moved today over parts
of 11 states in the central part of the nation, while temperatures
dipped to near freezing overnight in North Carolina.
   Rain fell this morning over northern Texas, northwest Louisiana,
southwest Arkansas, Oklahoma, eastern and southern Kansas, eastern
Nebraska, South Dakota, eastern North Dakota, southwest Iowa, the
northwest corner of Missouri, and northern Alabama.
   Republic, Kan., had three-quarter-inch diameter hail, while
Enid, Okla., recorded more than a half inch of rain in the six
hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT.
   Mount Washington in New Hampshire had two inches of snow in the
same six hours.
   Clear skies dropped temperatures across North Carolina this
morning. A frost warning was posted over the state's northern
mountains.
   The high temperature for the nation Wednesday was 105 degrees at
Laughlin, Nev.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
over the Mississippi, Tennessee and Ohio valleys, the Gulf of
Mexico states and the eastern part of the southern Plains;
thunderstorms possibly becoming severe over parts of Oklahoma,
northern Texas, Arkansas, Louisiana, Mississippi, Tennessee and
Alabama; and widely scattered showers from eastern Kansas to
portions of the Dakotas and over the northern and central Rockies.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s across much of the
nation; in the 50s along parts of the Canadian border from Montana
to Wisconsin and over northern Maine; in the 80s over Florida,
along the Gulf Coast, over much of Texas and New Mexico, and from
central California across western Oregon to south-central
Washington; in the 90s along the Rio Grande Valley of Texas; and in
the 90s to near 105 in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 28
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 81 degrees at Blythe, Calif., and
El Paso, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 59 rain; Boston 48 fair; Buffalo 43 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 56 fair; Cincinnati 43 fair; Cleveland 42 fair;
Detroit 43 fair; Miami 77 cloudy; New York 49 fair; Philadelphia 45
fair; Pittsburgh 38 fair; Portland, Maine, 46 partly cloudy;
Washington 46 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 41 foggy; Chicago 49 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
66 thunderstorms; Denver 39 fair; Des Moines 53 cloudy;
Indianapolis 45 fair; Kansas City 56 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul 51
partly cloudy; Nashville 50 fair; New Orleans 70 partly cloudy; St.
Louis 55 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 60 fair; Anchorage 48 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 76 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 60 foggy; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt
Lake City 52 rain; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 60 fair;
Seattle 52 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 partly cloudy; Toronto 39 fair.
