<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-04 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shells, Rockets Fired Despite Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howitzer shells and rockets fired from
Syrian-policed west Beirut crashed along the coast of a Christian
area north of the city today despite a cease-fire brokered by the
Arab League.
   A police spokesman said the artillery fire hit the beach of the
310-square-mile Christian enclave at the rate of four per hour. No
casualties were reported.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing rules,
said the barrage was ``obviously an attempt to maintain the
blockade'' of Christian ports.
   Gunners of Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000-strong Christian army units
did not return fire, the spokesman said.
   Aoun, also head of the Christian cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, on Wednesday accepted a truce that involves lifting the
blockades he imposed on illegal ports run by Moslem militias, said
Arab League envoys Lakhdar Ibrahimi of Algeria and Abdel-Aziz
Al-Jassem of Syria.
   They said Aoun's Sunni Moslem rival and Cabinet leader Salim
Hoss also agreed to the cease-fire.
   The Christian-run Voice of Lebanon radio station quoted Jassem
as saying today the agreement was ``not a magic stick that can
block the barrel of each cannon to silence it.''
   ``We will ask leaders in west Beirut why the cease-fire is not
being honored,'' Jassem was quoted as saying.
   The Arab envoys spent the night at a hotel in the Christian
mountain resort of Brummana, northeast of Beirut. They crossed
Beirut's dividing Green Line this morning for meetings with Moslem
leaders in the city's western sector.
   On Wednesday, the ferry service between the Christian enclave
and Cyprus resumed, with the Baroness M taking on about 400
passengers. The service had been suspended while the port of
Jounieh north of Beirut was shelled.
   The captain of the Cypriot-flagged ferry remained 15 miles
offshore because he was skeptical about guarantees the vessel would
not be shelled, and small boats shuttled passengers to the ferry.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt, Syria's main ally in the
confrontation with Aoun, on Wednesday demanded measures to block
alleged weapon supplies from Iraq to Aoun through the Christian
ports.
   ``There is no justification for any shot to be fired in Lebanon
as of now,'' Ibrahimi said Wednesday after meeting separately with
Aoun and Hoss.
   ``I can say the cease-fire has taken effect today after the
settlement of ports dispute. The observer force will begin arriving
soon,'' he said without elaborating.
   The truce, announced Friday after an emergency meeting of Arab
foreign ministers in Tunisia, calls for a group of military
observers from Arab nations to monitor implementation of the
cease-fire.
   Aoun had welcomed the decision, saying the observers would
``watch the Syrians here.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces as well as in west and south
Beirut under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab league.
   The current round of violence broke out on March 8, two days
after Aoun ordered a blockade of the ports run by Syria's two main
allies _ Jumblatt's militia and Amal, led by Shiite Moslem leader
Nabih Berri.
   Aoun's army blockaded two of Jumblatt's ports and Druse and
Syrian gunners _ who outnumber Christian forces by 3-1 _ retaliated
by firing at Christian ports then besieged the Christian enclave.
   The Amal militia has not joined in.
</TEXT>
