<FIRST>r a PM-BirthControlSentence     05-04 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Birth Control Sentence,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Sentenced To Lifetime Birth Control Has Fourth Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old woman whose sentence on child abuse
charges had included an order for lifetime birth control recently
gave birth to her fourth child, officials said.
   Debra Ann Forster had pleaded guilty April 4, 1988, to two
counts of attempted child abuse for leaving her two sons, then 7
months and 18 months old, in her sweltering suburban Mesa apartment
unattended for three days in May 1987. When her estranged husband
and father of the children found them, they were severely
dehydrated and one was near death, according to court testimony.
The boys recovered.
   The judge who sentenced Ms. Forster in May 1988 lifted the birth
control condition of the probation sentence in August as
unenforceable when she learned Ms. Forster was pregnant.
   The probation term ordered by Judge Lindsay Ellis of Maricopa
County Superior Court also barred Ms. Forster from caring for any
child.
   Ms. Forster's probation officer, Lori Scott, confirmed Wednesday
that Ms. Forster gave birth last week, but she would not disclose
the date or location.
   ``It's a very delicate situation,'' the probation officer said,
adding that the judge ordered her not to release any details on the
case.
   A daughter born in March 1988, while Ms. Forster was in jail
awaiting resolution of her case, was put up for adoption. The two
boys were put in the state's custody.
   Ms. Ellis said Wednesday that the infant's fate is likely to be
``decided largely by Child Protective Services and perhaps
ultimately by Juvenile Court.''
   The judge would not say who is caring for the infant, but said
she has been assured it is not Ms. Forster.
   She declined to discuss the case further.
   Ms. Forster's stepfather, Joseph Lantier of Patterson, La., said
Wednesday he spoke with his stepdaughter on Tuesday and that she
gave birth to a healthy girl. He would not say what her intentions
were regarding the baby.
   ``It's a controversial case, and I'm not going to say anything
to jeopardize her,'' said Lantier.
   Lantier cared for Ms. Forster from age 10 to 15 in Louisiana.
Ms. Forster, a seventh-grade dropout, married at 15 and had her
first child at that age.
   In October, Ms. Ellis denied Ms. Forster permission to travel to
New York to appear on Phil Donahue's television show. The probation
order prohibited Ms. Forster from leaving Arizona without court
permission, and the judge said in October that allowing Ms. Forster
to appear on the show ``would be like throwing her into the mouths
of sharks.''
   Ms. Forster has reconciled with her husband and is attempting to
complete her high school education, Scott said.
</TEXT>
