<FIRST>r a PM-WilliamsFuneral     05-04 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Williams Funeral,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roy Williams Eulogized as Supporter of the Working Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Teamsters President Roy Lee
Williams was remembered as an aggressive leader who cared for the
disadvantaged and fought for the cause of the workingman.
   ``He was strong,'' said Danny Johnson, who now holds the
positions Williams occupied for nearly 30 years as president of
Teamsters Local 41 and Joint Council 56. ``He was aggressive. He
was a fighter who believed in the workingman's cause. He was tough
as nails at the negotiating table.''
   About 150 people attended Wednesday's memorial service for
Williams, who served as the leader of the Teamsters for three
years. Williams, 74, died Friday at his farm home about 70 miles
southeast of Kansas City. He had been ill with emphysema and an
enlarged heart.
   Williams also had a way of caring for the disadvantaged that has
long been overlooked, Johnson said in a brief eulogy.
   Williams' problems received news coverage, but Johnson said ``it
galls me sometimes that the news media doesn't recognize the good
things he did, such as his support for retarded children and the
Muscular Dystrophy foundation.''
   Williams was convicted in 1982 of conspiring to bribe then-Sen.
Howard Cannon in Nevada to get Cannon to scuttle a trucking
deregulation bill.
   In court testimony, Williams admitted that during his reign at
Local 41, he had been controlled by Nick Civella, the late Kansas
City crime leader. Williams also predicted that organized crime
would shadow the union nationally for a ``long time after I'm
gone.''
   Williams served three years in federal prison, and was released
last September. Friends and associates who visted him at his
Leeton, Mo., farm, said Williams maintained his innocence to the
end.
   Williams began as a trucker in 1935, hauling livestock to
Chicago. Twice decorated for bravery in World War II, he returned
to the Midwest and took control of a troubled Teamsters local in
Wichita.
   With the support of Teamsters leader Jimmy Hoffa, Williams in
1952 took over Local 41, and in 1954 was elected president of the
local and Joint Council 56, a coalition of area Teamsters locals.
He held those positions until 1981, when he was elected
international vice president. Later that year, he succeeded Frank
Fitzsimmons as Teamsters general president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
