<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unions 1stLd-Writethru   05-04 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unions, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0497,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leader Says Law Would Allow Right to Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE with passage of law considered likely.
Picks up 6th pvs, `Giving unions ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor unions will gain the right to strike in new
legislation designed to free them from decades of meek subservience
to the Communist Party and government, a leading Soviet union
official said.
   Unions ``must have the right to stop work at enterprises, in
organizations and institutions as a means of pressure on the
administration for speeding up the resolution of labor disputes,''
Stepan A. Shalaev told the labor newspaper Trud in an interview
published Wednesday.
   But Shalaev made clear that the Central Council of Trade Unions
that he chairs does not expect strikes to become as common as they
are elsewhere.
   ``The decision to stop work at an enterprise _ this is an
extreme measure to be taken only in extreme circumstances,'' he
said.
   Shalaev said the draft law, published Saturday, would be
discussed by unions for three months. It must eventually be
approved by the new Supreme Soviet Parliament, which is considered
likely.
   Giving unions a limited right to strike appeared to be an effort
to prevent labor unrest from taking on the dimension that led to
the formation of the Solidarity free trade union movement in Poland.
   Solidarity was crushed in a 1981 military crackdown and not
reinstated until last month.
   Under current Soviet law, unions are not permitted to strike.
Instead, they are quiet partners with management and the ruling
Communist Party. Communist ideology considers strikes a Western
phenomenon stemming from worker exploitation.
   Soviet unions have assumed a variety of functions such as
building and organizing housing for members or running vacation
facilities for members. They traditionally have done nothing to
advance wage demands and work conditions.
   Shalaev said unions would be free of government interference
under the draft law and workers protected from losing their jobs as
a result of union activity. The law also ensures that local union
officials are independent of the administration of the factory or
office where they work, he said.
   In an article Monday, the international May Day holiday, an
economist wrote in the newspaper Socialist Industry that the
country's union system has done nothing to help workers.
   Alexander Auzan wrote that unions are subservient to the
government and are ``concerned not with defending the interests of
the workers but only with maintaining peace and quiet and an
imitation of `mass support.'''
   However, that has not prevented labor unrest from spreading in
certain industries as President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic
reforms take hold and greater openness encourages Soviets to speak
out on issues that affect them.
   In March, more than 100 coal miners in the Ural Mountains city
of Vorkuta struck to protest increased work orders, demand
replacement of the facility's director and chief economist and
changes in the salary system.
   In April, miners stayed underground in the Siberian city of
Norilsk to demand a 30 percent wage increase.
   In both cases, the strikes drew the attention of the government
ministers in Moscow, who promised to meet some of the strikers'
demands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FatalFire     05-04 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fatal Fire,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in Fire that Killed Nine Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man accused of killing nine
people by setting the most deadly residential fire in Peoria
history has pleaded innocent to nine counts of first-degree murder
and two counts of arson.
   James Pickens entered the plea in a brief appearance Wednesday
before Peoria County Circuit Judge Richard Eagleton. A trial was
scheduled for June 26.
   Pickens, 34, was named in nine murder indictments and two
indictments of aggravated arson Tuesday by a Peoria County grand
jury.
   State's Attorney Kevin Lyons said he is considering seeking the
death penalty if Pickens is convicted.
   According to police, Pickens, who has no permanent address, was
at a Peoria house on April 11 when residents asked him to leave so
they could go to bed. Authorities say he has confessed to returning
later and setting a roll-away bed afire in a vacant ground-floor
apartment while 12 people slept on the second floor.
   Seven children and two adults were killed and three others were
injured. Those who died ranged in age from two months to 27 years.
Authorities said they died of smoke inhalation.
   Pickens is being held in the Peoria County Jail on $2 million
bond.
</TEXT>
