<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Marcos Rallies in the Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with details on protests in Manila
and Marcos' hometown. Pickup 5th graf, ``Batac Mayor...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Ferdinand Marcos
supporters staged a rally in Manila today to mark one year since
the death of his still-unburied mother and to demand the ousted
president be allowed to return.
   Police in San Juan, a Manila suburb, said 2,000 pro-Marcos
protesters marched to the former president's former home where a
Mass was celebrated in honor of his mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos,
who died last year at 95.
   The protesters then held a rally at a downtown square where they
made speeches extolling Marcos and demanding his return from exile.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos died in a Manila military hospital May 4,
1988, but her family has refused to bury her until President
Corazon Aquino allows Marcos to return from his Hawaiian exile to
preside over the funeral.
   Officials in Marcos' hometown, Batac, 250 miles north of Manila,
declared today as a ``day of mourning.'' Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' body
has been lying in an open casket in the Marcos ancestral home,
which has been turned into a museum.
   About 400 people packed the living room of the two-story home to
listen to sermons by local priests reminiscing about Marcos'
20-year rule. At least three Masses were said, one lasting four
hours. A Protestant service was also held.
   The Rev. Domingo Nebres said he visited Marcos last week in
Honolulu. Marcos, hospitalized since last January for respiratory
and heart ailments, was optimistic that he would be able to return
to the Philippines, Nebres said.
   ``Just wait for me. I will definitely come home. While there is
life, there is hope,'' Nebres quoted Marcos as telling him.
   Batac Mayor Jesus Nalupta said no special ceremonies were
scheduled apart from Roman Catholic Masses, which have been said
nearly every day since Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' body was brought from
Manila last year.
   Private radio station DZXL in Manila broadcast a taped message
from Marcos' wife, Imelda, saying her mother-in-law's soul is still
on earth ``to carry out God's will to bring home her son.''
   Mrs. Marcos said she hopes she will soon be allowed to return.
She spoke in Tagalog with the theme music from a soap opera playing
in the background.
   Mrs. Marcos said she receives calls from employees at the
presidential palace who say they often see Mrs. Edralin-Marcos'
ghost wandering through the grounds ``searching for her son whom
she cannot find by her side.''
   Mrs. Aquino was swept to power in a civilian-military uprising
that ousted Marcos in February 1986. She has survived several coup
attempts since then and says his return would jeopardize the
national security.
</TEXT>
