<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US Bases,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Senator Says Aquino Supports U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition politician claimed
today the government has secretly agreed to allow six U.S. military
bases to remain open in the Philippines after their leases expire
in 1991.
   President Corazon Aquino, faced with mounting opposition to U.S.
military presence, has refused to say whether she supports
extending the 1947 treaty.
   But Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile called Mrs. Aquino's avowed policy to
keep her options open a ``face-saving act.''
   ``There is no open option,'' Enrile said in an interview with
DZXL radio. ``There is already an extension of the bases agreement.
What they are discussing now is how much'' the United States will
pay.
   Last year, the United States agreed to pay the Philippines $962
million in aid to extend the treaty for two years.
   In an interview today, Mrs. Aquino said her government will
decide by September 1990 on whether to maintain the Clark Air Base,
Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller facilities in the
Philippines. She said talks on the issue with U.S. officials will
begin by year's end.
   Resentment has spread toward the 40,000 U.S. soldiers and their
dependents in the country. The Communist National Democratic Front
rebel army has offered to declare a unilateral cease-fire in its
20-year-old rebellion against the government if Mrs. Aquino
promises to close the bases.
