<SECOND>PM-UMW-Pittston,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>21 Striking Miners Arrested in Second Week of Civil Disobedience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCLURE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police arrested 21 striking miners
today for blocking the entrance to a mine run by the Pittston Coal
Group Inc.
   Members of the United Mine Workers union were continuing civil
disobedience tactics to keep pressure on the mining company as
mediated talks get started.
   The arrested miners were escorted into a state-owned bus and
taken to the Dickenson County jail. Strike organizers said they
expected the miners, who worked at McClure, to remain in jail
overnight.
   Students from nearby Ervington High School planned to
demonstrate at the jail tonight, said strike coordinator Marty
Hudson.
   UMW District President Jackie Stump told the miners as they were
being put on the bus, ``Remember now, go peaceably; no violence.''
   The strike, which began April 5, affects about 1,500 miners in
Virginia and West Virginia. Two hundred other union miners working
at Pittston operations in Kentucky have not yet left their jobs.
   Last week, more than 1,000 demonstrators were arrested by state
police outside Pittston operations in southwest Virginia. For the
most part, the demonstrations were non-violent and those arrested
were charged with misdemeanor trespassing. On Tuesday, several
miners and two contract drivers for the company were injured in a
rock-throwing melee that ended with a vehicle striking several
demonstrators.
   Meantime, representatives of the UMW and Pittston said they were
cautiously optimistic that federal mediation will break the
20-month deadlock in contract negotiations.
   ``I think it's a positive move in the right direction,''
Pittston President Michael Odom said Wednesday.
   A mediator with the U.S. Labor Department's Mediation and
Conciliation Service discussed the ground rules and agenda with
union and company officials Wednesday. The sides, however, have not
agreed on a date for the start of mediation or who the principal
negotiators will be.
