<FIRST>r i PM-NIreland-Bomb 2ndLd-Writethru a0515 05-04 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NIreland-Bomb, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0515,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed In Separate Bombings In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with IRA claiming responsibility
for roadside attack. Pickup 5th pvs, ``The prison...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb exploded near a
road today, killing one soldier and injuring two civilians, police
said. In a second attack, a prison nurse died when a bomb exploded
under his car.
   The roadside bomb exploded as soldiers passed by on a foot
patrol in the village of Silverbridge, near the South Armagh border
of the province, a local police spokesman said on condition of
anonymity. Three soldiers in the patrol were in shock after the
bombing, the spokesman said.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility. The IRA said
in a statement that the bombing was intented to coincide with the
celebration today of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's 10th
anniversary in power.
   ``We remind the British people on this, the 10th anniversary of
Mrs. Thatcher's government, that the Irish question remains
unresolved and cannot be resolved by military policies,'' said the
statement.
   ``If Mrs. Thatcher continues to pursue military goals, the IRA
will have no alternative but to continue to bring the British
occupation of Ireland to the attention of the British public.''
   The IRA is fighting to oust the British from the province and
often targets British security forces.
   The prison nurse, who was not identified, was married and had
two children, said a spokesman in Belfast for the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, the province police force.
   He had driven a short way from his home near Loughgall, County
Armagh, en route to his job at Maze Prison in Belfast, said the
spokesman, who was not identified in keeping with British custom.
   He said no one claimed responsibility in the bombing.
   On Wednesday night, a third bomb exploded at an army observation
post on the South Armagh border, injuring three people, police said.
   Police said one civilian was treated for minor injuries and two
were treated for shock, but there were no security force casualties
from the bomb, which was believed to have been planted by the IRA.
   A man was arrested close to the scene moments after a tractor
parked in a field close to the scene exploded, said police.
   In Moy, in County Tyrone, army experts were searching for a
1,000-pound bomb the IRA claimed it had planted near Charlmount
Bridge.
</TEXT>
