<HEAD>Man Questioned on Prostitute Assaults</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 12th graf, bgng `She also said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man is being investigated in the
alleged assaults of as many as 17 prostitutes in an area where nine
women have been found dead along the highways since last summer, a
court document says.
   State police filed an affidavit in New Bedford District Court
last month to obtain a warrant to search the man's house and truck.
The affidavit said police had interviewed 12 women, described as
prostitutes, who identified the man from photographs. Five other
women also were believed to have been assaulted.
   Three of the women said the man choked them, and two said they
were choked into unconsciousness, according to the affidavit
reported Wednesday by WJAR-TV in Providence, R.I., and today by the
Boston Herald and The Boston Globe.
   One woman said she saw a cord or rope in the man's vehicle and
thought the man was going to choke her with it, according to the
affidavit.
   The bodies of nine women have been found since July along
highways in the New Bedford area. Three were strangled, according
to death certificates. The cause of death was not determined for
the other six women.
   Authorities believe the women were killed by the same person or
persons, and all nine had ties to the drug community in New
Bedford. Some had turned to prostitution.
   Two New Bedford women missing since last summer are also feared
to be victims.
   The 26-year-old Freetown man whose home and truck were searched
April 19, one day after the affidavit was filed for the search
warrant, has not been charged in either the deaths or the assaults.
   State police said the search found bloodstains on the dashboard
and seat in the truck and that hair, fibers, clothes and four
knives were seized, the papers and television station reported.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina has refused to
identify any suspects in the investigation into the killings.
   But Tuesday, after testifying before the grand jury
investigating the killings, Margaret Medeiros, 22, a self-described
prostitute, told reporters that police had told her the man was a
suspect.
   She also said the man had tried to ``break my neck'' and told
her, ```I'm going to do to you what I did to them other bitches.'''
   The affidavit used to obtain the search warrant reportedly was
based on interviews conducted last month by state troopers and New
Bedford detectives investigating the deaths of the nine women, but
the affidavit did not mention the killings.
   The man whose home and truck were searched has told the Boston
Herald he had nothing to do with the assaults and was being linked
unfairly to the killings.
   ``If it was me, I wouldn't be talking to you right now,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
