<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-Crowds     05-04 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Crowds,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Turn Out For Second Attempt To Launch Atlantis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roads leading to the launch pad where
the shuttle Atlantis waited for its second attempt at liftoff were
relatively empty of spectators today, and officials called it the
lowest turnout of recent years.
   ``There's nobody here,'' said Jerry Eads, assistant chief of
police in Titusville, which is just across the Indian River from
the space center. He estimated 1,000 people were in place five
hours before the scheduled launch of 1:48 p.m. Some of them had
been waiting since Wednesday night.
   Eads said he expected no more than 20,000 or 30,000 in his city
by launch time today, which would be the smallest crowd in recent
years.
   At the Kennedy Space Center itself, 8,000 to 10,000 people were
expected, according to Mitch Varnes, a spokesman for the National
Aeronautics Space Administration.
   Last Friday, when NASA stopped the countdown 31 seconds before
launch, the center was filled to capacity with 15,000 people.
   ``Each day we have a scrub we usually lose 50 percent of our
attendance,'' Varnes said.
   An estimated 250,000 well-wishers turned out for the launch of
Discovery in September, the first shuttle mission since the
Challenger explosion in January 1986.
</TEXT>
