<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     05-04 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Planes Said To Bomb Refugee Camp in Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan warplane bombed a refugee
camp in Pakistan today, killing three Afghans and injuring 16,
officials said.
   The warplane was one of two that flew over the Gambila refugee
camp this morning, 70 miles east of the Afghanistan border,
officials in Pakistan's North West Frontier Province said on
condition of anonymity.
   One plane dropped a bomb that destroyed six houses and left a
crater 20-feet wide, the officials said. Seven of the injured were
in serious condition.
   Pakistan supports the Moslem guerrillas fighting the communist
government in Kabul and shelters more than 3 million refugees of
the 11-year Afghan civil war. Many of the guerrilla leaders are
based in Pakistan.
   Today's incursion by Afghan warplanes was the first reported
since last fall. The Foreign Ministry is expected to lodge a
protest with the Afghan government as it has after previous air
raids.
   On Wednesday, Afghanistan accused Pakistan of helping the
guerrillas prepare new attacks on the Afghan cities of Jalalabad
and Kandahar.
   The Moslem guerrillas have besieged Jalalabad since March 6,
about three weeks after Soviet forces ended nine years of
intervention in the war. Pakistan funnels mainly-U.S. arms to the
guerrillas. Kabul has warned the war may spill over into Pakistan
unless Islamabad stops helping the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
