<FIRST>r a PM-BillboardBacklash     05-04 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Billboard Backlash,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Counseling Billboard Angers Divorced Fathers' Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNDALE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A good-bride, bad-groom billboard
advertising a family counseling service is coming down after an
organization of divorced men called it a slap at males.
   The sign on the roof of a suburban Detroit office building
showed a beaming bride with a demonically transformed groom at her
shoulder.
   ``After marriage, people sometimes change,'' it read, and it
told where to get help for troubled marriages.
   Fathers for Equal Rights, a support group for divorced fathers,
called the portrayal of the groom a sexist smear.
   ``She's a beautiful spring bride, but he looks like Dracula, or
a demon with spiked hair, Friday the 13th eyes, flared nostrils and
bared teeth,'' said executive director Al Lebow.
   ``It's another example of male bashing ... which everyone seems
to accept. They wouldn't dare depict a woman like that,'' Lebow
said.
   He said if the sign weren't removed and replaced with an apology
his group would campaign to curtail contributions to United Way of
America, which supports the Oakland County group that put up the
sign.
   The sign will be removed, said Bill Fry, executive director of
Oakland Family Services. ``The intent of the billboard was to draw
attention to our organization, not to insult men.''
   He said the billboard space was donated, and his group doesn't
have money to post an apology.
</TEXT>
