<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-PrayerDay     05-04 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Prayer Day,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>No One Offers Grace at Bush Prayer Breakfast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush observed National Day of Prayer
with a breakfast with religious leaders at the White House today,
and promptly noticed no one had offered to begin the meal with a
prayer.
   Bush also told the ecumenical gathering, ``I'm sure we would all
agree that we believe in separation of church and state, but not in
the separation of morality or moral values and state.''
   ``While the government must remain neutral towards particular
religions, it must not _ certainly it need not _ remain neutral
towards values that Americans support,'' the president said.
   One of the participants, the Rev. Billy Zeoli, president of
Gospel Films in Grand Rapids, Mich., said, ``I was fascinated by
Mr. Bush when the president noticed that, as we were sitting at
breakfast, no one began with a prayer.''
   Zeoli, who was White House chaplain during the Ford
administration, said Bush ``simply stood up'' and made the
observation, then picked one from the group, Senate Chaplain
Richard C. Halverson, to say a few words.
   Vonette Bright, chairwoman of the National Day of Prayer Task
Force, said she asked Bush privately ``what can we pray for?''
   She said he mentioned ``in private conversation'' the upcoming
conference of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, deeply split
on the subject of short-range missiles, and also ``his great
concern for the moral values of our country, particularly to do
with drugs.''
   Bush noted that it was the first time that the National Day of
Prayer had a permanent date of designation _ the first Thursday of
every May.
   ``We welcome you, we are pleased you're and if you have an extra
minute for a prayer when the going gets a little tough, remember
the Congress. They need it, too,'' the president joked.
   Several members of Congress in attendance.
</TEXT>
