<HEAD>Guilty Pleas By One Defendant In Newspaper Hostage Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd graf to UPDATE with comments from
Jacobs and his mother. Pick up 3 graf pvs, `Jacobs and ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DROSCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two men who said they took
hostages in The Robesonian newspaper office to draw attention to
official corruption pleaded guilty today to fourteen counts of
second-degree kidnapping.
   Timothy Jacobs, 20, agreed to a plea bargain that called for him
to serve six years in prison followed by a six-year suspended
sentence with supervised probation.
   ``He wants to get on with his life and do something with
himself,'' said his mother, Eleanor Jacobs, after the court
appearance. ``It was his decision (to plea bargain). I didn't talk
him into anything.''
   Jacobs was whisked away by deputies after posting bond so that
he could sign out of the Cumberland County Jail. Asked what he
would do during the 30-day leave, he said, ``Enjoy myself. ... Sign
a movie contract.''
   His lawyer had asked for the time so that Jacobs could get
married and attend to other personal affairs. District Attorney
Richard Townsend criticized the arrangement, saying, ``I object to
him having a honeymoon.''
   Jacobs and Eddie Hatcher held up to 20 people hostage in the
newspaper's newsroom for 10 hours on Feb. 1, 1988. They said they
took over the newspaper to draw attention to allegations of
official corruption and drug trafficking in Robeson County.
   A state task force appointed by Gov. Jim Martin found no
evidence to support their allegations.
   Hatcher and Jacobs were acquitted last year by a federal jury in
Raleigh on hostage-taking charges. The state charges then were
filed by Robeson County authorities.
   Jacobs had sought refuge from the state charges by fleeing to an
Indian reservation in upstate New York. He was returned to North
Carolina in March after dropping an appeal of a New York
extradition order.
   Hatcher, 31, is being held in San Francisco in lieu of $1
million bail and an extradition hearing is scheduled for Friday.
Hatcher had sought refuge on a reservation in Idaho. He later asked
the Soviet consulate in San Francisco for political asylum but his
plea was rejected and he was arrested.
</TEXT>
