<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Panama     05-04 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Panama,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House GOP Leader Questions Reliquinshing Canal to Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich said today
that Americans would not tolerate turning over the Panama Canal to
an administrator handpicked by a dictator.
   Echoing Bush administration statements predicting fraud in
Sunday's Panamanian national elections, Gingrich said ``there's a
very grave danger _ I would say almost a probability _ that the
dictatorship plans to steal the election.''
   Gingrich said that during a White House meeting of Republican
leaders with Bush there was considerable discussion about ``the
concern that all of us feel'' about the possibility the elections
will be rigged to keep strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in
charge.
   Gingrich said a continuing dictatorship rule in Panama could
jeopardize consummation of the Panama Canal treaties, ratified by
the Senate in 1979. Gingrich stopped short, however, of calling for
the United States to abrogate the treaties.
   Under terms of the pacts, the United States is scheduled to
relinquish the strategic canal to Panama in 1999. The U.S.
government is scheduled this year, however, to approve a Panamanian
selected by that government to be the canal's administrator.
   Gingrich said that people committed to democracy in Central
America must ``figure out how the people of Panama can regain
control over their country and have fair and honest elections.''
   Bush said in a speech earlier this week that ``it is evident
that the regime is ready to resort to massive election fraud in
order to remain in power.''
   He said the United States ``will not recognize the results of a
fraudulent election engineered simply to keep Noriega in power.''
But the president didn't say what other steps he might take in the
wake of an election considered to be fraudulent.
   Gingrich, talking to reporters in the White House driveway, said
he favors ``making clear to the people of Panama that we very much
want to work to implement the treaty only with a duly-elected
government that's democratic and that's honest.''
   The U.S. aim, he said, should be to ``serve notice that a phony
election, stolen by a dictatorship, does not constitute the kind of
sovereign government that the United States had in mind in terms of
having treaty relations with Panama.''
   ``I think it is inconceivable that the American people would
tolerate allowing Noriega, either directly or through a puppet, to
appoint the administrator of the Panama Canal,'' Gingrich said. ``I
can't imagine that the American people would tolerate that. It's a
very real and very serious danger.''
</TEXT>
