<FIRST>r i AM-Islands     05-04 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Islands,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Scottish Islands For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two islands off Scotland's west coast
are for sale, and only the rich need apply.
   The 3,400-acre island of Gigha is expected to fetch between $3.4
million and $5 million, according to the real estate agent, Savills.
   Offers for the 600-acre Holy Island are to begin at $1.6
million, said estate agent Knight, Frank and Rutley.
   Included in the Gigha sale are rhododendron and exotic shrub
gardens, planted in 1944 when Sir James Horlick acquired the island
to pursue his passion for the species.
   The island, with a population of 160, was bought in the 1970s by
the Landales, a prominent Scottish landowning family, which is
leaving ``for family reasons,'' the agent said.
   The 19th century Achamore House, its gardens, a hotel, 39 estate
cottages, six farms, and 1,250 acres of farmland are included.
   Holy Island, being sold by Edward and Catherine Morris because
of Morris' ill health, also is home to rare breeds of animals and
plants. On the island are 11 Eriskay ponies, 100 Soay sheep, wild
goats and a small herd of Highland cattle.
   There's a small farmhouse, two automatic lighthouses and four
cottages.
   During the late 17th century, a missionary of the Celtic Church,
St. Molio, lived on the island. His influence gave the site its
religious signifigance.
</TEXT>
