<FIRST>u i PM-Mexico-BusStrike 1stLd-Writethru   05-04 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Bus Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0488,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commuters Turn to Other Means as Mexican Bus Strike Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with morning commute, move up
salary figures. Pickup 14th pvs, `The buses...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxis did a land-office business today and
private vehicles gave lifts to commuters after the government
refused to rescind its decision to fire 23,000 city bus workers who
went on strike.
   Hundreds of buses from the neighboring state of Mexico were
brought in to cover the most heavily used routes of the bus system,
which carries an estimated 2 million riders a day.
   Authorities said military vehicles might be pressed into service
if needed.
   Downtown streets appeared less congested than normal without the
big yellow buses belching black diesel fumes. But the state buses
were charging about 16 cents a ride, four times the regular fare.
   The government fired city bus drivers, mechanics and
administrative workers who staged a one-day walkout Wednesday over
demands for a 50 percent wage increase.
   The workers called off the walkout after they were fired, but
the government refused to rehire them and said it would move ahead
with plans to reorganize the bus line.
   The workers' action came after the government offered
concessions to public school teachers who have been striking for
nearly three weeks.
   The bus workers' salaries average more than $9,000 a year, the
highest in the country for employees of a municipal service.
   Teachers average $1,700 a year.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's office said concessions
granted to teachers would not be extended to other public employees
because teachers had been left behind in past years.
   The president's statement did not mention bus workers but said
widespread raises could revive severe inflation.
   Enrique Jackson, city transportation coordinator, told a news
conference the bus workers could apply for jobs in the new system.
He did not say if there would be spots for all of them.
   He said service under the reorganization should be back to
normal next week.
   City spokesman Jose Luis Manjarrez said that because the bus
strike was declared illegal in advance by the federal labor
mediation board, employees knew they faced dismissal.
   The board acted after the bus workers rejected a 14 percent
increase in wages and benefits.
   The government had increased its offer of an 18 percent raise in
teachers' wages and benefits to 25 percent. Talks on extending that
offer to non-teaching employees and on union democracy continued
Wednesday.
   The buses are part of a system that includes a subway, jitneys
and private bus lines in the city of 19 million. City buses charge
100 pesos, or about 4 cents, a ride.
   Extra police have been assigned to handle crowds at subway
stations and idle government vehicles mobilized to pick up riders
for free.
   A communique from Mayor Manuel Camacho Solis' office said that
under preliminary plans for the bus line reorganization, workers
are to become part owners and operate more independently.
   It appeared a fare increase might come with the reorganization.
Salinas has started a campaign to make state-owned companies
profitable or get rid of them.
   Alfonso Macin, a city spokesman, said the fare for the
reorganized system would be agreed upon ``without the union in the
middle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
