<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0457 05-04 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel May Start Trial of Speaker in Late May</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Dixon comments; picks up at pvs 8th graf,
Dixon and; Maryln is correcr in 8th graf, Today the</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges against Speaker Jim Wright will
probably go to trial before the House ethics committee late this
month and will take seven to 10 days to complete, the panel's
chairman said today.
   Unless there is agreement between the lawyers for Wright,
D-Texas, and the committee to do otherwise, the process will begin
with a presentation of witnesses and other evidence by the
committee's special outside counsel, Richard Phelan.
   Wright's lawyer would then have a chance to offer rebuttal
evidence and bring Wright to the stand for a personal defense.
   Committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said he expected the
disciplinary hearing _ the trial-like proceeding at which the panel
decides whether the 69 ethics charges against Wright have been
proved _ to begin ``the latter part of this month.''
   Dixon told reporters the committee has not yet decided whether
to waive its rules against televising the hearing but added that he
thought ``we should adhere to the rules.'' Wright's supporters
believe television coverage would not be favorable to him and thus
oppose it.
   The ethics panel continued today to interview investors in a
Texas gas drilling venture that made a hefty profit for Wright last
year. Dixon said the interviews were progressing more slowly than
expected and could continue Friday.
   On Wednesday, the panel interviewed San Antonio businessman
Morris Jaffe and geologist Doug Prestridge, both involved in the
deal last year that turned $9,120 into $340,000 over a five-month
period for an investment partnership in which Wright, D-Texas, held
a 50 percent stake.
   Today, the panel began talking to Maryln Cherry, Jaffe's
bookkeeper. It also was scheduled to talk to Jaffe's son Doug, who
is president of the family enterprises, and to Dave Myers, who
supplied the drilling equipment for the well.
   ``There are still a lot of unresolved questions,'' Rep. John T.
Myers of Indiana, the committee's senior Republican, said during a
break in Wednesday's daylong, closed-door hearing.
   Myers said the continuing investigation was distracting
committee staff from the task of preparing for Wright's
disciplinary hearing.
   But Dixon defended his panel against Wright's criticism Tuesday
that the probe had become ``a moving target'' and impossible to
defend against.
   ``The record of the committee shows we have tried to rigidly
adhere to the rules,'' Dixon said. Wright ``will in an appropriate
time have a chance to respond to all the charges.''
   Dixon and other committee members declined to discuss details of
the closed-door testimony, but Stanley Brand, the Washington lawyer
for the investors, said it largely covered the same territory as a
23-page statement on the deal he issued earlier this week.
   That document justified the transaction as a legitimate business
venture and noted that the remaining partners in the deal plan to
drill another well, believing substantial gas deposits remain to be
tapped. It was not, Brand's statement contended, a gift to Wright
designed to gain favor and influence over legislation.
   The Jaffes have been competing to sell the Air Force a new
trainer aircraft produced by one of their companies, Jaffe
Aerospace.
   When it announced last week it was charging Wright with 69 House
rules violations, the ethics committee said it was continuing to
investigate the gas venture, known as the Sabine Lake project after
its location near the Louisiana-Texas line.
   As the ethics panel went about its work, a separate House task
force on ethics began looking at the changing ethical landscape in
Washington and began examining whether it is time after 12 years to
update House rules again.
   At the task force hearing, which opened Wednesday, chairman Vic
Fazio, D-Calif., sought to isolate the hearing from the current
Wright controversy. One witness made the case against revision:
former Rep. Otis Pike, D-N.Y., who opposed the last rewrite of the
rules in 1977.
   ``You were not sent here to peek through the windows of each
other's private lives,'' Pike said. ``You were sent here to pass
laws and solve problems. Your preoccupation with each other's
ethics is preventing you from doing your jobs.''
   He added: ``No one learns his ethics in Congress. No one needs
to be told by his colleagues what is right and fair and honorable.
... Ethics is not as great a problem with Congress as is courage.''
</TEXT>
