<HEAD>Battle Lines Drawn Over Chalk-Mark Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALOS VERDES ESTATES, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some say the police here have
chalked up a victory in the war on crime, others say they've erased
democracy by arresting two women who allegedly wiped away a meter
maid's tire marks.
   ``Nobody is in the middle,'' Police Chief Gary Johansen said
after misdemeanor charges were filed against Rosina Baur and Anne
Bisco. ``Either we are the Gestapo, or they say, `Right on, you did
exactly the right thing.'''
   What police say they did was handcuff and frisk the two women,
who were also arrested for investigation of interfering with a city
official.
   The two are scheduled to appear in court next month. If
convicted they could be fined up to $1,000 and jailed for up to six
months.
   Police in this seaside community have received about 50 letters
and calls since the April 21 arrests, Johansen said recently.
Opinions have been about equally divided, he said.
   The two said Officer Robert Connor took them to jail after
saying he was going to teach them a lesson. Police have advised
Connor not to comment.
   Ms. Bisco acknowledged she wiped a chalk mark off her car's
tire, adding she expects to settle the case by paying a fine.
   But Ms. Baur said she did no such thing. She said she simply
moved her car to a different space in a shopping center parking lot
when she saw the meter maid approaching. She said she will fight
the case in court.
