<FIRST>u i PM-Caledonia 3rdLd-Writethru a0591 05-04 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Caledonia, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0591,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hard-Line Nationalist Kills Pro-Independence Leader In New Caledonia</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with assailant dying. Pickup 5th
graf pvs, ``Leaders of...''</UNK>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hard-line nationalist today shot
and killed the leader of pro-independence forces in the French
Pacific territory of New Caledonia and one of his top aides,
officials said.
   The assailant was mortally wounded by bodyguards of Jean-Marie
Tjibaou, 53, president of the Kanak Socialist National Liberation
Front, officials said.
   High Commissioner Bernard Grasset, New Caledonia's top
administrator, said Tjibaou and his assistant, Yeiwene Yeiwene,
were shot by Djubelly Wea of the United Front for Kanak Liberation,
an extremist faction that considers Tjibaou too moderate.
   Grasset said Wea and two unidentifed accomplices were shot and
badly wounded by the bodyguards and that Wea later died. Grasset
said a criminal investigation was opened, and the wounded men will
be brought back to Noumea.
   Leaders of the assassin's group today announced they are
breaking from a nationalist coalition led by Tjibaou.
   The United Front wants independence at any cost, including
violent action, while Tjibaou, in a surprise move last year, agreed
to a French proposal that includes a referendum in 1998 to decide
whether the territory will become independent or remain part of
France.
   In Paris, the minister for overseas departments and territories,
Louis le Pensec, praised Tjibaou's courage. ``He placed a bet on
peace and reconciliation,'' le Pensec said in a statement. ``The
choice was not easy. He did not give in either for the present, or
for the future.''
   The assassinations occurred on the outlying island of Ouvea, the
scene last year of bloody clashes between nationalists and French
soldiers that left 25 people dead, including six soldiers.
   The nationalists were there to mark the May 5 anniversary of the
storming of a cave where nationalists were holding 22 paramilitary
policemen hostage to press their demands for independence.
   Four policemen were killed in the April 22 attack on a remote
station in which the hostages were taken. The May 5 assault left 19
Kanaks and two more policemen dead.
   Native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, have the fastest growing
population and make up 43 percent of the 145,000 inhabitants of
these islands 1,000 miles east of Australia. European settlers and
their descendants comprise 37 percent, and the rest are Polynesians
and Asians.
</TEXT>
