<DOCNO> AP890504-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Students     05-04 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Students,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disciplined Students Hold Love-Fest With the Masses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Group by group they set out, and so they returned
to campuses 12 hours later.
   But in between, the many student groups coalesced to hold a
disciplined crusade for democracy and love-fest with the masses.
   Broad smiles, applause, ``V'' for victory signs and donations of
cash and drinks greeted the tens of thousands of students as they
trudged under a searing sun Thursday from campuses in northern and
eastern Beijing to central Tiananmen Square.
   ``Thank you, people!'' the students chanted back, exhilarated by
the welcome.
   The march began small and subdued compared with one April 27,
which was livened by repeated police efforts to stop them.
   Early risers on Haidian Road, where several schools are located,
asked each other, ``Have they come out yet?'' and peered down the
street for sign of student banners.
   But when the first groups of students emerged from their walled
campuses, singing out of tune, the reaction was disappointment.
``There aren't very many,'' said one bystander. ``Wait a bit, there
are more coming,'' was the students' answer.
   Come they did, from at least 55 schools, by tens and by
hundreds, until at Tiananmen they formed a mass 60,000 strong.
   Along the way they picked up zest, their chants grew firmer and
their singing stronger. They took as their march song ``The
Internationale,'' a stirring call for world revolution that was
blared from a loudspeaker carried on a three-wheeled car.
   Taxis, trucks loaded with cabbage and public buses steamed on
the hot asphalt, backed up in every direction as the protesters
swarmed over main streets. A taxi driver who stood by his idled
vehicle said he'd been stuck for an hour. ``It's no trouble, it's a
legitimate demonstration,'' he said, calmly smoking.
   Passengers on one bus pasted a sheet of paper outside their
window saying sympathetically, ``The students try hard.''
   Dozens of eager hands reached from cars and buses to snatch at
faintly mimeographed pamphlets distributed by the marchers. Many
people quickly tucked the sheets of paper into their pockets as if
they were contraband.
   ``The rights the people have won with their blood are turned
over to the bureaucrats,'' thundered one.
   The students marched past shiny glass-fronted computer stores on
Haidian Road, called Beijing's Silicon Valley; past construction
sites where workers in yellow hard hats waved their fists in the
air in support; past the Capital Theater showing ``AIDS Victims,''
a movie about the disease.
   Once in Tiananmen, they turned a giant portrait of Sun Yat-sen,
leader of a 1911 revolution, into a backdrop for a rally
celebrating their goals of democratic reform.
   ``We hope the people of China will support us,'' a student
leader shouted into a bullhorn. ``What is there to fear?''
   Students draped their banners over their heads for shade or
fashioned pamphlets into paper hats. Two girls spread their
``Advanced English'' texts over their heads.
   Three hundred students from the Arts and Crafts College stood
out in the sea of white and red banners. They all wore something
yellow: headbands, wrist bands, shirts, neckerchiefs.
   ``We think yellow is the color of democracy,'' said one. ``Red
is the color of repression.''
   By 4 p.m., the footsore and thirsty students had had enough.
   ``Return to your schools and continue to do propaganda work,''
exhorted student leader Wu'er Kaixi as he dismissed the crowd.
   Some left still weakly singing ``The Internationale'' with
parched throats.
   Bystanders lingered longer, shuffling through shards of broken
bottles and squashed plastic water containers, while a breeze
tossed paper across the vast square.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
