<FIRST>r a AM-ChangedCrucifix     05-04 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Changed Crucifix,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diocesan Group Investigates Crucifix Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic officials are interviewing
witnesses in an investigation of reports that the eyes of a
life-size crucifix closed during a Good Friday service in a church.
   ``There are no conclusions yet. We have no report for the bishop
yet,'' said Auxiliary Bishop William Winter, a member of the
investigative committee named by Bishop Donald Wuerl of the Diocese
of Pittsburgh.
   On Wednesday, the panel interviewed the Rev. Vincent Cvitkovic,
pastor of Holy Trinity Catholic Church in Ambridge, where the
crucifix is located, and several others who were present during the
March 24 service.
   Cvitkovic said the plaster figure's eyes were about a third open
when it was moved in January from a corner of the church, where it
hung at eye level, to a more prominent position 15 feet above the
altar.
   He said the eyes closed to narrow slits on Good Friday.
   News reports of the incident drew thousands of people to the
church northwest of Pittburgh in the days following Good Friday.
   ``They're still coming, but probably not as many as when it
first happened,'' the pastor said Wednesday.
   He said some of the visitors are sick or handicapped people
seeking a cure.
   ``They all come here with hope,'' he said.
</TEXT>
