<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-PLO     05-04 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-PLO,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes to Bar Funding for U.N. Units That Admit PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A move to bar U.S. funding for any United
Nations organization that admits the Palestine Liberation
Organization as a member state won 10-0 approval today from a panel
of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The move came as a warning in advance of a decision next week by
the World Health Organization, a U.N. agency, on the PLO's
application for full membership.
   The subcommittee on human rights and international organizations
acted after members declared that the PLO does not meet the
qualifications of a state under international law.
   ``It is not a government and does not meet the qualifications of
a state,'' said Chairman Gus Yatron, D-Pa.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said that if the WHO does vote to
admit the PLO he will introduce legislation demanding that the
United States suspend its recently opened dialogue with the PLO,
which has been accused of fomenting terrorism against Israel.
   The resolution endorsed by the subcommittee would forbid U.S.
contributions ``to the United Nations or any of its affiliated
organizations which grant full membership as a state to any
organization or group that does not have the internationally
recognized attributes of statehood.''
   It was not clear whether the full House would be able to act on
the legislation before the WHO votes on the issue.
   The PLO currently has observer status at the United Nations and
in its organizations but is not a full voting member.
</TEXT>
