<FIRST>u a PM-Obit-Younger     05-04 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Younger,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former California Attorney General Evelle Younger Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former California Attorney General Evelle
Younger, who as a tough district attorney oversaw the prosecution
of Charles Manson and Sirhan Sirhan, was found dead in his home
today. He was 70.
   Police were called to Younger's home in Hollywood at 8:30 a.m.
and found him dead, apparently of natural causes, said Officer Bill
Frio.
   Along with his public service careers as California's and Los
Angeles County's top prosecutor, Younger was a municipal and
superior court judge. In 1978 he was an unsuccessful Republican
candidate for governor.
   Younger described himself as a moderate Republican, tough on
crime issues and sympathetic to consumer and environmental concerns.
   When he lost the governor's race to Democratic incumbent Gov.
Jerry Brown, he had been in public service for 37 years, 25 of
which were in elected office. Younger went into private practice
after his defeat.
   Born in Nebraska on June 19, 1918, Younger attended Northwestern
Law School in Chicago as a student of criminology.
   He was admitted to the California Bar in 1946 and was a deputy
city attorney in Los Angeles from 1946 to 1950. He went in to
private practice in 1950 and became a Municipal Court judge in 1953.
   He was appointed to the Superior Court bench in 1958 and became
District Attorney in 1964. It was in that position that he oversaw
the successful prosecution of Sirhan, convicted of assassinating
Sen. Robert F. Kennedy in 1968, and Manson, convicted of
masterminding the 1969 murders of actress Sharon Tate and eight
other people.
   Younger served as California attorney general from 1970 to 1978.
   He was also chief of President Ronald Reagan's Task Force on
Administration of Justice.
</TEXT>
