<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Theft     05-04 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Theft,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Museum Robbed of Works by Dali and Matisse</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RIO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six armed men flashing fake police
badges entered a museum and got away with millions of dollars in
art by such masters as Dali and Matisse, a museum official said
Thursday.
   Marcia Moreira, an assistant to the director of Rio's Chacara do
Ceu Museum, said the thieves arrived Wednesday night, showed their
fake badges to a guard and told him they were looking for men who
had just mugged a tourist.
   They tied up the guard and two other employees, stole paintings,
sculptures and tapestries and escaped, Moreira said.
   Marcio Fortes, the museum's director, said the lost works were
worth $30 million to $40 million and were mostly uninsured.
   Lucia Olinto, the museum's executive director, told The
Associated Press, ``We didn't have the money to insure the works of
art against theft. The only insurance practically any museum in
Brazil can afford is against fire and other disasters.''
   Among the most valuable works stolen, according to Moreira, were
a 1929 painting by the Spanish surrealist Salvador Dali, ``Les Deux
Balcons,'' or ``The Two Balconies.'' It was the only Dali on public
display in Brazil. The artist died Jan. 23.
   The Dali was insured, but only when outside of Brazil, Moreira
said.
   Also stolen was a 1905 painting, ``Le Jardin du Luxembourg,'' or
``Luxembourg Garden,'' by French artist Henri Matisse.
   Two Chinese ceramic sculptured horses from the 7th century T'ang
dynasty were taken, along with various other works, he said.
   The thieves left behind valuable paintings by Spanish master
Pablo Picasso, Moreira said.
   Police spokesman Jorge Marques Sobrinho said the robbers knew
what they were looking for.
   The museum, in the neighborhood of Santa Teresa, had been the
residence of the late Brazilian industrialist Raymundo Ottoni de
Castro Maya, who left his home and collection to the nation.
</TEXT>
