<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-PLO     05-04 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-PLO,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Aide Off Critical List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A PLO official who was shot in the head
spoke Thursday for the first time since the assassination attempt
and was taken off the critical list, his surgeon said.
   Police have arrested several people in connection with the
attack on Issam Salem and the fatal shooting of a Palestinian
security officer, according to an official of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   At Hammoud Hospital, Dr. Hussein Mansour said Salem asked about
the swelling on the left side of his temple.
   ``He's still in the intensive care unit, but he is improving
gradually. He needs time. He's going to make it,'' said Mansour,
one of the doctors who operated on Salem for five hours after the
Tuesday shooting.
   Salem, 48, is PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's personal envoy in
Lebanon and is based in Sidon, the city 25 miles south of Beirut
that is the PLO's main power base.
   Mansour said Salem ``removed the oxygen mask early today. He's
breathing normally, so we didn't put it back again. His heart is
functioning properly and he doesn't have a fever.''
   Salem was taken off the critical list on the recommendation of
various physicians, he said.
   The PLO official in Sidon refused to give details about arrested
suspects. ``Several arrests have been made and we expect to make
more arrests,'' he said on condition of anonymity.
   A day after Salem was hit, a lone assassin shot and killed
Bassam Hourani, a 30-year-old Palestinian security official.
   Sidon police said they have no explanation for the shootings
targeting pro-Arafat Palestinians, including a Saturday
rocket-propelled grenade attack on the residence of PLO spokesman
Zeid Wehbi. He was not home at the time, but two passers-by were
injured.
   Arafat has implied Syrians are behind the attacks because the
PLO leader backs Christians in sectarian fighting in Beirut. But
Wehbi on Wednesday blamed Israel, saying its secret service wants
to ``deal a blow to Lebanese-Palestinian coexistence.''
</TEXT>
