<FIRST>r w AM-IowaRepairs     05-04 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa Repairs,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Damage Assessed at $15 Million to $20 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department, in an assessment of
damage on the battleship Iowa, said Thursday that the Navy believes
the damaged gun turret can be repaired for $15 million to $20
million.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said no decision had
yet been made to proceed with repairs but that the dollar estimate
was sufficiently low that cost was unlikely to be a factor in
resolving the Iowa's future.
   A more important question, Howard said, is likely to be whether
the ship should be withdrawn from duty immediately for repairs, or
allowed to proceed with routine deployments until its next
regularly scheduled overhaul.
   Howard disclosed earlier this week that a 35-member team of Navy
specialists had determined the materials and expertise were still
available to make repairs.
   The answer to that basic question had not been clear in the
immediate aftermath of the April 19 tragedy because of the vessel's
age. The Iowa was commissioned in 1943 during World War II and no
vessel of its type has been built since that war.
   Forty-seven sailors died in the explosion inside the No. 2 gun
turret while loading a 16-inch gun with powder.
</TEXT>
