<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     05-04 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Leader Meets Rebels; Says He Wants Peace By Consensus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa met
Tamil Tiger rebels Thursday and said he wants to end their
separatist war through ``consultation, compromise and consensus,''
the government said.
   Rebels and government officials met for five hours, sources said
after the first peace talks since the guerrillas began a bloody
ethnic war that has killed 9,000 people in six years.
   The negotiators are four rebel leaders and seven government
envoys, a government official said on condition of anonymity.
   After several refusals, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
made a surprise announcement April 15 that they would accept a
government amnesty and start peace talks.
   On Thursday, the leader of this Indian Ocean island said the
first stage of talks will decide modalities and identify issues,
according to a government statement issued after the rebels called
on Premadasa.
   ``Premadasa told the Tamil rebels he plans to restore peace
through a process of consultation, compromise and consensus,'' it
said.
   Sources said the two teams met at a well-guarded luxury hotel in
Colombo as police and sailors patrolled the capital in jeeps.
   Premadasa slipped quietly into the hotel for a few minutes as
the talks began, a witness said on condition of anonymity.
   Five Tigers in camouflage uniforms stood guard with AK-47
assault rifles, the government official said. Other witnesses said
the government deployed plainclothes security men armed with
submachine guns and revolvers.
   Air force helicopters brought the Tigers from their jungle
hideout in Vavuniya, 135 miles north of Colombo.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said Wednesday the rebels
agreed to a cease-fire during the talks.
   But a Tiger leader who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Thursday they also want Indian troops to halt operations.
   The Tigers are battling 48,000 Indian peacekeeping soldiers
deployed to disarm them. India became involved because its Tamil
minority sympathizes with the rebel cause.
   The Tiger guerrilla said if the present talks succeed, he
expects them to lead soon to negotiations including Premadasa and
Tigers' leader Velupillai Prabhakaran.
   The government also faces opposition from Sinhalese radicals,
who accuse the government of making too many concessions to Tamils.
Officials accuse the extremist Sinhalese People's Liberation Front
of killing 2,500 people this year _ mostly government officials and
supporters.
   Tamil Tigers in 1983 launched their bloody bid for a separate
nation called Eelam in the north and east, where the minority
Tamils form a majority. They charge they are discriminated against
by Sinhalese, who outnumber them 4-1. Most Sinhalese are Buddhists
and most Tamils Hindu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
