<DOCNO> AP890504-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1414EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     05-04 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>US To Replace Seven Diplomats in Managua Expelled Last July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is sending seven U.S.
diplomats to Nicaragua to replace all but one of the American
envoys who were expelled by the Sandinista government 10 months
ago, a spokeswoman said Thursday.
   Nicaragua, in turn, will be allowed to replace seven of the
diplomats the Reagan administration had expelled in retaliation for
the ouster of the Americans.
   The upgrading of the respective embassy staffs does not reflect
an improvement in relations between the two countries but rather a
desire of both to be better represented in each other's capital,
according to U.S. officials.
   Last July, the Sandinista government ordered U.S. Ambassador
Richard Melton and seven other envoys out of Nicaragua on charges
they were fomenting unrest.
   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said all seven slots
below the ambassador level will be filled. In addition, four others
in Managua who are being reassigned will be replaced, bringing to
11 the number of new American diplomats being sent there.
   U.S. officials said the embassy in Managua has been operating
under considerable strain because the number of diplomats there has
been too small for the work load. The area most affected has been
reporting on political and economic affairs, according to the
officials, who asked not to be identified.
   Among those expelled by the Reagan administration was Ambassador
Carlos Tunnermann, who was accredited both to the United States and
the Organization of American States.
   Nicaragua objected to vigorously to Tunnermann's expulsion,
contending it was a violation of standard procedure to expel a
diplomat assigned to an international organization.
   The Bush administration's policy toward Nicaragua has been to
promote a democratic evolution there through political, economic
and diplomatic pressures. This represented a marked change from the
approach of President Reagan, who felt military pressure by the
Contra rebels was the only way to achieve that objective.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has said that the United
States is prepared to make conciliatory gestures toward the
Sandinistas if they promote genuine democratic reform between now
and next February, when national elections are scheduled.
Otherwise, he has said, the administration will increase economic
pressures and take other steps against the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
