<FIRST>r w AM-US-Warming     05-04 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Warming,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Opposes Global Warming Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Thursday opposed
legislation calling for a 10-year program to study the warming of
the world's climate and to require that federal agencies consider
the effect of their actions on the global environment.
   The House bill calls for coordinating research with other
countries and international organizations, including the World
Meteorological Organization and the U.N. Environmental Program.
   ``We oppose the enactment of the bill as unnecessary because it
duplicates existing government function and authority,'' said
Wiiliam E. Evans, undersecretary for oceans and atmosphere in the
Commerce Department.
   He objected to asking federal agencies to take the global
environment into consideration on the ground that the government
already has the power to do that.
   ``The administration is currently reviewing this issue,'' he
said.
   Dalas L. Peck, director of the U.S. Geological Survey, singled
out the bill's provision for a ``Council on Global Environmental
Policy'' as unnecessary because the federal government already has
the Council on Environmental Quality. He also opposed giving
Congress a say in setting the way the administration handles its
budget.
   Both Evans and Peck endorsed the purpose of the bill, which
seeks to advance scientific understanding of global climate changes
and to provide a basis for the government's policy decisions.
   It was introduced by Rep. Walter B. Jones, D-N.C., chairman of
the House Committee on Merchant Marine and Fisheries. Wednesday's
hearing was held by its subcommittee on Oceanography and the Great
Lakes.
   The bill was endorsed by Stephen H. Schneider of the National
Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., which is
sponsored by the National Science Foundation.
   ``Such a measure to coordinate federal activities in global
change research and the policy implications of global change is
long overdue,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
