<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Press     05-04 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Press,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Join Students in Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists from China's tightly controlled
official media joined students Thursday in an unprecedented
demonstration for freedom of the press.
   China's most outspoken newspaper, the World Economic Herald, in
its latest issue called for freedom of speech and the development
of independent newspapers, despite the fact that its editor was
fired last week for refusing to obey government orders.
   About 300 journalists, students and onlookers gathered outside
the rustic gates of the state-run Xinhua News Agency.
   Chinese reporters participating in the march said journalists
from more than 30 major newspapers and magazines, all
state-controlled, had joined the protest.
   After hoisting banners reading ``Don't make us tell lies'' and
``Citizens, China is yours,'' they moved down the street,
surprising residents who had not expected to see marchers coming
from their own neighborhood far to the south of Beijing's
university district.
   Xinhua authorities warned employees against joining the protest,
said two reporters. ``We had to sneak out. Many people were unable
to come,'' one said.
   On Wednesday, dozens of journalists of the official media
launched a petition drive to demand the reinstatement of Qin Benli,
former editor of the Shanghai-based World Economic Herald, who was
fired last week for refusing to alter articles officials said were
``likely to cause disturbances.''
   The respected weekly, which implicitly protested Qin's firing,
also called for an independent, free press.
   ``Political democratization is closely linked to press
democratization,'' it said. ``We need an environment for free,
truthful speech.''
   Reporters, many belonging to the Communist Party, have demanded
a dialogue with government officials on broader issues of
censorship, reflecting growing dissatisfaction with a system in
which much of their work is never released.
   Their protests have been prompted in part by tight government
limits on reporting of student demonstrations over the past few
weeks. Dozens of Chinese journalists have covered the protests, but
only a few newspapers have reported the scale and popularity of the
marches.
   ``Most of us young reporters at the People's Daily want to speak
the truth, but our paper is the most tightly controlled,'' said one
journalist. ``Since the students have shouted so much for a free
press, we should speak out, too,'' he said.
   When the journalists and student marchers converged on Beijing's
main thoroughfare, Changan Boulevard, there was an explosion of
applause, hand shaking and cheers.
   ``I think the journalists' joining us will give our movement
more strength,'' said one student.
</TEXT>
