<FIRST>r w AM-LewisIndicted     05-04 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lewis Indicted,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Drug Charges Filed Against Lewis, Friend of Barry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia
filed new charges Thursday against former city employee Charles
Lewis, adding one count of conspiracy and five counts of cocaine
distribution to the 10 charges lodged against him earlier.
   ``Today's indictment alleges signficant involvement by Mr. Lewis
in a pattern of narcotics trafficking over several years in the
District of Columbia and elsewhere in the United States, '' said
U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens.
   The new indictment alleges that Lewis, a resident of the Virgin
Islands, periodically transported cocaine from Florida to
Washington and neighboring Virginia.
   Lewis, a friend of Mayor Marion Barry, was originally indicted
April 13 on seven counts of lying to a grand jury and three counts
of cocaine possession. In a separate action, he was convicted April
25 of four counts of cocaine trafficking in the Virgin Islands.
   The federal investigation began after two city police officers
were called off an attempt on Dec. 22 to make an undercover drug
purchase from Lewis after Barry showed up at Lewis' hotel room.
Barry has acknowledged contacting police officials looking into the
affair but has said he was only trying to speed up the
investigation.
   Stephens said when the previous indictments were announced that
police had been cleared of any misconduct.
   One of the perjury charges alleges that Lewis lied about whether
he had possessed cocaine Dec. 22. Lewis was also charged with lying
about whether he had bought or used drugs with two companions Dec.
21, a day on which Barry reportedly visited Lewis' room twice.
   Thursday's indictment claims that Lewis possessed and
distributed a mixture containing an unknown amount of cocaine on or
about Dec. 10 and on or about Dec. 22 in Washington.
   Although Lewis checked out of his hotel room Dec. 23, before
police could search it or officially link traces of cocaine found
in the room to him, Stephens said investigators may have gathered
physical evidence to be used in the trial.
   Federal investigators also are looking into Lewis' role in
coordinating a $260,000 joint project involving the city and Virgin
Islands governments. Lewis was fired from the project, which was
supposed to revise the Virgin Islands government's personnel
policies and procedures, a year ago amid concerns about cost
overruns.
   The conspiracy charge and each of the distribution counts
carries a penalty of up to 20 years imprisonment and a maximum fine
of $1 million.
   Lewis is to be arraigned May 8 before U.S District Judge Stanley
Sporkin.
</TEXT>
