<FIRST>r a PM-BradleyTroubles 1stLd-Writethru a0522 05-04 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bradley Troubles, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC To Investigate Bradley's Stock Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs and SUBS grafs 10-11, bgng, `But Hahn ...,
with 4 grafs to CORRECT that transactions weren't necessarily with Drexel
and that Hahn gave documents to SEC sted vice versa; DELETES last 3 grafs
to conform. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city attorney has asked the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission to look into Mayor Tom Bradley's
stock trades in companies that later were swept up in a major
insider-trading scandal.
   City Attorney James Hahn forwarded information on the trades to
the Securities and Exchange Commission, Hahn's spokesman, Mike
Qualls, said today.
   ``We did it on our own initiative,'' the spokesman said.
``Questions had arisen and we felt they were the ones with
expertise to look into it.''
   The mayor has ties to indicted junk-bond guru Michael Milken,
who was fired as the top bond trader for Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. after being charged with racketeering and fraud in the
insider-trading probe.
   Hahn's statements came after he testified before a City Council
Government Operations Committee hearing in which city lawmakers
took up the issue of whether Bradley violated city conflict of
interest ordinances.
   City Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg told the committee he takes
responsibility for a $600,000 deposit in federal grant money that
sat idle in a bank. That bank later paid Bradley to serve as an
adviser.
   ``Very frankly, we screwed up,'' Rittenberg said, explaining the
city's handling of funds from the federal Urban Mass Transportation
Administration. He said he was not pressured by Bradley to make the
deposit.
   Far East National Bank at one point held more than $1.3 million
in city money deposits and paid Bradley $18,000 last year as a
consultant. The mayor has since returned the salary.
   In addition to Far East National Bank, the city attorney also is
investigating the mayor's $24,000-a-year salary as a member of the
board of directors of Valley Federal Savings and Loan Association,
which has been involved in city business.
   Though Hahn wouldn't detail the SEC connection, it appears to
center on the mayor's 1985 and 1986 purchases of stock in two
companies _ Beatrice Foods Inc. and the Wickes Cos. Inc. _ that now
are part of the investigation of Drexel and Milken.
   The federal indictment of Milken alleges he manipulated the
price of Wickes stock. Congressional investigators have said they
found Drexel employees bought significant amounts of the junk bonds
used to finance a leveraged buyout of Beatrice.
   Hahn said he gave the SEC copies of the mayor's financial
disclosure statements _ on public file with the City Clerk _ which
describe both transactions.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder refused to comment on the matter
and wouldn't say if Bradley ever had an account at the brokerage.
   Bradley has close ties to Milken, a major contributor to the
mayor's political campaigns. Bradley helped organize an effort to
lobby Congress to persuade the SEC to allow Drexel's junk bond
division to remain in Beverly Hills after a federal investigation
began.
</TEXT>
