<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GorillaDeath     05-04 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gorilla Death,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Zoo Gorilla Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Penelope, an African-born lowland gorilla that
produced four offspring in the Cincinnati Zoo's mating program, has
died at age 35.
   She had lived at the zoo since 1957 and was its oldest lowland
gorilla.
   Penelope's keepers found her in critical condition early
Wednesday. Despite efforts to save her, Penelope died later in the
day. Results of tests to determine the cause of death will be
available in about two weeks, zoo officials said.
   The small, 3-year-old gorilla was a gift to the children of
Cincinnati from Nobel Prize winner Dr. Albert Schweitzer. He gave
Penelope to show his appreciation for a gift of goats and medical
supplies for his hospital at Lambarane, Africa, sent him by
Cincinnati residents.
   Gorillas usually live 35 to 40 years in captivity, zoo officials
said.
</TEXT>
