<HEAD>DeBartolo Family Gives $33 Million to Notre Dame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developers Edward J. DeBartolo and his
son, Edward J. DeBartolo Jr., have donated $33 million to the
University of Notre Dame, one of the largest gifts ever made to an
American university.
   Most of the money will be spent in construction of a
computer-equipped classroom building and a performing arts center,
university board chairman Donald R. Keough, president of Coca-Cola
Co. Inc., said Thursday.
   Both DeBartolos are graduates of Notre Dame.
   The elder DeBartolo is founder of the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp.
headquartered in Youngstown, Ohio. His son is the company's chief
administrative officer. The corporation is one of the world's
largest developers of commercial and office property and owns three
shopping centers in Indianapolis.
   The gift is the largest contribution ever given Notre Dame and
the 18th largest to an American university. The largest gift was
$105 million given to Emory University in 1979 by Coca-Cola.
