<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Executions,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Traffickers Hanged in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Thursday hanged 27 drug
traffickers convicted on narcotics charges, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   The traffickers were hanged in Mashhad, near the northern border
with Afghanistan, where most drugs are smuggled into the country,
the news agency said.
   They had been wanted for importing, purchasing, selling and
distributing illegal drugs before they were captured, according to
the agency, monitored in Nicosia. The agency did not say when they
were arrested.
   The death sentences fell under a tough drug law that took effect
in January, and 543 people have been executed. The law mandates the
death penalty for anyone caught in possession of even small
quantities of narcotics.
   In one recent two-day crackdown, police rounded up 792 alleged
traffickers and drug addicts, Tehran radio said last week.
