<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-04 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Say Decision They Have `Last Word' About Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials said Thursday the
decision about whether to have nuclear missiles on its territory
ultimately rests with West Germany, not its NATO partners.
   The West Germans insist, over strong objections by the United
States and Britains, that East-West negotiations be held on
reducing the number of short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
   Also at issue is whether to modernize the alliance's 88
battlefield-range Lance missiles, most of which are stationed in
this country and would be used here in case of war. West Germany
wants NATO to postpone a decision on modernization.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said in an interview
Wednesday night: ``We have the first and last word about the
stationing of rockets on our territory, and no one else.''
   On Thursday, a government official said Genscher meant decisions
on nuclear missiles based in West Germany should be made by
consultation within the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, but
Bonn has the final say.
   ``We have to give our consent,'' the official said, speaking
privately.
   He noted Genscher's previous comment that West Germany's views
on missiles based within its boundaries must be given ``special
weight.''
   Alfred Dregger, parliamentary chairman of Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's Christian Democratic Union party, was quoted as saying some
NATO countries refuse to understand why West Germany wants
increased efforts for disarmament.
   Those nations ``are not ready to acknowledge the strategic
situation of the only divided country in Europe, through which the
militarized border between East and West runs,'' he said, according
to the newspaper Sueddeutsche Zeitung.
   It also quoted Dregger as saying NATO's ``foundations of trust''
could be damaged if the alliance does not show enough consideration
for the interests of individual members.
   NATO nations are trying to heal the rift before the alliance
summit May 29-30 in Brussels. West Germany claims nearly half the
16 members are on its side.
   Genscher and Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg sent a letter
Wednesday to Secretary of State James A. Baker III, a West German
official said privately. He called it ``part of the decision-making
process'' but said he did not know the contents.
   Canada has proposed a compromise that calls for negotiations on
short-range nuclear weapons with the understanding that some
modernized Lances would remain and the Warsaw Pact's edge in
conventional forces would be ended.
   President Bush said Wednesday that starting negotiations on
short-range weapons now ``would be a mistake.''
   Baker and his 15 NATO counterparts are to meet in Brussels on
May 10-11. The weapons disagreement is expected to be the major
topic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
