<FIRST>r a AM-AdamsExecution     05-04 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Adams Execution,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prison Guard Dies In Electric Chair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of an 8-year-old murder victim
applauded Thursday outside Florida State Prison when witnesses
signaled that a former prison guard convicted of her murder had
been executed.
   Aubrey Dennis Adams Jr., 31, died in the electric chair for
suffocating Trisa Gail Thornley, an Ocala third-grader who was
kidnapped on her way home from school Jan. 23, 1978, and died in an
assault Adams claimed he didn't remember. Her mutilated, naked body
was found in a plastic bag 53 days later.
   The victim's mother, Ann Thornley, now living in Reliance,
Tenn., burst into tears and hugged her surviving daughter, Traci
Freeman, after the electrocution.
   ``I'm glad it's over. It's a decade too late in coming,'' said
Ms. Thornley, who left after the execution to visit her daughter's
grave in Ocala.
   She and other relatives clapped when the execution was confirmed
and again when an ambulance carrying Adams' body drove by.
   Seven capital-punishment opponents kept a silent vigil for
Florida's first execution since notorious serial killer Ted Bundy
died Jan. 24. Adams was the 21st man to die in Florida's electric
chair since the state resumed executions in 1979.
   ``We finally got justice today. I just wish my husband was
here,'' said Mrs. Thornley, whose husband, James, died late last
year of heart problems. ``This killed him.''
   Adams left a final statement with the Rev. W.J. Barfield, an
execution witness and pastor of the Church of God in Newberry.
   ``I hope and pray that all the new and reopened wounds will be
healed quickly after my passing,'' Adams wrote.
   Barfield said he and Adams talked all night, and that Adams
expressed remorse but never mentioned specifics of the crime.
   A large puff of white smoke rose from Adams' right leg when the
2,000 volts of electricity jolted him at 7:04 a.m. EDT. He surged
violently back into the chair, then was pronounced dead five
minutes later.
   Adams' attorneys made a whirlwind round of appeals Wednesday in
hopes of finding a judge to stay the execution. But the U.S.
Supreme Court voted 7-2 Wednesday night to reject Adams' emergency
request.
   Adams was linked to the crime when the family asked for a
telephone trace to find the source of obscene calls, and a call
made two days before the girl's body was found was traced to his
home.
   He admitted picking her up. He said he recalled that she
screamed and he placed his hand over her mouth to silence her. An
autopsy showed she suffocated.
   Adams, once an officer at Marion Correctional Institution, had
no prior criminal record.
</TEXT>
