<FIRST>u w PM-CanadianEmbassy 2ndLd-Writethru a0623 05-04 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canadian Embassy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0623,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Negotiate Missile Cut Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs with Bush comment; picks up at pvs 5th graf, Mulroney
was</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he is willing to
negotiate over a dispute in NATO over short-range nuclear weapons
but that he would not accept total elimination of the weapons or
permit the Soviet Union to maintain its superiority.
   Bush commented in a joint news conference with Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney after the two leaders discussed the issue
during a White House meeting.
   West Germany has called for negotiations to reduce the
nuclear-tipped missiles and artillery shells, but Bush has rejected
the idea. The dispute threatens to disrupt the harmony of a North
Atlantic Treaty Organization summit in Brussels on May 29-30.
   ``I want the NATO summit to be a success and we will be working
with the Germans and with others to see that there is a common NATO
position,'' the president said. ``This is no time for one to
compromise or somebody not to compromise.''
   Bush said the United States had made some proposals to Bonn and
``I expect we'll be hearing from them soon. ...''
   ``I'm always willing to negotiate, but we're not going to go for
any third zero (elimination of the weapons) or getting SNF (another
term for the weapons) out of whack in terms of negotiations. So
let's be clear on that,'' he said.
   Mulroney said that although NATO must debate the issue, ``in the
end there must be solidarity, total solidarity.''
   Mulroney was in Washington to dedicate his country's new $76
million embassy, the first ever built on Pennsylvania Avenue. It is
a modernistic, six-story building of Ontario limestone and
unpolished aluminum.
   The embassy was occupied in March, a year behind schedule, at a
cost of $76 million, nearly double the original estimate. But its
troubles were forgotten Wednesday evening as Mulroney and Secretary
of State James A. Baker III paid tribute to the enduring friendship
between their two countries.
   ``The maple leaf comes to Pennsylvania Avenue,'' Mulroney
declared.
   Baker said the new embassy ``conveys the warmth and openness of
the people of Canada'' and promised to give U.S.-Canadian ties
``the personal attention this friendship deserves.''
   With a smiling Baker at his elbow, Mulroney then took a pair of
scissors and snipped a royal blue ribbon draped across the main
entrance to the chancery building. Together, they went up to
Ambassador Derek Burney's penthouse office suite to admire the view
below.
   Their audience of several hundred dignitaries included
congressional leaders, Supreme Court Justice Harry A. Blackmun, CIA
Director William Webster and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
   They feasted on shrimp, beef and salmon canapes and iced bottles
of Canadian ale while kilted bagpipers and a military band from
Ottawa performed on the courtyard outside.
   The dramatic building, designed by Vancouver architect Arthur
Erickson, is the only foreign embassy situated on Pennsylvania
Avenue, the ceremonial route linking the Capitol and the White
House.
   Standing on a 1.2-acre plot opposite the National Gallery of Art
and close to Capitol Hill, the embassy site was chosen to symbolize
the close historic ties between the United States and Canada.
   The land formerly was the site of boarding houses, a library, a
Ford automobile factory and most recently a city shelter for
homeless women. Former White House chief of staff Howard Baker once
called it ``the finest piece of real estate in North America.''
   The embassy's 327-member staff moved into the building a month
ago from its previous quarters in two buildings on Massachusetts
Avenue, the city's traditional ``embassy row,'' and rented space in
a downtown office building.
   Burney, who arrived shortly before Bush was inaugurated on Jan.
20, will continue to reside in an elegant, six-story mansion on
Massachusetts Avenue where Canadian envoys had maintained their
offices since 1928.
   The stone courtyard outside the main entrance features a
statuary pool, terraced greenery along office balconies and a
fountain surrounding a rotunda resting on 12 columns representing
Canada's 10 provinces and two territories.
   Inside the 287,000-square-foot building, whose ground floor is
shielded by bullet-resistant glass windows, are a 20,000-volume
library, a 175-seat theater, a small exercise room, an art gallery,
an underground garage and a ``safe room'' to guard secret
discussions against electronic eavesdropping.
   The start of construction, originally scheduled for 1985, was
delayed for a year because of spending cuts ordered by Mulroney's
government after he took office in 1984.
   Earlier, the government of Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau came
under fire when it selected Erickson, an old Trudeau friend, as
embassy architect after an independent advisory commission had
rejected Erickson in favor of four other architects.
</TEXT>
