<HEAD>Bonbs Kill Soldier and Prison Employee</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Thatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs killed a British soldier
and a prison employee Thursday, and the IRA said it planted the
first one to mark Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's 10th
anniversary in office.
   Cpl. Stephen McGonigle, 30, was killed in Silverbridge, near the
province's border with the Irish Republic, according to Armagh
police.
   Police said the bomb went off as soldiers examined a parked car,
but whether the explosives were in the car was not known.
   John Griffiths, a prison employee, was killed by a bomb that
exploded under his car. There was no immediate claim of
responsibility.
   Griffiths, a 37-year-old former soldier with two children, had
driven a short way from his home near Loughgall, County Armagh, on
the way to his job at the Maze Prison in Belfast, police reported.
   An Irish Republican Army statement distributed to Irish media
claimed responsibility for the Silverbridge bombing.
   ``We remind the British people on this the 10th anniversary of
Mrs. Thatcher's government that the Irish question remains
unresolved and cannot be resolved by military policies,'' it said.
   ``If Mrs. Thatcher continues to pursue military goals, the IRA
will have no alternative but to continue to bring the British
occupation of Ireland to the attention of the British public.''
   The IRA is fighting to drive Britain from Protestant-dominated
Northern Ireland and unite it with the republic, which is
overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
