<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson paid soul music
legend James Brown a belated 56th birthday visit in prison Thursday.
   Brown, the self-proclaimed ``Godfather of Soul,'' did not have
any visitors on his birthday Wednesday, said Bennish Brown, a
spokesman for the South Carolina Department of Corrections who is
not related to the singer.
   Jackson, who appeared before the state parole board on Brown's
behalf March 8, declined to talk to reporters on his way into the
prison.
   Brown is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault and
failing to stop for police during a Sept. 26 chase across the
Georgia-South Carolina border.
   He works on kitchen detail in the mornings. In the evenings,
Brown, whose gold records include ``Please, Please, Please,'' and
``Papa's Got a Brand New Bag,'' conducts the prison choir.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vermonters will lose millions of dollars
if they tax movie stars making films in their states, actor Don
Johnson warned Thursday.
   Johnson's comments came in a statement a day after a legislative
committee reversed itself and killed a provision of a new law that
would have exempted entertainers from state income tax. It was
retroactive to Jan. 1, 1986, and would have saved Johnson $50,000.
   The Senate Finance Committee approved the exemption Tuesday, but
24 hours and dozens of telephone calls from angry constituents
later, the panel reversed itself.
   The state billed Johnson for money he earned in Vermont while
making the 1987 film ``Sweetheart's Dance.'' The actor is best
known for his starring role on television's ``Miami Vice.''
   Johnson appealed his tax bill and threatened to spread the word
in Hollywood that Vermont was a bad place to make movies.
   Johnson said Thursday he pays his fair share in taxes already.
``I have never attempted to avoid my personal financial
responsibilities with respect to the funding of governmental
services. I am not a resident of Vermont and do not make use of the
various services provided by that state.''
   Backers of the exemption, including Gov. Madeleine Kunin, said
it would make moviemakers more welcome in Vermont.
   Vermont's income tax is figured as 25 percent of a person's
federal tax liability.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Johnny Cash was being treated
Thursday for a pulled ligament in his right knee.
   Cash, 57, was admitted to the American Hospital of Paris after
his show Wednesday night at the Zenith auditorium, a hospital
statement said.
   Reba Hancock, his sister and spokeswoman, said the injury
apparently is minor. ``He's fine,'' she said in Nashville, Tenn.
   Cash, his wife, June Carter Cash, and an entourage left the
United States about 10 days ago and are expected to return May 17,
Ms. Hancock said.
   Cash, a member of the Country Music Hall of Fame, is known for
such hits as ``I Walk the Line,'' ``Folsom Prison Blues'' and
``Ring of Fire.''
