<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Atwood-Osprey     05-04 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atwood-Osprey,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Defense Secretary Says Pentagon Considers Options on Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is considering two options that
could temporarily stave off elimination of the V-22 Osprey aircraft
program, Deputy Defense Secretary Donald Atwood Jr. said Thursday.
   Atwood told the Senate Appropriations defense subcommittee that
the Defense Department is considering either continuing the Osprey
through a ``flight test program'' or a ``minimal effort of
technology demonstration.''
   Both options would require reprogramming of money, according to
Atwood, who said $330 million exists for long-lead materials for
production of 12 aircraft. The funds could be used if Congress
approved.
   ``We hope to have a decision within a matter of a day or so,''
Atwood told the panel.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, faced with an agreement by the
White House and Congress requiring a $10 billion cut in the fiscal
1990 defense budget, decided to eliminate the Marine Corps'
battlefield aircraft which is designed to take off like a
helicopter but fly like an airplane.
   The Pentagon had hoped to spend $25.9 billion on 663 Ospreys,
including $1.3 billion in 1990. Over a nine-year period, the
department had invested $2 billion in the program.
   Cheney's decision, which he has termed his most difficult, has
met with considerable opposition on Capitol Hill, including some
from Republicans.
   Sens. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, and Arlen Specter, R-Pa., lashed
out at the termination of the program as they questioned Atwood
about the Pentagon budget.
   The Defense Department ``appears ... to be playing games with
us,'' Stevens told Atwood. ``The Defense Department knows how
strongly Congress feels about it and intends to put it back in,''
he added.
   Stevens said he would not vote for any defense bill that does
not include funding for the Osprey program.
   Specter, who discussed the issue with Atwood before the hearing,
said the department should ``explore the possibility of maintaining
at least enough efforts to keep Bell in operation to maintain the
status quo while this matter is evaluated by the Congress. This is
not some peripheral issue where the Congress is likely to accede.''
   The Pentagon faced a deadline because the Osprey's two
contractors, Bell Helicopter Textron Inc., and Boeing Helicopter
Co., have said they will stop work on the project Friday.
   Defense Department spokesman Dan Howard said the companies
received $245.8 million in March on their fiscal 1989 contract and
the Navy expects completion of the contract.
   However, the companies are facing a debt of $27 million and have
been using their own money. The cost overrun is about $25 million a
month and may go as high as $150 million by the end of fiscal 1989.
   Howard said ``what we have here is a game of high-stakes
chicken.''
   ``The intent of the DoD is very clear. We are not at fault. The
contractor (has) expended more money in the program than it
anticipated when it bid,'' Howard said.
   ``The secretary's determination has been that we will not issue
a stop-work order; that we will continue to require the contractor
to complete the testing program under the terms of the contract,''
Howard said.
   Meanwhile, the commandant of the Marine Corps cast doubt on the
information Cheney used in deciding to eliminate the Osprey.
   ``I do not agree with the cost advice that he got nor do I agree
with the military operation use and conceptual framework of that,
but then I'm but one voice,'' Commandant Alfred Gray told the
Senate Armed Services Committee.
   Gray praised the Osprey as an aircraft ``that has enormous
commercial potential ... and one that is not only for your corps
Marines.'' Nevertheless, he said he supported Cheney's decision.
   ``Do you believe Secretary Cheney made the best decision he
could make based on faulty information?'' asked Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee.
   ``No,'' responded Gray, ``but based on the information he was
given by learned people who have their right to believe that
they're correct.''
   ``But you don't believe they're correct,'' Nunn said.
   ``No, I don't, but I had my day in court,'' said Gray, who plans
to submit to the committee his interpretation of the program's cost
benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MoodyBeach Bjt   05-04 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moody Beach, Bjt,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Likely To Visit Moody Beach Despite Property Owners' Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLS, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Property owners won the right to keep the
public off a popular beach, but as the sunbathing season
approaches, town officials say there will be no way to keep people
off the sandy stretch.
   ``It almost seems like we're going back to square one, back to
where we started,'' said Joe Magne, one of the property owners who
prevailed in a decision by the Maine's highest court.
   The divided court ruled in March that public access to the
mile-long Moody Beach is limited to fishing, bird-hunting and
boating on the basis of a 17th century colonial ordinance.
   Maine's attorney general and officials from Wells, a town with a
population of about 10,000, fought to keep the beach open, fearing
a closed beach could harm the state's tourism industry. Maine's
meandering coast is 3,500 miles long, but most of the shoreline is
rocky. Just about 35 miles of sandy beaches are available.
   Wells Town Manager Jonathan Carter requested that Moody Beach
property owners meet with town officials Sunday to discuss two
options for beach use this summer.
   Under the town's first proposal, property owners would agree to
make the beach public and the town will maintain it. Under the
second option, access to the beach would be controlled by the
property owners, but town officials point out that keeping
unauthorized people away would be difficult.
   If police are called with trespassing complaints, they will
handle the complaints like any other non-emergency, Carter said.
Police would enter the beach through the complaining property
owner's home, and the trespassers would merely have to move a few
feet away onto another person's land to satisfy police, Carter said.
   Any complaints taken to court probably would get backlogged
until the tourists are long gone, the town manager said.
   ``It would probably be put off until, say, November,'' Carter
said.
   Carter rejected the suggestion that the town is using the threat
of such delays to make property owners reluctant to complain about
unwelcome tourists.
   But property owners believe the town is trying to set up terms
for beach use even though it lost in court.
   ``To my way of thinking, they're sort of condoning
trespassing,'' said Dr. Warren Jones, one of the litigants.
   Jones said people have used the area around his home and even
under his steps as a toilet.
   ``I'm not the old curmudgeon that wants to keep everyone from
walking across his land,'' Jones said. ``All we ever wanted was
control of our own property. If we're planning a big family picnic,
I want to be able to ask people to leave.''
   Some Wells residents who don't own beachfront land see the
property owners as mean-spirited wealthy people trying to keep
Mainers and visitors from enjoying the beach.
   ``That's nature out there,'' said Luke Nuccio. ``That doesn't
belong to me or you or anyone. Nature's for everybody. Native Maine
people never thought this could happen.''
   ``I plan to waitress in the morning and come to the beach in the
afternoon this summer,'' said schoolteacher Ann French. ``I never
thought this would happen. I think it's going to bring out the
worst in people.''
   Both sides predict that no matter how the issue is resolved,
publicity given to the court case probably will keep some tourists
away, or at an adjacent public beach in Ogunquit.
   The battle over access to Moody Beach may finally be resolved
with the town or the state seeking to acquire the beach through the
government's legal right of eminent domain, both sides said. The
town asked appraisal companies to submit proposals for the beach to
buy as a recreational easement or to take fees for use of Moody
Beach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
