<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Population     05-04 0113</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Population,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Population Falls to Record Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are fewer Japanese children under 15 years of
age today than at any time since the end of World War II, a
government agency said Thursday.
   On April 1, there were 23.6 million under-15-year-olds, which
amounted to 19.2 percent of the 120 billion population, the
Management and Coordination Agency said.
   It was the first time in postwar history the figure fell below
20 percent. In 1945, 36 percent of the Japanese population was
under 15.
   The agency said there were 2 million 14-year-olds and 1.3
million babies aged 11 months or under.
   Boys outnumbered girls 12.1 million to 11.5 million.
</TEXT>
