<DOCNO> AP890504-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Greece-Strikes     05-04 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Greece-Strikes,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes Cripple Services Nationwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nationwide strikes and slowdowns for
higher pay Thursday closed hospitals, tied up major seaports and
caused air traffic delays.
   A 16-day slowdown for overtime pay by longshoremen stranded
dozens of ships waiting to unload. More than 800 trucks waited to
drop off cargo.
   Many ships were diverted to Italian and Maltese ports, shippers
said.
   A five-day strike called by Civil Aviation Authority electrical
engineers delayed international flights and those by Olympic
Airways, Greece's national carrier. The engineers want higher wages
and more fringe benefits.
   A 24-hour strike by more than 40,000 doctors and medical
personnel closed public and private hospitals around Athens. The
doctors also want higher pay. Three state-run hospitals were
staffed by skeleton crews to handle emergencies.
</TEXT>
