<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle     05-04 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Greeted by Thousands at Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SITE B REFUGEE CAMP, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle
visited thousands of Cambodian refugees at their remote, dusty camp
Thursday to ``call the attention of the world'' to their plight.
   In a dramatic finale of the Asian leg of his 12-day trip, Quayle
and his wife Marilyn traveled for two hours _ by military transport
plane, helicopter and limousine _ to reach this camp of bamboo and
thatched houses just six miles from the Thai-Cambodian border and
some 250 miles from Bangkok.
   ``Today is to call the attention of the world to what is going
on. These poor kids here, the sick ...,'' he said.
   The refugees ``want to return to their home (in Cambodia) and
yet they can't because of the illegal occupation by Vietnam,'' he
said. He called the plight of Cambodians ``something that has been
overlooked _ it's a tragedy, a human tragedy.''
   Quayle, the highest-ranking American to visit a refugee camp in
Thailand, was given a hero's welcome by villagers, many of whom
have lived at Site B for a decade awaiting word as to when they can
return to Cambodia.
   The dirt road from the camp's entrance to a central square where
Quayle made a brief speech in the broiling sun was lined for nearly
two miles with children waving paper American, Thai and Cambodian
flags.
   ``I hope his visit will help me go home,'' said Vu Thi, a
40-year-old woman who fled Cambodia a decade ago.
   Some 10,000 people, mainly women and children, greeted Quayle,
who frequently leaned over a rope barrier to touch the youngsters,
pat their stomachs or pose for photographs with them.
   Later, Quayle said he found his visit to a medical clinic at the
well-maintained camp ``very depressing.'' He saw mothers sitting on
bamboo beds surrounded by their sick children.
   The vice president used his visit to underscore what has been a
dominant theme of his Australia-Pacific trip: Cambodia's future
once the Vietnamese troops withdraw Sept. 30.
   ``We will continue our support (for the non-communist
resistance) until there is a complete withdrawal ... and a
political settlement,'' Quayle said, looking out on a sea of people
protecting themselves from the sun with umbrellas.
   ``Vietnam, NO,'' and ``U.S.A., Strong Supporter of Cambodia,''
read large banners hoisted by the crowd.
   The camp is run by Prince Norodom Ranariddh, the son of Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's former leader whom Washington wants to
head a transitional government once Vietnamese troops leave.
   Quayle met with Sihanouk in Indonesia, the second Southeast
Asian country he visited.
   Part of Quayle's mission has been to gather information for
President's Bush's policy review on Cambodia. The two will meet for
lunch Friday after the vice president returns to Washington.
   One option is providing military assistance to the non-communist
factions. While Washington would prefer a diplomatic to a military
solution in Cambodia, it is adamant about refusing to permit the
Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge to dominate any future government.
   The Khmer Rouge were responsible for killing at least 1.5
million people in Cambodia between 1975 and 1978. Cambodia's
current leader, Hun Sen, was installed by Vietnam.
   Security was tight at the camp, where 60,000 people live, with
Secret Service agents in flak jackets wielding assault rifles.
   Quayle had initially planned to tour a larger camp, Site 2, but
the location was changed several days ago because the vice
president's aides thought recent shelling believed to be coming
from Cambodia would place Quayle in too much danger.
   The Site B camp, where Quayle stayed two hours, receives much of
its aid through the U.N. Border Relief Operation.
   Mitchell Carlson, a U.N. worker, said the camp residents have
``very little they can do'' at the camp. He described the place as
``a welfare state,'' with about one-third of the population under
10 years old.
   More than 300,000 Cambodians live in Thai camps, where they are
classified as displaced people and are unable to leave. They are
hoping that Sihanouk's and the other Cambodian factions can arrive
at a solution so they can go home.
   Quayle left Thailand on Thursday, made a refueling stop in Japan
and was heading for Alaska for a brief tour of the cleanup
operations from the March oil spill in Prince William Sound before
returning to Washington.
</TEXT>
