<FIRST>r a AM-People-TrumpGame     05-04 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Trump Game,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheeler-Dealer Faces New Type Of Board</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Trump The Game' is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST LONGMEADOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald J. Trump, a consummate
player in the high-stakes, serious world of big business, visited
the nation's oldest game manufacturer Thursday to herald new
editions of ``Trump The Game.''
   Female workers at the Milton Bradley Co. screeched when he
passed by and one cried when he bussed her on the cheek. ``He
kissed me! He kissed me!'' said a shaky Grace Adams of Springfield,
who has worked 31 years at the company.
   The New York City and Atlantic City, N.J., real estate mogul
flew to the western Massachusetts factory of 2,300 workers in his
black private helicopter to fulfill a promise to the company, which
expects ``Trump The Game'' to be the biggest seller in its 129-year
history, despite its $25 pricetag.
   ``They were intent on having me come up to meet the real
people,'' Trump said. ``These are the people doing the work.''
   Employees clapped at each stop in the 45-minute visit, women
sighed ``Isn't he handsome?'' and men lined up for autographs on
the game money that bears his likeness and comes in denominations
no smaller than $10 million.
   More than 2 million games are scheduled for production by year's
end. It is the No. 1 seller in the 300 stores that have received
advance copies, Milton Bradley President George Ditomassi said.
   Neither the company nor Trump will reveal his royalties from the
game, but both said he is donating proceeds to charities for the
homeless and for research on AIDS, cerebral palsy and multiple
sclerosis.
   The board game is a sophisticated battle in which players first
bid against each other for airlines, casinos, luxury hotels and
other major properties, then try to negotiate deals.
   ``If you don't do well at this game, you should stay on
9-to-5,'' Trump advised, adding that the game is tough even for a
veteran like him.
   But he resisted explaining its appeal. ``If I said it, you'd say
I have a big ego, so why say it?''
   Although several game manufacturers tried to peddle their ideas
to Trump, the one that caught his eye came from an independent
inventor from Chicago who suggested Milton Bradley as a
manufacturer.
   Trump said he settled on the nation's largest board game maker
because ``the loyalty, decisiveness and professionalism of this
company is just unbelievable.''
</TEXT>
