<DOCNO> AP890504-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet 790   05-04 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet, 790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Challenges Soviets to Fulfill Promise of Perestroika</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III
challenged the Soviet Union on Thursday to fulfill Mikhail
Gorbachev's promises of reform, saying the administration intends
``to test the application of Soviet `new thinking' again and
again.''
   Baker's outline of U.S. policy toward the Soviet Union comes as
he prepares to leave Monday on a five-day trip that includes his
first Moscow meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   It also occurs during a crisis within the NATO alliance as the
United States is struggling with its allies on forging a strategy
to deal with Gorbachev's troop reduction and arms control
initiatives.
   The secretary's remarks _ the result of a long-awaited review of
U.S.-Soviet policy undertaken since President Bush took office more
than three months ago _ were contained in a speech prepared for
delivery to members of the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a Washington think tank.
   While applauding such moves such as the withdrawal of troops
from Afghanistan and the agreement banning all U.S. and Soviet
intermediate-range nuclear missiles in Europe, Baker complained
that Soviet behavior still does not square with the slogans of
perestroika.
   The secretary said the United States intends to build on the
progress made in the human rights and arms control arenas, in
particular suggesting a date for the continuation of the strategic
arms talks. The talks dealing with the most dangerous weapons in
the U.S. and Soviet arsenal went into recess late last year.
   But Baker said he intends to go to Moscow to broaden the
U.S.-Soviet agenda, seeking to focus on regional conflicts, the
proliferation of ballistic missiles and chemical weapons and other
issues such as terrorism, the environment and drug abuse.
   ``The president has said, and I have said that we have no wish
to see perestroika fail. To the contrary: we would very much like
it to succeed,'' said Baker. ``... A process that promises to
increase the freedom and improve the well-being of the Soviet
peoples is in everyone's interest.''
   The secretary said it is too early to tell whether Gorbachev's
``new thinking,'' known by the Russian name ``perestroika,'' will
succeed or not.
   And as Baker challenged the Soviets to do more, he offered no
specific U.S. overtures to encourage Soviet concessions.
   ``Unfortunately, there are still many regions where the `new
thinking' has yet to take root. We still see many signs of the old
thoughts and the old actions in Central America, where the Soviets
sent over $500 million in aid to the Sandinistas last year,'' Baker
said.
   He cited Soviet shipments of long-range bombers to Libya's
Moammar Khadafy, Soviet military support of militant North Korea
and the Soviet occupation of Japan's Northern Territories.
   ``At a time when we hear talk of unilateral reductions, of the
need to cut defense spending, and of the necessity to transfer
precious resources from the military economy to the civilian
sector, 3,500 new Soviet tanks continue to roll off the production
lines each year _ a production rate five times greater than our
own,'' Baker said.
   The secretary faulted the Soviets for failing to publish ``a
real defense budget,'' one that would allow an independent
evaluation of Gorbachev's military spending and his pledge to slash
his defense spending by 14 percent.
   He also complained that while there has been talk of a ``common
European home,'' the Berlin Wall still stands and the Brezhnev
Doctrine, which affirms the right to send Soviet troops into other
East European countries, has not been repealed.
   Baker added that the United States does not intend to sit
quietly and await the outcome of Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``Our policy must be to press forward with our agenda, to test
the application of Soviet `new thinking' again and again,'' Baker
said.
   On arms control, Baker suggested the Soviets ``come clean'' in
the conventional force talks going on in Vienna and ``engage in
careful reductions that diminish the threat to the West.''
   Baker said the administration intends to press the Soviets to
make human rights and democratization changes a permanent part of
the Soviet political system and legal code.
   ``By testing Moscow across the board, we have the opportunity to
turn many of the opportunities presented by the `new thinking' into
realities. We can establish frameworks and baselines for common
dialogue in areas where no real dialogue or basis for cooperation
now exists,'' Baker argued.
   The secretary said the administration intends to find out
``whether the `new thinking' is real once we probe beyond the
slogans ... and we can also determine where the old thinking still
holds sway.''
</TEXT>
