<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     05-04 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Welcomes Progress in Cambodian Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday praised the
progress made in talks for a political settlement in Cambodia but
said Vietnam must remove its troops for any agreement to work.
   ``We believe the concessions discussed can help achieve a
comprehensive and durable settlement to bring peace and stability
to the Cambodian people,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   The three opposition factions, led by U.S.-backed Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, met in Jakarta, Indonesia, on Tuesday and Wednesday with
the Vietnam-backed government of Cambodia led by Hun Sen. Both
sides agreed progress was made.
   ``The key remains Vietnam's total withdrawal. Hanoi should meet
its September deadline without preconditions, and under
internationally acceptable verification,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
Vietnam has promised to pull its troops out of Cambodia by
September and end a 10-year occupation.
   The State Department reaffirmed its views that once the
Vietnamese withdraw, ``Prince Sihanouk's role as a leader of an
interim coalition preceding elections remains essential.''
   The last comment appeared a response to reports that Sihanouk
told Hun Sen he would consider striking a separate deal with him if
no agreement is reached on inclusion of the Chinese-backed Khmer
Rouge in an interim government.
