<HEAD>Ten Die in Fighting Between Northern Ghanaian Tribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ACCRA, Ghana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces were sent to northeastern
Ghana to quell tribal fighting that has claimed 10 lives, police
said Thursday.
   Houses were destroyed in the fighting that broke out over the
weekend in Bimbagu village between members of the Bimoda and
Konkomba tribes.
   It was not clear what started the violence.
   Kwasi Nkansah, the regional police commander, said security
forces from Accra, Ghana's capital, were sent to the village in
East Maprusi district. Tribesmen were asked to surrender their
weapons, he said.
   The last big clash between the tribes occurred in 1985.
