<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-US     05-04 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Nicaragua Resume Exchanging Diplomats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Nicaragua said
Thursday they are about to exchange diplomats again, 10 months
after expelling each other's envoys because of an opposition march
the government ended by force.
   Jose Leon Talavera, deputy foreign minister, said the exchanges
involves diplomats below the rank of ambassador, and replacing
ambassadors will be discussed later.
   ``We don't know the reason for this sudden change of attitude''
by the United States, he said. ``It's probably their famous
carrot-and-stick policy, but this carrot is so small it takes a
magnifying glass to see it.''
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said seven U.S. diplomats were being sent to Managua, and Nicaragua
would be allowed to post the same number.
   Lois Mervin, a U.S. Embassy spokeswoman, said it was ``an
administrative move and not a change in policy.''
   Nicaragua expelled Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other
U.S. diplomats last July 11, accusing them of scheming to undermine
the Sandinista government.
   It acted the day after police broke up the opposition March in
Nandaime, 40 miles south of Managua. Scores of people were injured,
including policemen.
   Several embassy diplomats were at the march, but U.S. officials
said they had attended only as ``observers.''
   Washington retaliated by expelling Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann
and seven other Nicaraguan diplomats.
   The expulsions led to a ``visa war.'' Nicaragua began requiring
15 days notice before issuing visas to U.S. diplomats. The United
States stopped sending diplomats and refused visas to Nicaraguan
officials.
   That meant embassy staffers could not be replaced, so both
embassies have been in the hands of junior diplomats.
   Nicaragua's leftist government had offered to end the visa
restrictions on Jan. 20, inauguration day for President Bush.
   Talavera said the United States responded last weekend, telling
Nicaragua it would replace seven officials. He said they were
expected next week.
   This week, Washington ``authorized a number of visas so we could
replace our expelled people,'' Talavera said, adding that Nicaragua
would have four new diplomats at its embassy by the end of May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
