<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-China     05-04 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-China,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: I Support Demands By Chinese Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in his first public comments
on the massive pro-democracy demonstrations that have rocked China
in recent weeks, gave his ``enthusiastic backing'' to many demands
by the Chinese students.
   But the president, who served as the first U.S. liaison officer
to Beijing when the United States opened relations with China under
President Nixon, declined to specifically criticize the Chinese
government, which has sought to stop the demonstrations.
   ``I have words of encouragement for freedom and democracy,
wherever, and I would like to see progress in China, in the Soviet
Union, and in other systems that have heretofore not been in the
forefront, to put it mildly, of human rights or of democratic
rights. And I wouldn't suggest that, to any leadership of any
country, that they accept every demand by every group.''
   However, the president told a news conference on the White House
lawn that he has reviewed the demands by the hundreds of thousands
of students who have taken to the streets of Beijing and other
Chinese cities.
   ``We can certainly, as the United States, identify with them.''
   Bush mentioned the demand for press freedom and said he forgot
other specific demands, but stated, ``A lot of them had my
enthusiastic backing,in a broad, generic sense, and I would like to
encourage China or the Soviet Union or other totalitarian
countries...to move as quick as they can down democracy's path.''
   Bush said that since he lived in China in 1975, ``I`ve been
pleased with some of the changes in China. It's changed
dramatically.''
   ``But they've got a ways to go and other countries in this
hemisphere have a long ways to go, and countries in Europe have a
long way to go.''
   Bush has spoken often and forcefully in favor of the forces
opposing oppressive regimes in such places as Poland and Nicaragua,
but has been quiet on China.
   Bush's comments came as some 100,000 people occupied Beijing's
Tiananmen Square to mark the 70th anniversary of China's first
student movement.
   The crowd, mostly students, defied police and peacefully
gathered for a festive rally to seek greater freedom, cleaner
government, a free press and official recognition of the new
independent student union that authorities say is illegal.
   Students held much smaller demonstrations in Shanghai, Nanjing
and Changsha.
   China's communist leaders initially said the student marches
were designed to undermine China's government, but in recent days
has said that the demonstrators are being manipulated by
unspecified people and that most protesting students are patriotic.
   Student activists on Thursday indicated that after six
successful marches in defiance of the government, they indicated
future activity may not center on demonstrations.
</TEXT>
