<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Telecommunications     05-04 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telecommunications,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Voiced to Lifting Bell Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to lift court-imposed restrictions
on the seven regional Bell telephone companies drew opposition in a
House committee Thursday from newspaper publishers and other
telephone companies.
   The bill, co-sponsored by Reps. Al Swift, D-Wash., and Tom
Tauke, R-Iowa, would lift restraints imposed when the Bell System
was broken up by a federal consent decree in 1984.
   Those restraints prevent the regional Bell companies from
manufacturing telecommunications equipment and offering information
services such as electronic yellow pages, computer data bases and
home shopping and banking.
   Opening hearings on the legislation and new telecommunications
policy, the telecommunications subcommittee of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee heard opposition to the bill from David E.
Easterly, president of Cox Newspapers who represented the American
Newspaper Publishers Association, and William T. Esrey, president
and chief executive officer of United Telecommunications Inc. and
US Sprint Communications Co.
   Easterly said the Bell companies should remain banned from
providing electronic publishing services because as operators of
the local phone systems, they control the delivery system and have
the ability to harm competitors trying to use it to sell electronic
publishing products.
   ``The phone companies have to be banned from publishing over
their own lines,'' Easterly said.
   ``The potential for abuse is absolutely enormous,'' he said.
   William L. Weiss, chairman and chief executive officer of
Ameritech Corp., one of the local Bell companies, supported the
legislation and said the restriction on information services was
added to the consent decree ``to pacify special interest groups''
who wanted to preserve ``their competitive advantage.''
   Weiss said the real issue in their debate with newspaper
publishers is advertising, as electronic yellow pages would be in
competition with electronic classified ads that some newspapers may
want to offer via home video or computer services.
   ``We'd like to take our own business, yellow pages, and move it
forward with technology,'' Weiss said.
</TEXT>
