<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-North-Scene     05-04 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-Scene,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Leaves Quietly, But With a Smile</HEAD>
<HEAD>By LEE BYRD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver L. North left on verdict day just as he
arrived _ through the back door, shoulders squared, eyes fixed dead
ahead, no comment for public consumption. But first there was a
broad smile, and a courtroom kiss for his wife.
   She smiled, too, even as the federal jury of nine women, three
men had pronounced her husband both guilty and innocent, convicting
him on three felony counts, acquitting him on nine others.
   The jury rendered that verdict, on its 12th day of
deliberations, without casting a single glance at the defendant,
the former Vietnam war hero and Marine lieutenant colonel charged
with scheming outside of the law and White House order as the
principal action officer in the Iran-Contra affair.
   North sat impassively as U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell
read the verdict, including the findings of guilt _ falsifying and
destroying documents, accepting an illegal gratuity, and aiding and
abetting the obstruction of Congress. Then, after both judge and
jury filed solemnly from the room, North strode to wife Betsy and
they embraced.
   The couple, the North defense team and their bodyguards,
departed from the rear of the building in a gray van, their usual
practice throughout the trial. Reporters were not allowed close
enough to ask questions. Betsy waved at a small group of supporters
hoisting placards and chanting encouragement, but North did not
turn their way.
   ``Ollie, Ollie, Ollie!'' chanted the pro-North group. Their
signs read ``Oliver North, American hero,'' and ``Baseball, Hot
Dogs, Apple Pie and Ollie North.'' One member of the group, Bob
Goulder, said North ``was doing something he belived in for a
cause, which probably not one in 10 people in America do.''
   At the main entrance to the courthouse, chief trial prosecutor
John Keker, himself a former Vietnam hero, declared: ``Col. North
has been convicted of three very serious charges ... The jury has
spoken after a long and difficult trial, and the principle that no
man is above the law has been vindicated.''
   But Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., a former White House aide
for whom North campaigned last year, said the jury had found North
guilty ``of only cutting corners and not breaking the law.''
   Rohrabacher and Reps. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., and Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., had gone to the courtroom to lend support to North as the
verdict was announced, and met briefly with him afterward. North
was ``absolutely elated,'' and his wife expressed ``a true sense of
relief,'' said Rohrabacher.
   Hyde said ``I am sorry he was found guilty of anything. If the
president had been able to testify and (former National Security
Adviser John) Poindexter had been able to testify, he would have
had a fair trial.''
   ``I consider this a vindication. I considered this a political
trial from day one,'' said Rohrabacher. ``George Bush should end
this travesty and give him a pardon.''
   A hundred reporters and dozens of camera crews were stationed at
the front of the courthouse in hopes of catching North and other
key players in the trial.
   The first person to give that assemblage word of the outcome was
Dornan, R-Calif., who got the verdict wrong _ proclaiming that
North had been convicted of only two counts.
   Speaking as a ``personal friend and admirer of Col. North,''
Dornan said he didn't expect the conviction on the illegal
acceptance of a gratuity _ a security gate _ would hold up on
appeal.
   ``If that one isn't overturned on appeal, I'll eat your
microphones,'' Dornan said.
   The outside world's view of the verdict changed some 10 minutes
later when several dozen reporters scrambled out of the courtroom
itself, many to do instantaneous stand-up reports for television.
   ``Some said our system of justice could not deal fairly, if at
all, with this case,'' Keker said. ``Some even said that it
couldn't be tried.''
   Then, after noting the three felony convictions and proclaiming
vindication of the principle than no man stands above the law,
Keker said ``Thank you very much,'' and walked away, refusing all
questions.
   Soon thereafter, a scream of sirens announced the departure,
with an escort of U.S. marshals, of the jury. They weren't taking
questions, either.
</TEXT>
