<FIRST>u w AM-Koop-Highlights     05-04 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop-Highlights,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Koop, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of Dr. C. Everett Koop's
accomplishments and controversies during his seven years as surgeon
general:
   _In 1983, Koop helped write regulations designed to protect
handicapped infants by ensuring they be provided nourishment and
care. The regulations were later thrown out by the Supreme Court.
   _On May 20, 1984, Koop declared the nation's No. 1 health goal
to be a ``smoke-free society by the year 2000.''
   _On March 25, 1986, the surgeon general declared snuff and
chewing tobacco to be a ``significant health risk'' that can be
addictive and lead to cancer.
   _On Aug. 1, 1986, Koop put himself at odds with the White House
and endorsed a proposed ban on cigarette advertising in magazines,
newspapers and other publications.
   _On Oct. 22, 1986, Koop issued a report on the AIDS epidemic in
which he said use of condoms for ``safe sex'' was a key weapon in
the fight against the spread of AIDS, and supported sex education
for children as early as the third grade.
   _In a May 1988 report, the surgeon general declared nicotine to
be addictive, like heroin and cocaine, providing new ammunition for
anti-smoking forces.
   _In January 1989, Koop declined to issue a report requested by
the White House because he said there was insufficient scientific
data to determine whether abortion harms women psychologically.
</TEXT>
