<FIRST>r w AM-Cavazos-Literacy     05-04 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cavazos-Literacy,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kennedy Grills Cavazos on Litercy Funds Cutback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after delivering a report critical of
the performance of U.S. high schools, Education Secretary Lauro
Cavazos faced sharp questioning from Sen. Edward M. Kennedy about
the Bush administration's elimination of most federal literacy
programs.
   Even before Cavazos could deliver his opening statement to the
Senate Labor and Human Resources education subcommittee, Kennedy, a
Massachusetts Democrat, asked Cavazos to explain why President Bush
has asked for money to fund only one major adult literacy program
in his 1990 budget request.
   ``We have to ask ourselves how much we're really gaining ... if
we are focusing on one program and yet cutting back on others,''
said Kennedy, who heads the labor and human resources panel.
   Cavazos said his department was exercising ``a little bit of
academic deregulation'' and giving the states more flexibility in
using the available money.
   Bush has asked for $192 million in the 1990 education budget for
adult literacy programs. Experts say there are 25 million to 30
million functionally illiterate adults in the United States.
   ``You raised the adult education state grant by $24 million but
other programs are cut by $21 million,'' Kennedy said.
   ``I can't look and read this budget and think that it does very
much in terms of where the administration's commitments are because
it basically is not even a current services program,'' Kennedy
persisted in an exchange after Cavazos delivered his prepared
testimony.
   ``We look at these projects as demonstration projects. And
that's why they are not contained in our budget request for 1990,''
said D. Kay Wright, deputy assistant secretary for vocational and
adult education.
   ``We hope that after two years the states can take a look at
some of these projects and decide that they want to do similar
projects.''
   ``Then the program is effectively eliminated,'' countered
Kennedy.
   ``I think that the effort has to come across from everybody. ...
It is not just a federal problem. It's a problem that really needs
to be dealt with at every level,'' said the secretary.
</TEXT>
