<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Baseball     05-04 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baseball,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Autographs Ball for Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed the presidents' baseball
Thursday and pitched it back to the head of the Baseball Hall of
Fame for display in the Cooperstown, N.Y., museum.
   Bush autographed the ball at a White House ceremony with Hall of
Fame President Ed Stack, baseball legend Stan Musial, Musial's
granddaughter Laura, and Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y.
   ``We had a good time talking baseball,'' Boehlert said
afterward. ``We talked about ... the Texas Rangers, now in first
place in the American League.''
   Bush's son is part-owner of the Rangers.
   The baseball Bush signed is the second presidents' baseball on
display in the Hall of Fame. The first, with presidential
signatures going back to William Howard Taft, ran out of space with
the autograph of Richard Nixon, Boehlert said.
   Boehlert, a baseball fan and half-owner of the minor league
Utica Blue Sox, said Bush recently made a videotape about the sport
which is on view at the Hall of Fame in commemoration of the
museum's 50th anniversary, Boehlert said.
   Bush is a former captain of the Yale baseball team.
</TEXT>
