<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Europe     05-04 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Europe,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Negotiator Says Europe Must Reform Farm Exports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man President Bush has picked to negotiate
trade treaties for the United States said Thursday that 12 European
governments must reform the way they subsidize their agricultural
exports.
   Rufus H. Yerxa commented at Senate confirmation hearings held on
his nomination to become deputy U.S. trade representative.
   If confirmed by the Senate Finance Committee, Yerza will be the
chief U.S. negotiator in Geneva, Switzerland, where about 100
countries hope to complete trade agreements in the ``Uruguay
round'' of negotiations by the end of 1990.
   Agricultural exports will likely play a key role in the talks.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., said he had spoken last week in
Brussels, Belgium, with Ray MacSharry of Ireland, who is in charge
of agriculture for the European Commission, which handles trade for
its 12 member governments. Their European Economic Community is the
main competitor of the United States in worldwide sales of farm
products.
   The 12 European governments subsidize agricultural exports
through the community's Common Agricultural Policy. The Bush
administration opposes the subsidies, contending they put American
exports at a competitive disadvantage on the world market.
   ``The Common Agricultural Policy is one of the most distorting,
if not the most distorting, elements in agricultural trade,'' Yerxa
said. ``There will have to be a fundamental reform in it.''
   He said the United States had not yet seen what he called ``the
color of the Europeans' money'' _ that is, firm European bargaining
proposals _ on farm export subsidies.
</TEXT>
