<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Chippewas     05-04 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Chippewas,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Congressman Propose Bill To Settle Chippewa Fishing Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wisconsin's congressional delegation
introduced legislation Thursday that would revise the terms of
150-year-old Indian treaties to allow more sport fishing in the
Chippewa area of the state.
   ``The bill adapts the treaties to today's world,'' said Sen.
Robert Kasten, R-Wis.
   Many fear the dispute pitting northern Wisconsin resort owners
and sportsmen against the Indians, who have federal court approval
to begin spear fishing before fishing season opens, will turn
violent.
   Kasten and three of the state's congressmen said they were
working with Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson to restart stalled
negotiations between the Chippewas and the state.
   ``A large part of what we are trying to do is get both parties
back to the negotiating table,'' said Rep. David Obey, D-Wis. ``The
issue is whether everyone can get along.''
   Obey said he called every tribe in his district to tell them
about the legislation and ask them to cease spearing. He said the
tribes are spearing more fish than they need to feed their families
and should be willing to share with hook-and-line sportsmen.
   Kasten said he was concerned about possible confrontations
between the Indians and fishermen who say the Chippewas are robbing
the lakes of trophy size fish.
   The dispute stems from a federal court decision two years ago
that the Chippewas, under treaties negotiated in 1837 and 1842,
were guaranteed fishing rights in the territories they gave up to
the government.
   ``When the treaties were signed, Wisconsin was a wilderness,''
said Obey. ``The court opinion that caused the problem was off
base.''
   He and the others conceded that their proposed legislation may
be difficult to push through Congress.
   The bill limits the Chippewa tribes' share of the fish from any
Wisconsin lake to 10 percent of the safe harvest level, which means
the tribes would be limited primarily to ceremonial spearing, said
the congressmen.
   The legislation would allow the Indians to go to court to seek
compensation for the amount of fish they would no longer be allowed
to spear. State and federal governments would pay the costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
