<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-France     05-04 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-France,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Jewish Group Threatens French Premier with Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone caller said a radical Jewish
underground group pronounced a death sentence on the French foreign
minister Thursday for meeting with PLO chief Yasser Arafat, Israel
radio reported.
   It said the anonymous informant claimed to speak for a group
called the Sicarites, which claimed responsibility for a
submachine-gun attack April 10 in Arab east Jerusalem that killed
one Palestinian and wounded three. The assailant, clad in an army
uniform, escaped on foot and has not been caught.
   According to the radio, the caller said a Sicarite court
sentenced Roland Dumas, the foreign minister, to death for meeting
the Palestine Liberation Organization chairman on Tuesday during
Arafat's official visit to France.
   Dumas said Thursday he expected to visit Israel soon to discuss
Middle East peace prospects, but gave no indication of a date.
   The caller, who also telephoned several newspapers and the
national news agency Itim, said the Sicarites uprooted a tree
Thursday that Dumas planted in honor of his father at the Yad
Vashem Holocaust Memorial in Jerusalem.
   ``A man who shook the hand of Arafat is not allowed to desecrate
the soil of Yad Vashem in the land of Israel,'' the radio quoted
the caller as saying.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sanduri confirmed the tree honoring George
Dumas had been torn out for the second time in three months. The
foreign minister planted it during a visit to Israel in January and
it was first uprooted Feb. 2.
   Yad Vashem spokesman Menachem Fogel said: ``I think this is
stupid. ``George Dumas saved Jews and has paid with his life for
that. He has nothing to do with the deeds of his son.''
   George Dumas was a French resistance leader who saved Jews in
Limoges and was executed by the Nazis in March 1944. The Yad Vashem
institution lists him among the ``Righteous Among the Nations,'' a
title reserved for people who saved Jews from the Nazi Holocaust.
   The Sicarites are named for assassins in ancient Israel who
killed collaborators with Rome. The group also has claimed
responsibility for several arson attacks on apartments and cars of
Israelis with liberal views toward the Palestinians.
</TEXT>
