<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     05-04 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Proposes Pardons for Political Offenses Since 1980</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski proposed
Thursday that Parliament pass a blanket pardon for political
offenses committed since the original agreements of August 1980
that legalized Solidarity.
   Gen. Jaruzelski, the Communist Party chief, made the
conciliatory gesture toward the opposition in a speech opening a
two-day party conference on plans for partially democratic
elections to be held in June.
   New agreements concluded April 5 made the independent union
legal again, after a seven-year ban, in exchange for opposition
participation in the elections.
   Jaruzelski said Thursday the arrangement was a step toward
national harmony and declared:
   ``We think it purposeful to file ... a bill on pardoning and
committing to oblivion breaches of law that were politically
motivated or related to strikes or protest actions after the August
1980 agreements. We hope this initiative will contribute to
strengthening responsible democracy.''
   One of Solidarity's main demands in negotiations for the April 5
accords was an end to such penalties.
   A union spokesman said it would have no immediate comment on
Jaruzelski's proposal.
   Jan Bisztyga, spokesman for the party Central Committee, told
reporters a bill to pardon political offenders would be introduced
``soon'' but that he could not provide copies.
   In his speech, Jaruzelski also said the party is committed to
political reform and recognizes that ``constructive, realistic
opposition is a natural consequence'' of democracy.
   ``We are ahead of the major part of the opposition, which seems
to be taking a nap, because it still sees us in the old, so-called
non-reformable edition,'' he said.
   Jaruzelski said the April agreements were reached after ``a long
and bumpy road. The necessary time had to pass, emotions had to
ease and seeds of trust had to appear. It is all still fragile, but
it is awakening hopes.
   ``In any case, we are treating the cause of national accord with
utmost seriousness,'' he said. ``Constructive, realistic opposition
is a natural consequence of broadening the democratic foundations
of our state system.''
   Under the agreements, the opposition may contest 161 seats, or
35 percent of the total in the Sejm, the existing unicameral
parliament. A 100-member Senate is to be established, chosen by
fully democratic elections.
   The Sejm and Senate together will form the National Assembly,
which will elect a president. The presidency is a new office and
Jaruzelski is expected to fill it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
