<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-JapanAid     05-04 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan Aid,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Expertise Sought for Japanese Aid Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American engineers, builders, suppliers and
development experts have an opportunity to earn some of the
trillions of yen Japan plans to pour into overseas economic aid,
U.S. aid chief Alan Woods said Thursday.
   Japan, about to replace the United States as the world's largest
foreign aid donor, is interested in making use of U.S. expertise,
said Woods, head of the U.S. Agency for International Development.
   Britain has already responded to the Japanese desire for expert
collaboration and ``the British have become procurement agents for
the Japanese aid agency throughout East Africa,'' he said.
   Japan plans to spend $50 billion on overseas economic aid in the
next five years, with the emphasis on building dams, power
stations, roads, railways, and factories, AID officials said.
American aid in recent years has shifted from such major capital
projects to technical assistance, they said.
   Foreign firms are already increasing their share of contracts in
the Japanese aid program, but the U.S. share is dropping, strongly
suggesting ``that the competitive environment has become more
favorable but that potential America bidders are not widely aware
of it,'' an AID announcement said.
   Woods announced that AID is sponsoring conferences in San
Francisco on May 10-ll and Orlando, Fla., on May 15-16 to help
American enterprises learn about opportunities in the Japanese
overseas development program. Officials from three Japanese aid
agencies will participate in both meetings, the first such sessions
ever held, he said.
   The Japanese have only about 200 foreign aid specialists and
appear eager to draw on the experience of more than 2,000 Americans
working on AID programs, Woods said.
   There is no formal agreement on collaboration between the two
countries' agencies, Woods said.
   But foreign participation in Japanese-financed programs outside
Japan is governed by conditions different from those for Japanese
domestic projects, where difficult negotiations were held last year
to gain access for U.S. contractors, he added.
   Japanese aid has thus far chiefly been sent to other Asian
nations.
</TEXT>
