<HEAD>Eds: SUBS COLUMBIA, S.C.-dated 1st item to UPDATE with details of
Jackson visit.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson paid James Brown a
belated 56th birthday visit in prison Thursday, and later asked
that the soul music legend be allowed to give a television
interview to the French government.
   ``James Brown's musical contribution has earned him that
honor,'' Jackson said after meeting with Brown for an hour and 40
minutes at the State Park Correctional Center.
   Brown is serving a six-year sentence for aggravated assault and
failing to stop for police during a chase across the Georgia-South
Carolina border on Sept. 26.
   The French Ministry of Culture asked for the interview through
Los Angeles record producer Quincy Jones as part of France's
bicentennial celebration. Quincy in turn asked Jackson for help.
Jackson forwarded the request to Gov. Carroll Campbell and
corrections officials.
   Campbell has no authority in such matters, and deferred to the
corrections department, said a Campbell spokesman, Tucker Eskew.
   The commissioner of the South Carolina Department of
Corrections, Parker Evatt, was out of town and would not hear the
request until Monday, said corrections spokesman Bennish Brown, who
is not related to the singer.
   Brown, the self-proclaimed ``Godfather of Soul,'' did not have
any visitors on his birthday Wednesday, the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
