<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-California-Nuclear     05-04 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-California-Nuclear,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Cites Increased Accident Risk At Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The risk of serious safety lapses at a
Sacramento, Calif., nuclear plant is increasing with the approach
of a local referendum on whether to close the troubled plant, a
city utility official told a Senate panel on Thursday.
   ``The potential for employees to be pressured to keep the plant
operating even during adverse circumstances is high,'' said Ed
Smeloff, a member of the board of directors of the Sacramento
Municipal Utility District, owner of the Rancho Seco plant.
   Residents in the utility district are scheduled to vote June 6
on whether the plant should be closed permanently.
   Smeloff's remarks were disputed in later testimony by Lando W.
Zech Jr., chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which has
spent more time over the last three years inspecting Rancho Seco
than any of the 109 other U.S. nuclear reactors.
   ``The stressful environment for Rancho Seco workers has not
resulted in unsafe nuclear plant operations and the commission
concludes that Rancho Seco has been, and can continue to be,
operated safely,'' Zech told a Senate Environment and Public Works
subcomittee that is investigating NRC oversight of Rancho Seco.
   The plant has come under increased scrutiny since an
industry-sponsored safety group, the Institute of Nuclear Power
Operations, issued a report April 4 that sharply criticized the
plant's performance record and the utility district's management.
   The institute's president, Zack T. Pate, told the subcommittee
his group is still concerned about the terms of the June
referendum. The utility agreed last summer that if it failed during
an 18-month trial period starting last June, to operate at a
minimum of 40 percent of capacity, it would shut permanently.
   Smeloff said that since last December the plant has operated at
less than 40 percent of capacity. The average performance rating
for all U.S. nuclear plants is about 60 percent.
   Pate said pressure to meet the 40 percent target could cause
some plant workers to discard normal caution in order to save the
plant, and thus their jobs.
</TEXT>
