<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldDebt     05-04 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compromise Urged on Mexican Debt Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The architect of the Bush administration's
Third World debt plan urged Mexico and U.S. commercial banks on
Thursday to speed up their talks on reducing Mexico's debt burden
and implied that both sides would have to shift their positions.
   ``We are going to press all parties ... to move quickly,'' David
C. Mulford, Treasury undersecretary-designate for international
affairs, told the Senate Finance Committee.
   Asked by Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., whether the banks holding
Mexico's debt should be more willing to bend, he said, ``I have no
doubt the position taken by the banks is their first visible
negotiating position.''
   However, he added, ``It takes two to tango in that case'' and
said Mexico should make proposals that ``are seen as realistic.''
   Mulford is the chief architect of President Bush's new
initiative to relieve the crushing, $1.2 trillion debt burden on
developing countries, particularly in Latin America.
   Bush's Treasury secretary, Nicholas F. Brady, is calling on
banks, assisted by the World Bank and International Monetary Fund,
to forgive a portion of the debt _ a shift from the Reagan
administration's policy of adamantly opposing any broad-based debt
reduction plan.
   As one of the first tests of the new strategy, representatives
of large banks and Mexico have been meeting in New York to discuss
Mexico's proposal for about $4 billion in relief, either through
reduced interest rates or further loans.
   The Finance Committee recommended that the full Senate approve
the nominations of Mulford and two other top Treasury Department
officials, Deputy Secretary-designate John E. Robson, who would be
the department's No. 2 official, and Robert R. Glauber, nominated
to be undersecretary for finance. Glauber and Mulford would be
considered the No. 3 and No. 4 officials in the department.
   Robson was formerly dean of the business school at Emory
University in Atlanta and, before that, president and chief
executive officer of the pharmaceutical firm, G.D. Searle &amp; Co., in
Skokie, Ill.
   Glauber, a professor at the Harvard Business School, has been
serving as a consultant to the Treasury Department since October
and is one of the main authors of Bush's savings and loan bailout.
Earlier, he was staff director of President Reagan's task force to
study the 1987 stock market crash.
   Mulford has been assistant secretary of the Treasury since 1984.
   The committee also recommended the nominations of Rufus H.
Yerxa, an aide on the House Ways and Means Committee, as deputy
U.S. trade representative, and Eric I. Garfinkel, an attorney, as
assistant secretary of commerce for import administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
