<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Yugoslav     05-04 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Yugoslav,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Jailed In Scotland For Attack On Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUNFERMLINE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav alleged to be a major in
his country's secret police was convicted Thursday of trying to
murder a dissident emigre and sentenced to 15 years in prison.
   Vinklo Sindicic pleaded innocent to the charge of trying to
murder Nikola Stedul with a silenced pistol outside Stedul's home
in Scotland, and denied the prosecution's allegations that he was
in the secret police. Stedul survived wounds to the head and body.
   A High Court jury in Dunfermline found Sindicic guilty after an
11-day trial.
   Lord Allanbridge, the presiding judge, said in passing sentence
the 46-year-old defendant made a ``callous, calculated and
carefully planned attempt'' to murder Stedul.
   Stedul, 51, left Yugoslavia as a young man to avoid military
service and has lived in Scotland for 14 years. He is president of
the Croatian Movement for Statehood, which seeks independence for
Croatia, one of communist Yugoslavia's six republics.
   He told the court he was certain the shooting last Oct. 20 was
ordered by Yugoslav authorities for political reasons.
   Sindicic said he was making telephone calls to Yugoslavia at the
time of the shooting in Kirkcaldy, just north of Edinburgh. A
neighbor of the victim noted the license plate number of the car
from which the shots were fired and it was traced to Sindicic.
   After the verdict, Stedul said: `I think this trial has proven
beyond any doubt that Yugoslavia is involved in state terrorism,
and I think this is probably more importart than today's
conviction.''
   He claimed Sindicic was involved in murders in other countries
and that Yugoslav agents had killed 70 people in foreign countries
since 1969.
   Stedul, whose wife and two daughters were with him, said he felt
``a little bit safer'' with Sindicic in jail, but ``I don't believe
we will ever lead a normal life.''
   Croatian exiles have reported several attacks in recent years in
Europe and Australia.
   Croat leader Branko Jelic survived a bombing in West Berlin, and
Josip Senic, leader of the Croatian Revolutionary Brotherhood, was
shot to death in his bed in West Germany.
</TEXT>
