<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Younger     05-04 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Younger,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former California Attorney General Evelle Younger Dies at 70</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former California Attorney General Evelle
Younger, who as a tough district attorney oversaw prosecution of
Charles Manson and Robert Kennedy's assassin Sirhan Sirhan, died at
home Thursday. He was 70.
   Police were called to Younger's Hollywood home at 8:30 a.m. and
found him dead, apparently of natural causes, said Officer Bill
Frio. His wife, Mildred, and son, Superior Court Judge Eric
Younger, were there when police arrived.
   Younger served eight years as state attorney general and won the
Republican nomination for governor in 1978 after careers as an FBI
agent, deputy city attorney, city prosecutor, municipal and
superior court judge, and district attorney.
   Younger was proud of being ``a double general,'' serving as a
general in the Air Force Reserve at the same time he was attorney
general.
   Those multiple titles were indirectly a political liability, as
his multiple pensions _ $53,226 annually from separate municipal,
judicial, state and military funds _ became a crippling campaign
issue.
   Younger was trounced by more than a million votes by incumbent
Democrat Edmund G. ``Jerry'' Brown in the gubernatorial election.
   ``Evelle Younger served the people of California with great
dedication and distinction,'' said former President Ronald Reagan,
who was governor of California during the first of Younger's two
terms as attorney general.
   Younger was also chief of Reagan's Task Force on Administration
of Justice.
   ``He was a loyal member of our team whose wisdom, common sense
and commitment to the cause of good government contributed much to
the betterment of our state,'' Reagan said.
   During Younger's six-year tenure as Los Angeles County district
attorney, Sirhan was tried and convicted for the June 1968
assassination of U.S. Sen. Robert Kennedy. His office also brought
the first indictments against Manson and his followers for the
August 1969 Tate-LaBianca slayings.
   ``His work as a district attorney and as attorney general set
standards of hard work, ethics and dedication that many have been
hard pressed to follow,'' said U.S. Sen. Pete Wilson in Washington,
D.C.
   After losing the gubernatorial election, Younger in 1979 became
a senior partner in the law firm of Buchalter, Nemer, Fields and
Chrystie.
   Younger was born June 19, 1918, in Stamford, Neb., and graduated
from the law school at the University of Nebraska at Lincoln in
1940. He joined the FBI. His first assignment was New York, where
he met his future wife.
   In 1953, Gov. Earl Warren appointed Younger, then a prosecutor
for the city of Pasadena, to the Municipal Court bench. In 1958, he
was elected to the Los Angeles County Superior Court and in 1964 he
was elected Los Angeles County district attorney. He won his first
terms as attorney general in 1970.
   In 1968, he headed President-elect Richard Nixon's Crime and Law
Enforcement Task Force. Four years later, he directed the
California delegation for Nixon to Miami Beach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
