<FIRST>r a AM-AdvertiserPullouts     05-04 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Advertiser Pullouts,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advertisers Taking Second Look at Shocking `Reality' Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Scandals II'' has become the second ABC
special in a week to be dropped for lack of commercial interest,
but NBC said Thursday a delay of the TV movie ``The Prize
Pulitzer'' was not a victim of advertiser angst.
   Pressure groups responding to this season's plethora of
``reality-based'' programs _ created in response to last summer's
writers' strike _ have caused advertisers to think twice before
associating themselves with stories of devil worship, brutal crime
and sex scandal.
   Both ``Scandals II'' and last week's ``Crimes of Passion II,''
also pulled for lack of advertisers, were sequels to specials that
had racked up decent ratings, if not critical acclaim, earlier this
season.
   When ABC tried to sell the second batch in a low-rated Saturday
time period this month, no advertisers wanted to buy time.
   USA Today reported Thursday that NBC had also dropped ``The
Prize Pulitzer,'' a TV movie based on Roxanne Pulitzer's
sensationalistic biography, for similar reasons. But NBC spokesman
Curt Block denied the report.
   The decision to put off ``The Prize Pulitzer'' until next season
was made in January and is unrelated to any bailout of advertisers,
Block said.
   ``It is not in response to `Crimes of Passion' and `Scandals'
and these things that we made this move,'' he said. ``Rolling over
(delaying) to the next season is something all the networks do all
of the time.''
   The delay of ``The Prize Pulitzer'' was announced in a March 22
news release that also mentioned a Perry Mason movie and two other
made-for-TV films that were being delayed until next season, Block
said.
   In a statement on the ``Scandals II'' move, ABC Entertainment
President Robert Iger said the network was ``considering the
appropriate role for reality-based programming on our schedule. In
the interim we will consider each program on a case-by-case basis.''
   ``Crimes of Passion II'' was replaced by two half-hour comedy
pilots that wound up in the bottom five in the Nielsens. A one-hour
drama will likely replace ``Scandals II'' this Saturday, said ABC
spokesman Jim Brochu in Los Angeles.
   The first ``Scandals'' program was one of several fact-based
shows created after last year's strike by scriptwriters. Such
``reality-based'' programming was not subject to the Writers Guild
of America contract and provided a stop-gap until regular
programming could resume.
   NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries'' enjoys continued healthy ratings.
So did a Geraldo Rivera special about Satan worship which aired on
NBC, though it was attacked for lurid content. NBC said that
despite high ratings, the network lost money on the special because
of advertiser pullout.
   In recent weeks, advertisers have pulled commercials from NBC's
``Saturday Night Live'' and ``Nightingales'' and have expressed
concern about the Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``Married ... With
Children,'' though its commercial time was sold out for the rest of
the season.
   SNL was criticized for a sketch that involved repeated use of
the word ``penis.'' ``Nightingales'' has been blasted by nursing
groups for its cheesecake depictions of the nursing profession.
   ``Married ... With Children'' is a decidedly raunchy
counterpunch to sitcoms such as ``The Cosby Show.'' It is Fox's
highest-rated show _ next to ``America's Most Wanted,'' which asks
viewers to help solve re-enacted, real-life crimes.
</TEXT>
