<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unions     05-04 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unions,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Official Says Workers Will Gain Right to Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's highest ranking union official says
that under new laws, labor unions in the Soviet Union will have the
right to strike to back up their demands.
   Stepan A. Shalaev, chairman of the Central Council of Trade
Unions, made it clear, however, that the council does not envision
strikes becoming common.
   ``The decision to stop work at an enterprise _ this is an
extreme measure to be taken only in extreme circumstances,'' he
said in an interview published Wednesday the labor newspaper Trud.
   He said that unions ``must have the right to stop work at
enterprises, in organizations and institutions as a means of
pressure on the administration for speeding up the resolution of
labor disputes.''
   New regulations are included in a draft law published Saturday
and will be discussed by the unions for the next three months,
Shalaev said. The Supreme Soviet parliament will have to approve
the legislation.
   Shalaev said unions will be free of government interference in
organization and financial activity and local union officials will
be independent of the administration of the factory or office where
they work.
   Workers must be protected from losing their jobs because of
union activity, he added.
   The laws are aimed at awakening the unions from decades of quiet
subservience to the Communist Party and government. The legislation
granting unions a limited right to strike appears to be an effort
to keep labor unrest from reaching the point that led to formation
in Poland of the Solidarity free trade union federation.
   Labor unrest has spread in certain industries, notably mining,
as President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's economic reforms take hold and
greater openness encourages Soviets to speak out on issues
affecting them.
   Soviet unions are not now permitted to strike by law, and
instead are quiet partners with management and the Communist Party.
In Communist ideology, strikes are viewed as a Western phenomenon
arising from management's exploitation of workers.
   Soviet unions traditionally have done nothing to advance
employees' wage and work condition demands, but busied themselves
instead with building and organizing housing for union members,
operating vacation facilities for members and the like. The law
gives unions wider rights over distribution of housing and other
local issues such as ecological protection, Shalaev said.
</TEXT>
