<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     05-04 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: Vietnam Made Mistake in Not Condemning Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister was quoted
Thursday as saying his country erred when it did not immediately
condemn the communist Khmer Rouge, which killed hundreds of
thousands of Cambodians in 1975-1978.
   Despite the mistake, Nguyen Co Thach said in an interview in the
Bangkok Post, Vietnam corrected itself when it invaded Cambodia in
late 1978 and ousted the Khmer Rouge government.
   Thach spoke in Bangkok Wednesday before returning to Hanoi, the
newspaper said.
   Vietnam's communists helped form the Cambodian Communist Party
and gave military aid and direction to the Khmer Rouge, whose
insurgents won a five-year civil war and overthrew the U.S.-backed
Lon Nol government in April 1975.
   Over the next three years and eight months, the Khmer Rouge
killed hundreds of thousands of people in torture chambers and
slave labor camps in its attempt to fashion an agrarian society
along communist lines.
   After Thach condemned the crimes of the Khmer Rouge, led by Pol
Pot, the interviewer said: ``But the Vietnamese did not condemn Pol
Pot before.''
   ``Yes, it is our mistake,'' Thach was quoted as saying. ``But we
have corrected our mistake by military means.''
   Vietnam did nothing until 1978, when it invaded Cambodia
following border attacks in which the Khmer Rouge killed thousands
of Vietnamese villagers.
   ``And now, what is the position of the Western countries?''
Thach was quoted as saying. ``They condemn them only by words, not
by deeds. And when we condemn them by force, they condemn Vietnam,
so it is a pity.''
   Some Asian and Western nations say the Khmer Rouge must be part
of a future coalition government because it might otherwise try to
take power by military means. Some reports have said the guerrillas
have stocked up arms for an all-out offensive after Vietnam
completes its promised troop withdrawal in September.
   Hun Sen, premier of the Vietnamese-installed government in
Cambodia, tried to rule out any future role for the Khmer Rouge at
this week's talks in Indonesia with resistance leaders Prince
Norodom Sihanouk and Son Sann.
   The two non-communist leaders are allied with the Khmer Rouge in
the resistance coalition. They say they hate the Khmer Rouge but
need its 30,000 to 40,000 guerrillas.
   In Washington, the United States praised the progress made in
the latest round of talks in Jakarta, Indonesia, but said Vietnam
must pull its troops out for any agreement to work.
   ``We believe the concessions discussed can help achieve a
comprehensive and durable settlement to bring peace and stability
to the Cambodian people,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   ``The key remains Vietnam's total withdrawal. Hanoi should meet
its September deadline without preconditions, and under
internationally acceptable verification,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Thach also welcomed the results of the talks in Indonesia.
   ``Now is is clear they have made some progress, to have
appropriate reconciliation, formula and mechanism on the basis of
the reality in Kampuchea (Cambodia),'' he was quoted as saying. ``I
think it is a good direction.''
   The State Department reaffirmed its views that once the
Vietnamese withdraw, ``Prince Sihanouk's role as a leader of an
interim coalition preceding elections remains essential.''
   That comment appeared a response to reports that Sihanouk told
Hun Sen he would consider striking a separate deal with him if no
agreement is reached on inclusion of the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge
in an interim government.
</TEXT>
