<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0470 05-04 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Say How U.S. Might React to Fraudulent Electon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Senate action in grafs 2-3, senators' comments
in 4 grafs after 11th graf pvs, His call</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday ``the world will
be looking'' to see if there is government fraud in Panama's
elections Sunday. But he declined to say if he would reconsider
relinquishing control of the Panama Canal should the elections not
be ``free and fair.''
   The Senate voted 100-0 to approve a resolution condemning any
attempts by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to manipulate the election
process and insisting that ``the Noriega regime conduct the
election in a free and fair manner.''
   Bush, at a White House news conference with Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney, called on the Panamanian people to do what
they can to pressure Noriega and his powerful military forces to
hold fair elections.
   Noriega is not a candidate in Sunday's election, but has an ally
running for president and is seen as the country's de facto ruler.
   Bush declined to answer directly when asked about a comment by
House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich that Americans will not
tolerate turning over the canal to a Noriega regime.
   The United States has signed a treaty under which the
U.S.-controlled canal will come under Panama's jurisdiction at the
end of the cetury.
   Bush said, ``My view on that is to warn Panama that the world
will be looking at them, not just the United States, in terms of
these elections, deciding what to do if the elections are
fraudulent, calling on them for free and fair elections.''
   As to what moves he might have in mind to follow up the
rhetorical attacks he has been making on Noriega and the Panamanian
electoral process, Bush said:
   ``There will be international observers there and then we'll
cross whatever hypothetical bridge we may have to cross later on.
   ``But this does give me an opportunity to say that I have been
very disturbed by the reports that the election will be less than
free and less that fair and less than open.
   ``I simply want ... to encourage the people in Panama to do
everything they can to guarantee free and fair elections. And what
pressures they can bring to bear on ... Mr. Noriega, I don't know.''
   His call appeared to be a subtle urging to Panamanian opposition
forces to reinvigorate the energetic anti-Noriega protests that
were prevalent in Panama last year.
   In the Senate, Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said the
United States ``cannot much longer tolerate Noriega's corrupt,
reckless and repressive rule in Panama.''
   ``We cannot much longer permit vital U.S. interests _ including
the Panama Canal and the U.S. Southern Command _ to remain squarely
in Noriega's gunsights,'' Dole said.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the resolution puts the
Senate strongly on record as demanding ``an end to the continuing
trauma of Gen. Noriega's rule of repression.''
   The Senate resolution also called on Bush to report to Congress
on the fairness of the elections and to ``consult with Congress on
the future course of action for United States foreign policy in
Panama.''
   One administration official noted that since the street
demonstrations have died down, it is more difficult for the United
States to spur internal momentum to remove Noriega.
   Gingrich suggested after he and a group of Republican
congressional leaders met with Bush on Thursday morning that
continued domination of Panama by Noriega could jeopardize the 1979
treaties under which the United States agreed to turn over the
canal to Panamanian control in 1999.
   Administration officials have indicated, however, that treading
such ground is a risky area, and one that is not high among the
options the administration is considering.
   U.S. credibility, particularly in Latin America, would be
seriously damaged if the government backed out of the treaty,
officials have said.
   Bush and his advisers have been weighing a series of options for
what policy to employ toward Panama after a fraudulent election.
   They have declined to say what they are looking at, only that
all options are being considered, including involving U.S. allies
in isolating Noriega.
   The United States has a substantial military force based in
Panama.
   Bush this week is sending a team of observers to represent his
administration at Sunday's elections.
   It was not known how the observers will be received by Noriega,
who has sought to limit the number of private observers allowed in
for the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
