<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial-Analysis     05-04 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial-Analysis,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Verdict Gives Something to Both Sides</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The verdict in Oliver L. North's Iran-Contra
trial gave both sides credible claims to partial victory in the
grueling battle for the jury's votes.
   ``You can't say at this juncture that either side walked away
with their theory intact,'' said Washington attorney Lawrence
Barcella.
   Although North stands convicted of three felony charges, the
jury acquitted him of all the charges that he lied to Congress _
including an allegation that he falsely answered lawmakers'
questions during a face-to-face meeting.
   ``There is something there for everyone,'' said Washington
attorney Richard Ven-Veniste, a former Watergate prosecutor.
   Throughout the case, prosecutors for independent counsel
Lawrence E. Walsh argued that North's lies to Congress cut to the
heart of the democratic process by subverting the government's
reliance on truth.
   But jurors cleared the former presidential aide of these
charges, accepting North's denials that he helped prepare false
statements. Jurors also apparently accepted North's explanation
that when he did participate in fabrications, it was on orders from
superiors.
   The jury's verdict on these counts was the worst defeat for
Walsh, whose office has spent $16 million investigating and
prosecuting North and the other Iran-Contra defendants.
   After dropping charges that North conspired to illegally divert
U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels, Walsh was
left with a case that North lied, cheated and stole money.
   Ben-Veniste noted that North was cleared of lies to Congress
that allegedly took place while the Contra resupply operation was
still secret but convicted him of destroying documents and aiding
and abetting obstruction of a congressional inquiry once the affair
was publicly known.
   ``I think perhaps they drew a distinction between the potential
for jeopardizing lives and assets while the mission was still
secret and what occurred after public revelations,'' Ben-Veniste
said.
   North himself appeared quite elated by the jury's verdicts
moments after it was announced in court. He gave his wife Betsy a
broad smile before kissing her.
   Later, the retired Marine lieutenant colonel called the verdict
a ``partial vindiction'' and vowed in his soldierly way to fight
``for as long as it takes to prevail.''
   The jury's decision that North illegally destroyed National
Security Council documents and aided and abetted the obstruction of
the first congressional inquiry into the Iran-Contra affair was a
vindication for the prosecution.
   Lead prosecutor John Keker, noting that North stood ``convicted
of three serious felony charges,'' insisted the result showed that
``the principle that no man is above the law has been vindicated.''
   Nevertheless, the jury rejected the prosecution notion that
North was a thief, acquitting him of a charge that he converted
$4,300 worth of travelers checks given to him by Contra leaders to
his personal use.
   It did find that North illegally accepted a gratuity when he let
arms dealer Richard V. Secord build a security system outside his
suburban Virginia home.
   North's admission that he fabricated proof that he had paid for
the security system probably showed to the jury that he understood
what he had done was wrong.
   Testimony by former national security adviser Robert C.
McFarlane about North's alleged role in the preparation of written
responses to inquiries from various House committees was equivocal,
at best.
   North told jurors he wanted to invoke executive privilege and
refuse to answer one query.
   In another case, he said he edited a letter but didn't have any
authority to make any substantive changes.
   North admitted he lied to members of the House Intelligence
Committee on Aug. 6, 1986 but told jurors that he only attended the
meeting at the insistence of his boss, then-national security John
Poindexter.
   ``You can't really tell from the verdict whether they rejected
the authorization defense or not,'' Barcella said. ``It appears to
be a very fact-bound decision.''
   The jury appeared to reject the authorization defense when it
convicted North of aiding and abetting the obstruction of Congress
in November, 1986 when a false chronology of the U.S.-Iran
arms-for-hostages deals was prepared for lawmakers.
   ``One could hardly say this was a jury that had it in for Ollie
North,'' Ben-Veniste said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>---</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eds: James Rowley covered the Iran-Contra investigation and
helped cover the North trial
</TEXT>
