<FIRST>r w AM-SpottedOwl     05-04 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service To Push Its Spotted Owl Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Forest Service will propose in
upcoming talks that its controversial plan for preserving spotted
owl habitat in the Northwest be implemented while the bird is under
consideration for listing as a threatened species, a top agency
official said Thursday.
   The plan has been widely criticized by environmentalists, who
say it is inadequate to ensure the survival of the owl, and the
timber industry, which believes it locks up too much of the forests
to logging.
   A federal judge in Seattle has banned sales involving nearly 1
billion board feet of ancient timber in the Northwest's national
forests while he considers a court challenge to the Forest
Service's plan.
   In related developments Thursday, the Forest Service said it has
identified potential sales involving roughly 280 million board feet
of timber that could be substituted for sales currently enjoined.
The sales would involve so called ``thinning'' operations with
trees in the 50-year-old to 70-year-old range. Some of the sales
could be offered by late summer.
   And Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., said efforts are underway to bring
together the Oregon and Washington congressional delegations to
discuss the spotted owl situation.
   George Leonard, associate chief of the Forest Service, said in
an interview that implementation of his agency's plan to protect
spotted owl habitat will ``allow us to get on to some semblance of
a timber sale program.
   ``We want to get the Fish and Wildlife Service to agree that our
spotted owl habitat plan could be used for a couple of years.''
   The agency's plan would set aside between 1,000 and 2,700 acres
for each of the estimated 2,000 breeding pairs of spotted owls in
the region.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service proposed last week that the owl,
thought to live almost exclusively in the old-growth forests of
Washington, Oregon and northern California, should be listed as a
threatened species under the Endangered Species Act.
   Under the act, the Fish and Wildlife Service has up to two years
to decide whether the owl should officially be listed and to
develop management plans to protect it.
   Leonard said during those two years, implementation of the
Forest Service's owl plan would ``allow us to follow through on the
sales program we have planned. And we think it ensures the
viability of the owl.''
   The Forest Service, Bureau of Land Management and the National
Park Service has requested a ``conference'' with the Fish and
Wildlife Service to discuss the short-term impact of the proposed
listing of the bird.
   Leonard said Secretary of Interior Manuel Lujan and Secretary of
Agriculture Clayton Yeutter also will meet next week to discuss the
spotted owl. The Forest Service is part of the Agriculture
Department and the Bureau of Land Management part of the Interior
Department.
   Environmentalists said they were ``disappointed'' with the
Forest Service's decision to push its plan.
   ``It's odd that the agency remains entrenched around a plan that
has been widely discredited,'' said Jay Watson, who handles
national forest issues for The Wilderness Society. ``It seemed like
we were moving away from that type of statement and starting
afresh.''
   Leonard warned that if logging were banned in all spotted owl
habitat, timber sales in the national forests of the Northwest
would be cut by about half in the short term and about one-third
over the long term.
   In addition, Leonard said the domestic supply of softwood lumber
would be diminished by between 10 and 15 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
