<FIRST>r a AM-JacobsPlea     05-04 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jacobs Plea,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Activist Sentenced To Six Years In Plea Bargain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DROSCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two Indian activists charged in
the takeover of a newspaper last year pleaded guilty to 14 counts
of second-degree kidnapping and was sentenced to six years in
prison Thursday.
   Timothy Jacobs, 20, had faced up to 420 years in prison on 14
counts of first-degree kidnapping before he agreed to a plea
bargain with Robeson County District Attorney Robert Townsend.
   ``There have been attempts by some to portray Timothy Jacobs as
the victim in this case,'' Townsend said. ``But I don't want anyone
in this courtroom to leave today thinking that. The hostages and
their families were the victims.''
   Jacobs and Eddie Hatcher held at least 14 people hostage in The
Robesonian newsroom in Lumberton for 10 hours on Feb. 1, 1988. They
carried shotguns when they entered and chained shut the newspaper's
front door.
   The Indians said they took over the newspaper to draw attention
to allegations of official corruption and drug trafficking in the
county. A task force appointed by Gov. Jim Martin found no evidence
to support the allegations.
   ``If Timothy Jacobs suffered, so be it,'' Townsend told the
crowded courtroom. ``He has brought it about himself. It's an
insult to all races to think that Timothy Jacobs' efforts have
brought changes in Robeson County.''
   The southeastern North Carolina county is one-third white,
one-third black and one-third Indian, primarily members of the
Lumbee tribe.
   ``I was very satisified with the sentencing,'' said Deborah
Adams, one of the hostages. ``I felt he did deserve to spend some
time ... but not 30 years in prison. The last thing I've heard out
of him is he may be trying to change from last year. I hope that's
true.''
   ``He wants to get on with his life and do something with
himself,'' said his mother, Eleanor Jacobs, after the court
appearance. ``It was his decision (to plea bargain). I didn't talk
him into anything.''
   Jacobs' six-year prison term will be followed by a six-year
suspended sentence with supervised probation.
   Superior Court Judge Anthony Brannon ruled that if any books or
movies are produced about the takeover, any money earned by Jacobs
will be forfeited to the victims of the takeover. Court documents
list 14 Robesonian employees as the people detained, but
authorities said up to 20 had been held at various times the night
of the siege.
   The judge also allowed Jacobs to be free for 30 days on bond
despite objections from Townsend. Asked what he would do during the
30-day leave, Jacobs told reporters, ``Enjoy myself. ... Sign a
movie contract.''
   Hatcher, 31, is being held in a San Francisco jail under $1
million bond and has an extradition hearing scheduled for Friday.
   Both Hatcher and Jacobs fled after the 1988 state indictments,
which followed their acquittal on federal charges. Jacobs escaped
to a Madison County, N.Y., Indian reservation, and Hatcher sought
refuge on an Idaho reservation.
   Hatcher later asked the Soviet consulate in San Francisco for
political asylum but his plea was rejected and authorities arrested
him.
</TEXT>
