<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mine Kills 2 Members of Israeli-Sponsored Militia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of an Israeli-sponsored
militia were killed Thursday when their armored personnel carrier
hit a mine in Israel's south Lebanon ``security zone,'' police
reported.
   A police statement said said the mine explosion occurred near
Khiyam, 2 miles north of the Israeli border.
   The 2,500-member militia helps Israeli soldiers patrol the zone,
which ranges in depth from 6 to 10 miles and was established when
Israel withdrew from Lebanon in 1985 after three years of invasion
and occupation.
   Voice of the South, a radio station operated by the
predominantly Christian militia, said a militia patrol captured a
guerrilla in the no-man's land that separates the Syrian-controlled
Bekaa Valley town of Hasbaya from the eastern flank of the security
zone.
   It said guerrilla was ``among a group that tried to infiltrate
into the security zone,'' but provided no further identification. A
patrol ``encircled the group and arrested one of the
infiltrators,'' the radio said.
