<FIRST>r a AM-EspionagePlea     05-04 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Espionage Plea,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Sailor Gets 12 Years For Espionage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Atlantic Fleet Sailor of the Year
pleaded guilty to espionage Thursday and was sentenced to 12 years
in prison.
   Craig Dee Kunkle, 39, of Virginia Beach, was arrested Jan. 10 in
a Williamsburg motel by two FBI agents posing as representatives of
the Soviet Union. The former chief petty officer took $5,000 for
telling the agents anti-submarine warfare secrets, evidence showed.
   ``I realize I made a serious mistake and I am not proud of my
actions,'' Kunkle told U.S. District Judge Robert G. Doumar. ``I
was born an American. I'm proud to be an American. God willing,
I'll die one,'' he said.
   Doumar imposed the 12-year sentence agreed upon by prosecutors
and Kunkle's attorneys. The judge also ordered Kunkle to pay $550
in fines and court costs and placed him on three years supervised
probation after his release.
   ``Any attempt to reveal secret or top-secret information to a
foreign government places in jeopardy the lives of the people,''
the judge said. ``It cannot be tolerated.''
   Doumar said Kunkle's attempt at espionage was unsophisticated
and caused little damage to national security.
   U.S. Attorney Henry E. Hudson said Kunkle told the agents what
he remembered about the Navy's acoustic intelligence techniques and
did not pass any classified documents.
   ``While there was harm to the national security, it was not
significant,'' Hudson told reporters. ``His motivation was greed.''
   Court records indicate that Kunkle had a history of alcohol and
cocaine abuse and received a less-than-honorable discharge from the
Navy.
   Kunkle's attorney, Gregory N. Stillman, said Kunkle pleaded
guilty because he did not want to subject his family to a trial.
   Kunkle, who was working as a security guard before his arrest,
entered the Navy in 1974 and was named Atlantic Fleet Sailor of the
Year in 1977. He worked as an anti-submarine warfare specialist
before he left the Navy in 1985.
   Kunkle called the Soviet Embassy in Washington late last year.
An FBI agent posing as a Soviet official called him back and had
Kunkle mail him information at an Alexandria post office box.
   The FBI secretly videotaped a Williamsburgt meeting and got
Kunkle to sign a receipt for his $5,000 payment.
   Kunkle's father is a retired Navy commander and his brother is
an active-duty commander.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
