<DOCNO> AP890504-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     05-04 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pontiff Offers Sympathy To AIDS Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELINDA HAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Thursday offered
words of consolation for those dying of AIDS and urged Christians
of different churches to support each other.
   ``If we cannot at this point agree on all matters, we can and
must avoid all forms of competition and rivalry,'' the pope said.
   The Pope made his plea in Lusaka, Zambia, at an ecumenical
gathering of Christians attended by three top leaders of the
African National Congress, the main guerrilla movement fighting
South Africa's apartheid system of racial separation.
   He then traveled to this British colony for the final leg of his
four-nation pilgrimage to African and Indian Ocean countries.
   In Blantyre, the pope was greeted by President-for-Life Hastings
Kamuzu Banda and his personal troupe of hundreds of women dancers,
who swayed and ululated to the beat of African drums.
   There were no barriers or armed police holding back the
thousands of Malawians lining the route into town to glimpse the
pope. Instead, they stood in a perfect line, grouped in bright
color-coordinated uniforms, barely moving.
   On Friday, the pontiff was scheduled to celebrate Mass for an
estimated 250,000 people before returning to Rome on Saturday.
   At an earlier Mass in Lusaka, John Paul made his first reference
to AIDS, which has ravaged Zambia. The World Health Organization
estimates that more than 10 percent of Zambia's urban population is
infected with the AIDS virus, and development agencies say the
figure could be far higher.
   Zambia has a population of 7.5 million.
   ``The church proclaims a message of hope to those of you who
suffer in Zambia today ... to the sick and dying, especially the
victims of AIDS, and to those who lack medical care,'' the pontiff
said.
   The 100,000 people attending the Mass included President Kenneth
Kaunda, who lost his 30-year-old son Masuzgo to AIDS in December
1986.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the immune system
and leaves the body defenseless against infection.
</TEXT>
