<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-04 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Weather In The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms struck parts of the South on Thursday with at
least two tornadoes, heavy rain, hail and 70-mph winds, toppling 89
electrical towers in Louisiana and causing scattered damage and
power outages elsewhere.
   Thunderstorms had produced severe weather in Louisiana and Texas
late Wednesday and during the night, and on Thursday they spread
across parts of Arkansas, Louisiana, Texas and Mississippi.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 2.92 inches of rain fell
on Jackson, Miss., while 1.64 inches and baseball-sized hail fell
on the Monroe, La., area.
   ``My car looks like the surface of the moon,'' said Greg Gulyas,
a reporter at Monroe radio station KJLO.
   Lexington elementary school in Monroe suffered extensive damage.
``It hit our windows on the north side and we went into our drills
and got the kids inside,'' said principal Charles Roaner.
   The toppled transmission towers, which were 60 to 70 feet tall
and supposedly built to withstand 100-mph winds, supported a
500,000-volt line in a 50-mile stretch between Talullah and
Vicksburg, Miss, said Charles Thacker, a division marketing manager
for Louisiana Power &amp; Light.
   As many as 10,000 LP&amp;L customers across the northern portion of
the state were temporarily without power, he said.
   Mississippi authorities reported one small tornado that caused
tree damage, and a second twister that wrecked two mobile homes,
but caused no injuries, in Pelahatchie.
   In Vicksburg, Miss., the Warren County Sheriff's Department said
trees and power lines were down and electricity was off in schools
and other buildings inside and outside the city limits after
thunderstorms. A spokeswoman said roofs had been ripped off houses
and that one woman was taken to a hospital after a tree fell on her
car.
   In downtown Vicksburg, two businesses had extensive roof damage
and a lumber company reported major damage with one wall blown in.
   Half an inch of rain fell in seven minutes at Vicksburg, the
National Weather Service said.
   The weather service said the storm system produced wind blowing
at 60 to 70 mph in parts of Mississippi.
   At Newton, Miss., an airport employee reported that high wind
had broken airplane tiedowns and blew over one small airplane.
   The weather service also reported wind damage in parts of
Arkansas and Texas, where wind gusted to 72 at Graford.
   Showers and thunderstorms also spread into central Alabama,
western Tennessee and western Kentucky.
   Elsewhere, showers prevailed from Illinois to Minnesota, with
showers over the central high Plains region.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 98 at Gila Bend,
Ariz. Thursday's low for the 48 contiguous states was 25 degrees at
Alamosa, Colo.
   For Friday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the
Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic Coast states.
   Highs only in the 40s were predicted from central North Dakota
through Minnesota to Upper Michigan; in the 40s and 50s from the
northern and central high Plains to the upper Great Lakes region;
above 80 from the Pacific Coast through much of Arizona and much of
Texas to Florida and southern Georgia; and in the 90s or above 100
in the desert Southwest and the valleys of southern California.
</TEXT>
