<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0727 05-04 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico City Uses Bus Strike to Reorganize Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADD 5 grafs on striking teachers' march</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makeshift measures filled the gap left by
23,000 fired bus workers Thursday as Mexico City's government
grabbed the chance to revamp its inefficient transport system.
   The drivers went on strike and were fired Wednesday, causing
some panic, but a spot survey showed commuters Thursday were just
15 minutes to half an hour late.
   ``As you can see, there's almost no problem,'' city spokesman
Alfonso Marin said in a telephone interview. He said a panel of
experts is meeting to discuss the reorganization.
   ``We will come up with a solution in about a week. Right now, we
don't know what shape it will take, but we are working it out,''
Marin said.
   The fact that nearly a quarter of the capital's 8.5 million
residents took the week off work reduced the strike's impact.
Monday _ international labor day _ was an official holiday, and on
Friday, Mexico commemorates an 1862 victory over the French.
   Union secretary-general Nacio Chicuellar said he hopes the
government will reverse its decision to fire all striking drivers,
mechanics and clerks. ``We hope so. We're waiting for them to give
us an appointment,'' he said.
   Ricardo Barco Lopez, the union's lawyer, said many strikers have
returned to their depots in hopes of going back to work.
   The Federal District, as the capital officially is called, has
8.5 million residents. About 10.5 million more live in surrounding
suburbs of the metropolitan area.
   About 9 million commute to work daily, 2 million by bus and the
rest on subways, trolleys and minibuses.
   The 23,000 bus workers walked off their jobs early Wednesday,
rejecting a 14 percent pay raise offer and demanding 50 percent. A
conciliation board had declared the strike illegal in advance and
the government fired them all. Bus workers are Mexico's highest
paid municipal employees, earning more than $9,000 a year.
   ``The drivers were wrong. They have no right to strike,'' said
Imelda, 46, a waitress who wakes up at 5:30 a.m. to get to work
across town by 11 a.m. ``It's perfect, what the government did.''
   Wednesday night the strikers tried to return to work, but city
transportation coordinator Enrique Jackson said it was too late. A
few hours later, the city subway workers' union accepted the 14
percent increase.
   To fill gaps, Jackson authorized taxicabs to pick up multiple
fares, allowed 1,000 suburban line buses to extend their routes
into the city and charge 16 cents a ride _ four times the usual
fare. He urged motorists to help stranded commuters.
   He said bus workers can apply for jobs in the new system, but
did not say if there would be spots for them all.
   Mayor Manuel Camacho Solis' office said preliminary plans for
the bus line would make workers part owners and allow more
independent operation.
   Fare increases seem likely, in line with President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's campaign to make state-owned companies
profitable or get rid of them.
   Tens of thousands of dissident public school teachers striking
for higher pay and for union reforms marched through the streets of
Mexico City Thursday, snarling traffic between downtown and the
Presidential Palace.
   Thousands of riot police were posted along the five-mile route
but no violence was reported.
   Reporters estimated that the march swelled at times to about
150,000 teachers and supporters.
   Teachers won a 25 percent increase in wages and benefits and
ouster of a union boss closely tied to the governing party. They
want the pay offer extended to non-teaching school employees and
want negotiations speeded up on elections in at least 11 union
locals.
   The strike, called by the dissident wing of the National
Federation of Education Workers, is now in its third week and has
closed down thousands of schools nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
