<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0725 05-04 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Noriega Ticket Holds Final Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with rally, quotes. Pick up 12th
pvs, `After Noriega...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing coalition's presidential
candidate pledged Thursday in the country's last major pre-election
rally to seek an end to disputes with the United States.
   Candidate Carlos Duque told more than 100,000 people that the
solution to U.S.-Panama problems ``would have to be based on mutual
respect and without impositions.''
   For the past several days U.S. officials, including President
Bush, have claimed that Panama's government is planning massive
electoral fraud in Sunday's balloting. So has a vocal oppositon,
which says there can be no democratization in Panama as long as
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega remains head of the nation's Defense
Forces.
   Duque, 59, is a Noriega business associate. Ramon Sieriro,
candidate for first vice president for the eight-party Coalition
for National Liberation, is Noriega's brother-in-law.
   The United States says it wants Noriega out. He was indicted
last year on charges of drug smuggling and money laundering by a
U.S. federal grand jury in Miami.
   Nearly 1.2 million voters are registered to vote in Sunday's
election.
   ``We are the only ones who can unite all of the social forces of
the country,'' Duque told the crowd as he invoked the memory of the
late populist dictator Omar Torrijos, who signed the treaty that
gives Panama total control of the Panama Canal in the year 2000.
   ``We are the only ones who can speak with all members of the
international community,'' he added, referring to Noriega's
connections with governments that are not on friendly terms with
the United States.
   Public employees were given the afternoon off to attend the
pro-government gathering, the last massive campaign rally before
the second presidential election in 21 years.
   Tens of thousands of opposition supporters gathered Wednesday
for their final rally in support of their presidential candidate,
Guillermo Endara.
   Pro-government parties accuse the opposition of having accepted
$10 million in foreign backing for the campaign.
   ``They know they have lost already and that is why they are
yelling fraud,'' Duque said in a speech Tuesday.
   Noriega claims the United States wants to oust him because he
opposes U.S. plans to maintain its Southern Command military
installations in Panama beyond the year 2000 and because it wants
to renege on the canal treaties.
   The anti-U.S. rhetoric of the government-controlled media has
increased in the past few days, and the government prohibited the
broadcasting of Voice of America programs.
   Both the government and the opposition have called on their
followers to go out into the streets to defend the vote.
   After Noriega was indicted, then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle
tried to oust him. Noriega in turn forced out Delvalle.
   In addition to choosing a new president Sunday, voters will
elect two vice presidents, 67 national legislators and 510 precinct
representatives.
   The newspaper La Estrella on Thursday ran an editorial asking
the U.S. government to ``lessen its political pressures over Panama
which has been a loyal partner in the operation of the Canal.''
   The government banned Voice of America programs on local radio.
   The first international observers of the election began
arriving. The government has invited observers from Latin America,
Europe and Asia, but refused to give visas to any official U.S.
delegation.
   However, it invited former presidents Jimmy Carter and Gerald
Ford. They will head a non-official group of observers from the
Council of Freely-elected Heads of Government.
   The government also has prevented some journalists from entering
Panama. Spanish journalists here Wednesday sent a letter to the
Defense Forces protesting the denial of visa to Joaquin Ibarz of
Vanguardia of Barcelona.
</TEXT>
