<HEAD>Police Chief Daryl Gates Withdraws From Governor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Chief Daryl Gates will not seek the
GOP nomination in the 1990 governor's race, saying on Thursday he
lacked support from Republicans and conservatives.
   Gates, 62, had announced three months ago that he was forming an
exploratory committee to consider a gubernatorial candidacy and
test his political support. He said he would not actively campaign
and but would continue as police chief.
   But he found he trailed far behind U.S. Sen. Pete Wilson, the
Republican front-runner, and former Baseball Commissioner Peter
Ueberroth, who also has strong statewide recognition and has been
mentioned as a possible GOP candidate.
   The chief could not be reached immediately by telephone,
although his secretary confirmed that he had decided to quit.
   In an interview with KNBC-TV, Gates cited his lack of support
among conservatives and Republican party regulars as reasons to
pull out. He also said that his outspokenness worked against him.
   He said he believes a political candidate should be ``willing to
put his political career, his reputation on the block and go
forward with an issue because he believes in that issue. And we
don't have that.''
   Gates was booed April 1 in Orange County during his address at
the annual meeting of the California Republican Assembly, an
influential grass-roots conservative group.
   Members of the audience complained stridently that Gates had
condoned police officers' rough treatment during arrests of
anti-abortion protesters in Los Angeles a week earlier.
   Gates said no other statewide elective offices interest him, and
he plans to remain police chief.
   ``I think that the Chief of Police of Los Angeles can have more
influence than any other statewide official, except the governor,''
Gates said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
