<SECOND>AM-Police Cover,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Halts Deputy's Impersonation Of Reporters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS News said Thursday it is
disturbed by revelations that sheriff's deputies impersonated
members of its staff and will have an attorney contact the Kootenai
County sheriff.
   Undercover Kootenai County deputies posed as members of a CBS
crew in March in Napa, Calif., and another deputy claimed he was a
Montana reporter at a Seattle rally in April, Sheriff Pierce Clegg
acknowledged this week.
   He said he has since adopted a policy against using such covers,
but can't promise it will never happen again. Clegg was unavailable
for comment Thursday, said his secretary, Marlee Aurora.
   ``We do understand the situation it puts you (reporters) in,''
Clegg said earlier this week. ``It would be stupid of me to say it
will never happen again because rules are made to be broken, but
it's not our intention to get information that way.''
   Clegg said both undercover operations were to gather information
on people expected to attend or counterdemonstrate at a
white-supremacist convention that took place in the county April
21-23.
   Deputy Capt. Tom Dickson conceded that he identified himself as
a reporter for the Missoulian in Montana on April 15 when
approached by a member of the Seattle Non-Violent Action Group.
Dickson was videotaping participants at a rally to counter the
skinhead convention the next week.
   Clegg also confirmed that a month earlier two of his deputies
posed as members of a CBS crew to videotape protesters and
neo-Nazis at a Napa, Calif., skinhead gathering. They were acting
officially along with members of a Southern California law
enforcement agency Clegg declined to identify.
   The Missoulian filed objections with Clegg over the April
incident, and CBS News spokesman Tom Goodman in New York said
Wednesday the network had not been able to reach Clegg yet about
the March 4 incident in California.
   Thursday, Goodman said CBS ``will seek assurances from
appropriate law enforcement officials in Kootenai County that these
actions will not be repeated.''
   He said a CBS lawyer will contact Clegg, possibly Friday.
