<FIRST>r a AM-SmugglingArrests     05-04 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smuggling Arrests,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS Arrests Nine In Alleged Immigrant Smuggling Rings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN F. BONFATTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undercover investigation into the
smuggling of Chinese aliens into the United States led to nine
arrests and gave officials a rare glimpse into how such operations
work, federal authorities said Thursday.
   ``Over the course of the last few months we've learned more
about smuggling than we have in the last 200 years,'' Benedict
Ferro, Buffalo district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said Thursday.
   The investigation was one of the few to penetrate beyond the
``transporter'' level to the level of those who actually arrange
the transactions, ``(Arrangers) are at the level above the actual
smuggler himself,'' Ferro said.
   Two arrangers, at least three illegal aliens brought into the
country by the ring and 20 other people thought to be illegal
aliens were arrested Wednesday in restaurants in New York City's
Chinatown section, Ferro said.
   Three illegal aliens also were arrested in Toronto earlier in
the week by Royal Canadian Mounted Police and another was arrested
last week by INS agents in Albany.
   Three people who were indicted for conspiring to violate U.S.
immigration laws were being sought along with two other reputed
smugglers, Ferro said.
   He said the smuggling rings transported Chinese nationals from
Hong Kong to Vancouver to Toronto and had links to organized crime
in China. Aliens were then transported across the Niagara River,
which forms the boundary between the United States and Canada, and
eventually to Chinatown.
   ``I would estimate that those nine arrangers have been
responsible for hundreds of Chinese being smuggled though these
routes,'' said Ferro.
   Buffalo investigators began their investigation a year ago when
a smuggler arrested by INS agents agreed to cooperate. The
informant introduced agents to the Toronto end of the smuggling
rings, which undercover agents infiltrated.
   The agents then became transporters, agreeing to move aliens
across one of four international bridges linking the United States
and Canada.
   Canada is a favored port of entry to North America because Hong
Kong residents don't need a visa to visit Canada, officials said.
   The investigation turned up ``arrangers previously on the
sideline who we had not identified, roots we hadn't identified in
the past, meeting places and safe houses _ the kinds of things we
don't get being outside the organization,'' he said.
   Agents learned of elaborate smuggling contracts which controlled
the whole process from China to New York City, Ferro said. The cost
of the trip to aliens was usually about $20,000.
   ``They signed contracts which included such things as the
posting of bail should they get caught,'' he said.
   Once in Chinatown, those who are smuggled into the country often
work many years for low wages in restaurants and ``sweatshops'' to
pay back the cost of the trip.
   More ominously, Ferro said, the illegal aliens find themselves
``financially over their heads'' and are forced to be involved in
criminal activities as a way of repaying the debt.
   ``Very often these gangs (in Chinatown) are made up of people
who are forced to perform in the gangs,'' he said.
   ``These are clearly the people we were trying to get,'' said
Ferro of the arrests. ``There are some significant aspects of
Chinese smuggling that the arrests of these people will address.''
   Two of those arrested, Tin Seong Hui and William Tsoi, both of
Manhattan, were accused of arranging the trips in a warrant issued
by U.S. District Court Judge John T. Curtin in Buffalo.
   Most of those arrested were charged with conspiracy to transport
illegal aliens, which Ferro said is punishable by fines up to
$250,000 and five years in jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0228 </DOCNO>
