<FIRST>r a AM-UMW-Pittston     05-04 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMW-Pittston,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Mediator Getting UMW, Pittston Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCLURE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran federal mediator plans to meet
with negotiators for striking miners and Virginia's largest coal
company on Friday and Saturday in an effort to break a two-year
deadlock in contract talks.
   Pittston Coal Group, however, has refused the United Mine
Workers' offer to suspend picketing and demonstrations if the
company stops mining operations during a seven-day cooling-off
period.
   In response, miners on Thursday resumed civil disobedience
tactics that have resulted in 1,290 arrests outside Pittston
operations in southwest Virginia since the strike began April 5.
   ``I'm keeping my fingers crossed on this,'' Ted Chaskelson,
legal counsel for the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service,
said from his Washington office.
   The agency, a wing of the U.S. Labor Department, assigned the
case to Joe Kirkham of Louisville, who has mediated labor disputes
for 28 years.
   Kirkham is planning to meet with the UMW negotiating team Friday
and the company representatives Saturday before getting them
together next week. Times and sites had not been decided late
Thursday.
   The strike, which began April 5, affects about 1,500 miners in
Virginia and West Virginia. Two hundred other union miners working
at Pittston operations in Kentucky have not yet left their jobs.
   For the most part, the demonstrations have been non-violent and
the charges limited to obstructing free passage, a misdemeanor.
   On Tuesday, however, seven miners and two contract drivers for
the company were injured when miners pelted the trucks with rocks
and the drivers plowed into demonstrators.
   State police Thursday arrested 21 striking miners for blocking
the entrance to a Pittston mine and processing plant at McClure. In
separate incidents later in the day, they arrested 14 miners for
throwing rocks at coal trucks, Lt. J.B. Willis said.
   Nonetheless, both sides said they were cautiously optimistic
that the federal mediation would help settle the strike.
</TEXT>
