<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Missiles,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Report of South African Bid for Missile Secrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa offered up to $17 million for secrets
of a British missile manufactured in Northern Ireland, Independent
Television News said Thursday.
   ITN said the offer was made to pro-British Protestant
paramilitary groups for the new surface-to-air Starstreak missile,
in return for cash or arms.
   Rae Killen, South Africa's ambassador in London, said on the
evening news program he doubted very much if money was offered for
Starstreak secrets.
   ``I would hope that no action is taken that would cause problems
to our ... (British-South African) relations,'' he said.
   The Starstreak, not yet fully developed, is scheduled to upgrade
British air defenses in the 1990s.
   Neither Protestant extremist sources nor the Northern Ireland
police had any immediate comment on the report.
   Starstreak, made at Short Brothers factory in Belfast, was top
of the South Africans' shopping list, according to the program,
which quoted sources in the province's Protestant majority.
   Protestant extremists have tried to counter the outlawed Irish
Republican Army's struggle to end British rule and unite the
province with the Irish Republic.
   The ITN report said a man from Northern Ireland living in South
Africa approached Protestant paramilitaries in 1985 and suggested
that a request for arms would be received sympathetically. It said
one official of such a group spent two weeks in South Africa
inspecting weapons in 1985.
   The program said the group could not afford the asking price of
$312,500, so the South Africans suggested an exchange of missile
parts for a delivery to Northern Ireland of illegal weapons.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe complained last month to Barend Du Plessis, the
visiting South African finance minister, about alleged attempts to
steal missile secrets.
   Howe said Britain would view seriously any support by any
government ``for those engaged in violence in the United Kingdom,''
the Foreign Office said.
   Published reports in Britain said South Africa supplied arms to
Protestant groups in January 1988 in return for blueprints of
Blowpipe, a shoulder-fired anti-aircraft missile made at Short
Brothers, and also for a cash payment of $255,000.
   Three South African officials implicated in the Blowpipe case
were ordered last week to leave France.
   The Federal Prosecutor's Office in Switzerland is investigating
allegations that an American with an office in Geneva was involved.
</TEXT>
