<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-Fighting     05-04 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Fighting,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 86 Die in Angolan Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting between government forces and
UNITA rebels has killed 86 people in Angola since late April, the
Angolan news agency ANGOP reported Thursday.
   The report from the Angolan capital of Luanda, monitored in
Lisbon, said most of the deaths came in fighting in Huambo, Bie and
Lunda Sul provinces.
   ANGOP said 37 guerrillas, six soldiers and 25 civilians died in
a government offensive against rebel positions in the three central
provinces.
   Eleven other civilians were killed in a rebel attack on a
village in Huambo on April 28, ANGOP said.
   The agency reported that a rebel attack killed three civilians
in Bula Atumba town in northern Kuanza Norte province, about 110
miles east of Luanda, and that four other non-combatants were
killed when a mine destroyed a vehicle in Kuanza Norte on April 28.
   It said that 426 civilians who had been held captive by UNITA _
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola _ were
released and reported to government authorities between April 26
and May 3.
   Six armed and uniformed guerrillas gave up to authorities at the
same time, it said.
   ANGOP said 97 Angolans accused of aiding rebels were freed
Wednesday under terms of a government amnesty.
   UNITA has fought to force the Marxist-orientated Luanda
government to share power since shortly after Angola gained
independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The United States supports UNITA and the Soviet Union backs the
Angolan government.
</TEXT>
