<FIRST>r a AM-Brites SUB a0643 05-04 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, SUB, a0643,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS the LAS CRUCES, N.M.-dated item on Batmobile copyright
dispute to CORRECT 6th graf, ``They may ..., to reflect that Marcy Driggers
is assistant city, sted assistant district, attorney.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holy copyright, Batman!
   Warner Communications wants the city of Las Cruces to stop using
the Batmobile name and Batman logo on its Breath Analyzing Testing
van used to test suspected drunken drivers.
   Warner owns DC Comics, which has the copyright to the Batman
character, a costumed crime-fighting super hero in mythical Gotham
City who drives a customized Batmobile.
   Police Chief Ron Axtell said the Batmobile is a tribute to the
comic book hero and is not exploitative.
   ``After all, we are all crime fighters,'' he said. ``But if they
want to pursue this, then we can do something else with the B.A.T.''
   ``They may be correct technically about the logo and the name,''
said Assistant City Attorney Marcy Driggers. ``But frankly, I don't
think that we are infringing. The purpose of a copyright is to
protect the company from merchandising, but the city is not making
money on our Batmobile.''
   Don't anybody tell Warner, but Las Cruces isn't the only New
Mexico city with a Batmobile.
   Santa Fe police Lt. Gilbert Ulibarri said Warner has not
contacted his department about its Batmobile.
   The Albuquerque Police Department has two Batmobiles, according
to the city's traffic department.
