<FIRST>u i AM-Thatcher 2ndLd-Writethru a0810 05-04 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0810,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says She's Transformed Britain in 10 Years in Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs UPDATING with election results, comment.
Picks up 9th graf, `Speaking to...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher celebrated her 10th anniversary
in power Thursday, declaring she has transformed Britain, but she
apparently lost a previously safe Welsh parliamentary district to
socialists.
   In Northern Ireland, the Irish Republican Army, which has vowed
to assassinate Mrs. Thatcher, killed a British soldier and said the
bomb attack was a 10th anniversary reminder that ``the Irish
question remains unresolved.''
   Mrs. Thatcher escaped injury in 1984 when the outlawed IRA blew
up her hotel in Brighton, England, killing five members of her
Conservative Party. The IRA warned her afterward, ``We only have to
be lucky once. You have to be lucky always.''
   Former President Reagan telephoned anniversary congratulations
Thursday from California, an aide said. The Reagans plan to visit
London next month.
   Soviet TV gave her a mixed review. It said she had been able to
``noticeably raise the international authority of England'' and
inject a new dynamism into the economy, but had done so at the
expense of British workers.
   Leaders of the main opposition Labor Party were particularly
delighted Thursday at their apparent win in the Vale of Glamorgan,
a largely rural Welsh district, declaring they were on their way
back to power after a decade in the shadows.
   The Conservatives held the parliamentary seat for 38 years.
Thursday's special election was caused by the death of the previous
legislator.
   Pre-election polls predicted a Tory loss. This partly reflected
opposition to an overhaul of the free National Health Service _
among the latest targets of Mrs. Thatcher's right-wing revolution.
   In separate county council elections in England and Wales, both
Conservatives and Labor made substantial gains, largely at the
expense of the two squabbling center parties _ the Social and
Liberal Democratic Party and the the smaller Social Democratic
Party.
   With results declared early Friday from 40 of the 47 county
councils, the Conservatives had overall control of 14, up from
seven, and Labor had overall control of 12, including four new
gains.
   The Social and Liberal Democratic Party kept control of its
district, the Isle of Wight, in county council elections but lost
seats across the country.
   Of the remaining councils declared, no party had overall control
in 11 and two were controlled by independents.
   Speaking to reporters on the steps of her 10 Downing St. office
Thursday morning, Mrs. Thatcher said ``Britain has been
transformed'' since she ousted James Callaghan's Labor Party
government and took office May 4, 1979.
   ``The standard of living for almost everyone is higher and ... I
think everyone recognizes that Britain's standing in the world is
greater than it's been for many a very long year,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 63, swept to power on a wave of anti-union
sentiment after a winter of strikes left garbage piled across the
country, hospitals turning away the sick and the dead unburied.
   Europe's first woman prime minister since has won two more
elections. She is the longest continuously serving British prime
minister this century and is expected to run for a fourth term.
   She gave no hint when she might go, saying, ``There's no thought
of slowing down.''
   Mrs. Thatcher cut an anniversary cake in the House of Commons
and was guest of honor at a Downing Street dinner Thursday given by
her 21 Cabinet colleagues. They are all men and only three are
survivors of her first Cabinet.
   Otherwise it was a regular day that included furious exchanges
in the Commons with opposition leader Neil Kinnock, with whom she
has a particularly antagonistic relationship.
   He charged her with failing to fulfill St. Francis of Assisi's
prayer, ``Where there is discord, may we bring harmony,'' which she
quoted on the steps of Downing Street when she moved in.
   Shouting above Labor jeers, Mrs. Thatcher retorted, ``Remember
the discord in the winter of discontent in 1979 when under
socialism ... you couldn't even get the dead buried.''
</TEXT>
