<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0855 05-04 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0855,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Felony Probe Targets Fired Tanker Skipper in Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Quayle arrival, inspection
plans; picks up 6th graf: `Federal Transportation ...; news conference
not expected until 3:25 a.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has begun investigating
fired tanker captain Joseph Hazelwood for possible felony
violations stemming from his role in the nation's worst oil spill,
sources said Thursday.
   Hazelwood, free on $50,000 bail, already has been ordered to
stand trial June 20 in Valdez on three misdemeanor charges that
include operating a vessel while drunk. He has pleaded innocent.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, meanwhile, arrived Thursday night to
inspect beaches fouled by the spill. Alaska officials were eager to
give him a tour, according to the state's ranking environmental
official at the spill zone.
   ``He's going to see oil and lots of it,'' said Bill Lamoreaux of
the state Department of Environmental Conservation. The beach on
Smith Island, where a wooden viewing platform has been constructed
for Quayle, was among the hardest hit.
   Quayle's government jet touched down about 6:30 p.m. (10:30 EDT)
at Cordova, about 50 miles from the site of the Exxon Valdez tanker
crash. Following the Smith Island stop, he was scheduled to visit
Elmendorf Air Force Base outside Anchorage later for a news
conference.
   Federal Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, Alaska Gov.
Steve Cowper and Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost Jr. were expected
to accompany Quayle.
   The grand jury probe is the first indication that Hazelwood, 42,
faces felony charges stemming from the spill March 24, when his
vessel slammed into a reef and poured more than 10 million gallons
of crude into Prince William Sound.
   Sources at the state District Court and the district attorney's
office, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the grand jury
was taking testimony on the possibility that Hazelwood committed a
felony in connection with his conduct the night of the spill.
   One source said the probe concerned second-degree criminal
mischief, which carrys a maximum term of five years in prison. For
first offenders, the sentence is often two years or less, with
probation.
   In other developments, Exxon officials Thursday proposed arming
the guards of their cleanup crews with shotguns _ rather than
chemical sprays they're now carrying _ to protect them against the
coastal brown bears.
   But state and federal environmental officials were concerned
that inexperienced guards might shoot the bears needlessly.
   Exxon also launched a public relations offensive Thursday
against critics of its cleanup plan, saying government bureaucracy
has crippled the effort.
   ``It's a comprehensive plan. It's a good plan. It's an
economically sound plan and we're convinced it will work,'' Otto
Harrison, Exxon's executive supervising the cleanup from Valdez,
said in an interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
   Exxon President Lee R. Raymond, at a news conference in his New
York offices, denied the company was trying to cut corners in the
cleanup. But he complained that as many as 14 government agencies
may be involved in approving and carrying out the final plan.
   ``I want one person in charge _ I don't care who it is _ because
there has to be one person that finally says, `Hey, it's midnight
and we gotta do something,'' Raymond said. ``Anything reasonable,
anything that makes sense that they would say you ought to do in
addition to what you have in the plan, we'll do it.''
   Raymond also said Exxon is not seeking exemptions from
environmental laws, although the oil company's proposal
specifically calls for ``letters of non-objection, waivers and
permit modifications'' from state and local governments to dispose
of the oil waste at the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. terminal in
Valdez.
   Raymond said Yost, who has authority over whether Exxon's
cleanup proposal is approved, was encouraged by Exxon's proposal.
Dennis Hubbard, a spokesman for Yost in Valdez, said the commandant
has not taken a position on the plan.
   Earlier this week, Yost called the plan ``very thin, very light.
There's not a lot of backup subsantiation.''
   Oil from the spill has spread throughout the sound and
contaminated shores more than 525 miles to the southwest, including
the spectacular Katmai National Park, a wildlife refuge.
   Exxon has recommended cleaning 364 miles of Alaska coastline by
mid-September. But the company wants to leave untouched nearly 200
of those miles and let them be cleaned by nature.
   The state, responding to a request from Yost to evaulate Exxon's
revised clean-up plan, rejected the Exxon proposal, saying it was
inadequate and didn't provide for enough personnel to do the job.
</TEXT>
