<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv05-1stLd-Writethru b044</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 05-1st Ld-Writethru, b0449,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, May 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TV Producer In Tiff With Fundamentalist Strategist</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS spelling of ``tussle'' in lead.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A widely respected television journalist, Bill
Moyers, is in a tussle with fundamentalist officials of his own
denomination, the Southern Baptists, particularly one of them.
   It's a peculiar scrap, and may lead to further rounds.
   ``I've been a Baptist all my life and I'm used to this,'' Moyers
commented. ``They say that where two or more Baptists are gathered
together, there'll be a fight.''
   This one was started by a virtually unheard-of action _ a
formally adopted resolution by a major denomination assailing an
individual journalist. It said Moyers' TV series, ``God and
Politics'' was biased.
   Moyers says, ``Nobody can point to a single frame of that series
and say it's inaccurate.
   ``We tried to be scrupulously fair and with the single exception
of Paul Pressler, the comments we have received from all sides have
underlined that fairness.''
   Pressler, a Houston judge, was the chief strategist for
fundamentalists gaining predominance in the country's biggest
Protestant body, elevating him to its national executive committee.
   There, he pushed through the resolution in February, charging
that the Moyers series supported ``one faction'' _ the moderates _
in a decade-long conflict with the now-ruling fundamentalist camp.
   Charging ``biased content,'' the resolution urged people to
complain to sponsors and the Public Broadcasting System that aired
it more than a year before, in December, 1987.
   ``Why they waited so long is a mystery to me,'' Moyers said in
an interview. ``Pressler now has the committee packed with his
people so he can do whatever he wants.''
   Pressler singled out a part of the series called, ``Battle for
the Bible,'' dealing with the denominational controversy, and
called it prejudiced.
   That show is to be repeated Sunday, May 21, on PBS as part of a
series of Moyers' best documentaries. He notified Pressler of the
re-showing ``in light of your spurious accusations'' and ``so
viewers can once more judge it for themselves.''
   Meyers invited Pressler to appear with him following the program
for a half-hour live discussion to ``say whatever he wants to say,
unedited.''
   However, the executive committee's chairman, the Rev. Charles
Sullivan of Lenoir City, Tenn., replied that Pressler had been
asked not to discuss the matter further publicly until the
committee considered it.
   The committee next meets just before the June 9-16 Southern
Baptist Convention in Las Vegas, Nev. Moyers earlier asked to
appear before it to ``discuss these matters in a Christian
manner.'' But Sullivan also had turned that down, saying there was
no time on the agenda.
   Pressler, at one point, proposed a 90-minute session with him
taped by the denomination's Sunday School Board, provided it was
shown in full on PBS _ something no independent producer could
guarantee.
   Ironically, while the jousting went on, the national convention
of the Religious Public Relations Council, representing
communications officers of most major denominations, presented a
special award to Moyers for his high journalistic standards and
sensitivity to religious values.
   Fundamentalists gained hegemony among the 14.8 million Southern
Baptists through a strategy _ planned by Pressler _ of electing
successive convention presidents to use appointive powers to
restrict personnel to ``biblical inerrantists'' or literalists.
   Baptists, while always honoring the Bible, historically have
resisted any official creed or control of interpretation.
   ``Most Baptists don't realize what's been going on,'' Moyers
said. ``They're too busy doing the Lord's work to pay any attention
to denominational politics.''
   A key element in Pressler's complaint against Moyers was that in
a filmed interview, Moyers changed the questions from those to
which Pressler is shown responding.
   Moyers told Baptist Press: ``Paul Pressler is not telling the
truth.''
   Pressler said that during the interview, the only camera shots
were ``full face of me'' but that Moyers' staff later ``recorded
him asking new questions front face of him.''
   They were ``somewhat similar questions,'' but had ``different
nuances,'' he said. ``And, brother, it is not fair to have...you
appear like you are answering questions that were never asked.''
   Moyers recounted of the interview: ``As I began to ask him
questions about his ties to right-wing politics and the beer man
Joseph Coors, he grew angry and flushed in the face, abruptly stood
up, tore off his microphone, announced the interview was over and
left the room in a huff, all of which we filmed but did not use in
the commentary.
   ``His unexpected departure meant that he was not present when,
as is customary, we reversed the single camera and repeated the
questions which my producer had taken down as the interview
progressed. But the content of the questions was unchanged.
   ``As a matter of professional practice, I do not treat my guests
unfairly; one would not survive in journalism and do so.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, May 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Franklin Adv07   05-04 1250</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Franklin, Adv 07,1293</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reflections of the Queen of Soul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Queen of Soul reigned over
her recent birthday party with the aloofness of a true monarch.
   Aretha Franklin watched with detachment while guests dined on
smoked salmon, fresh fruit and chocolate fondue, and danced to the
music of two bands. The furniture had been removed from her
cavernous home in this affluent suburb to accommodate the 300
friends.
   It all resembled a medieval court transported to the 1980s _
dandies in black tie replaced knights in shining armor, and
madrigals gave way to rhythm and blues.
   Looking relatively svelte in a white suit with a black halter
top, the singer often stood alone, surreptitiously puffing a
cigarette. Still shy at 47, Aretha Franklin values privacy.
   ``When I'm at home, I'm just like the lady next door,'' she said
later in an interview. ``I try to leave my act on stage. I do my
share of the dishes when I'm at home. That helps keep my feet on
the ground.''
   Franklin rules over soul music like a personal fiefdom. She's an
icon who has influenced singers from Chaka Khan to Bette Midler.
   She won her 15th Grammy award this year for a collection of
gospel songs, and she is the biggest female Grammy winner in
history. Her albums and singles are multimillion sellers.
   Her home mirrors those achievements. Grammys line the mantel
piece of her office; gold and platinum records cover the walls _
some even sit on the floor because there is no place to hang them.
   But Franklin doesn't use her success to bully those around her.
   ``We didn't have any ego battles,'' said Narada Michael Walden,
producer of ``Who's Zoomin' Who,'' a platinum LP. ``If she had been
on her throne, maybe. But her throne is the people's throne.''
   Her constant quest for perfection is sometimes misinterpreted,
the producer said, giving her the reputation as being difficult.
   ``She works on instinct, on spontaneity,'' Walden said. ``She's
a perfectionist in terms of the feeling of a song, and sometimes
she'll keep doing it until she thinks it's right.''
   Franklin tries to avoid becoming totally immersed in her work.
Outside the studio, she attempts to stay fresh by doing things
unrelated to music.
   ``She's truly an excellent cook,'' Walden said. ``She has a
fighting spirit and she has to balance out her life, and cooking is
that release.''
   There is little time for cooking these days. Instead of food,
projects are simmering on all burners.
   Her new album, ``Through the Storm,'' features duets with Elton
John, James Brown and Whitney Houston. She also plans to write her
memoirs.
   ``The book will contain several juicy tidbits,'' said Franklin,
whose life provides a lot of material.
   Her father was the Rev. C.L. Franklin, a civil rights activist
and religious leader who also was prominent in gospel music
circles. Aretha was born in Memphis, Tenn. Her mother, a gospel
singer, left when she was about six, and Franklin moved his family
first to Buffalo, N.Y., and then to Detroit.
   As a child, Aretha saw such luminaries as the Nobelist Martin
Luther King Jr., Motown Records founder Berry Gordy and pop star
Sam Cooke in the Franklin's inner-city Detroit home.
   Her father was a popular ``electronic'' preacher who toured the
country with appearances and made dozens of albums. Under his
tutelage, a shy and introverted Aretha started singing gospel songs
at an early age. She quit school when she was about 14 to tour with
him, and made the live LP, ``Aretha Gospel,'' at his Detroit
church. She signed her first recording contract with Columbia
Records at 18, a discovery of the great record producer John
Hammond.
   Hammond, who produced such artists as Bob Dylan, Bessie Smith
and Bruce Springsteen, called Franklin ``an untutored genius.'' He
said she was the best voice he'd heard since Billie Holiday, who he
had also produced.
   After some minor success with such songs as Otis Redding's ``Try
a Little Tenderness,'' Franklin moved to Atlantic Records in 1966.
A year later, she exploded on the charts with her interpretation of
his ``Respect.'' Redding, who died a few months later in a plane
crash, said he liked Franklin's version better than his own.
   By 1969, she had forged an impressive chain of hits: ``A Natural
Woman,'' ``Chain of Fools,'' ``Do Right Woman _ Do Right Man,'' ``I
Never Loved a Man (the Way I Love You),'' ``Dr. Feelgood,''
``Think.''
   Her trademark two-ocatave jumps, impassioned bursts and gospel
whoops made her something of a legend. She moved with ease from
soul to show tunes to popular standards, but after her two most
ambitious albums, ``Young, Gifted and Black'' and ``Spirit in the
Dark,'' in the early '70s, her career slowed; she was still
popular, but the commercial success wasn't there.
   And her personal life _ three marriages and an especially
difficult divorce _ seemed to affect her musical life. She left
Atlantic and moved to Arista in 1980, where she has once again
found the golden touch.
   Besides the book, Franklin would like to make a movie. She had a
cameo role in the John Belushi-Dan Aykroyd movie, ``The Blues
Brothers'' in 1980, singing ``Think.''
   Her fear of flying and addiction to afternoon soap operas keep
her home and off the road. ``From noon until 3:30 in the afternoon,
nothing gets done in my home until the soaps are over,'' she said.
   For the past few years, Franklin has been taking a class to
overcome her phobia, but she still hasn't flown. In December, she
gave a concert in Atlantic City, traveling to the New Jersey resort
by luxury bus.
   ``It was fun,'' the singer said. ``It gave me a chance to see
some of the country.''
   She's scheduled to sing there again May 26-28.
   The singer scoffs at the notion that her career is on the
decline, as some in the business have suggested. ``I would say that
my greatest accomplishment hasn't even happened yet. I'm just a
baby in the industry and I'm still learning.''
   But Franklin is far from a toddler in the music business, having
taken giant steps since her humble beginnings as a gospel singer.
With little formal training, she's achieved great success relying
mostly on raw talent, and taking her cue from such gospel greats as
Mahalia Jackson and Clara Ward.
   She's also been able to change with the times. The raw emotion
of her music in the '60s has been refined and slickly packaged _
with synthesizers and special audio effects _ to widen her appeal
in the '80s.
   Early on, such songs as ``Respect'' snared R&amp;B fans, and she
later won a pop audience with her tributes to Judy Garland and
Josephine Baker. In the '80s, she grabbed the rockers with
``Freeway of Love'' and ``Jump to It.''
   ``She's got a core following, so she'll always be popular,''
said Mary Moore, director of rhythm and blues publicity at Arista.
``But the new album should win over even more fans because of the
duets, like the one with Whitney Houston.''
   Popularity is fine, but as far as Franklin is concerned,
``There's no place like home. My family is here and my roots are
here.''
   The interview abruptly ended.
   ``I have to check on the gumbo simmering on the stove,'' said
the Queen of Soul.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
