<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv07   05-04 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 07,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>75 Years Ago, USDA Extension Service Was Born to Help Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agricultural progress has had many mileposts.
But none is more revered in the United States than the development
of the land-grant institutions of higher learning and the extension
system that carried knowledge to farmers.
   Seventy-five years ago, on May 8, 1914, the Smith-Lever Act was
signed into law by President Wilson, creating an Agriculture
Department agency to work with states, counties and land-grant
schools to get the latest word from classrooms and laboratories
into the farthest reaches of rural America.
   The federal role had already been important for decades. It was
the 1862 Morrill Act, after all, that initially endowed the
land-grant institutions _ the ``silo techs'' and ``cow colleges'' _
by selling off 11 million acres of federal land.
   The Hatch Act of 1887 provided funds for starting experiment
stations at every land-grant school. And, in 1890, a second Morrill
Act established black land-grant colleges in southern states.
   In 1898, USDA hired an Iowan, Seaman A. Knapp, to work in the
South. In Louisiana, Knapp used a farm in each township to
demonstrate the latest rice production methods to local farmers. In
1903, he set up demonstrations to reduce cotton boll weevil damage
in Louisiana and Texas.
   As Knapp's concepts of moving information from schools and
experiment stations caught on, new ``county agents'' were gradually
added, along with home demonstration agents and youth clubs, which
became 4-H.
   With private funds and local tax support augmenting limited USDA
funds, the cooperative extension system grew. By June 1918, during
World War I, 2,435 counties had agricultural agents and 1,715 had
home demonstration agents working with USDA to boost wartime food
production.
   By 1921, however, the number of county units was cut back
sharply as emergency war funds dried up. In the 1930s, extension
agents were selected by USDA to explain and interpret for farmers
the new agricultural agencies and programs created to help them dig
out of the Depression.
   Through the years, says USDA historian Doug Bowers, the
extension system has remained a popular fixture among rural people.
   ``Before extension, there had been lots of books written on
agriculture and there had been agricultural societies, which tended
to be for gentlemen farmers, for the most part,'' Bowers said in a
telephone interview.
   Most farmers in the late 19th century and well into the 20th
weren't reached by scholarly books and papers written by
professors. Farmers were slow to change their methods.
   ``Extension was a way to get down to the level of the farmer and
reach him with the latest research,'' Bowers said. ``It was the
first time that had been done systematically.''
   As the county agents did their jobs, farmers used technology to
produce more food and fiber. They were able to plow and plant more
land. They grew larger _ but fewer. Millions left the land and
moved to the cities as technology and economics gripped rural
America.
   In the early 1900s, there were more than 6 million farms in the
United States. Today, there are barely 2 million.
   ``The problem has certainly shifted,'' Bowers said. ``Back
around the turn of the century, there were a lot of farmers who had
very little idea of the research going on, they weren't terribly
well educated. So it was a matter of educating farmers about fairly
basic things.''
   For example, he said, conservation wasn't much of a concern
until the 1930s, when dust storms and drought drew national
attention to the plight of the nation's soil.
   So the typical county agent of 50 or 75 years ago was concerned
with getting farmers to try new seeds, fertilizer or a different
way of tillage. Perhaps crop rotation was required, or drainage, or
summer fallow. Improved livestock bloodlines, animal nutrition, new
breeds of poultry and other innovations were introduced.
   A recent USDA pamphlet speaks of ``extension professionals in
nearly all of the nation's 3,150 counties.''
   These days, the Extension Service cites a number of ``national
initiatives'' that are supposed to ``provide a new focus'' for
extension's educational efforts. Those range from helping farmers
find ``alternative agricultural opportunities'' to conservation and
management of natural resources, water quality, diet and nutrition,
rural development are others.
   Has extension been so successful that it is no longer needed?
Has it worked itself out of a job?
   ``That's a queston that's much debated,'' says historian Bowers.
``I don't think I could answer that.''
   Myron Johnsrud, Extension Service administrator, says there is
plenty to do. In remarks announcing this week's kickoff of
observances during the 75th anniversary year, Johnsrud said
extension's mission now, as it was in 1914, ``is to deliver
research-based information to people where they live and work.''
   Critical issues facing Americans, including food safety, water
quality and ``youth at risk,'' are at the top of the extension
agenda, he said.
   ``And the tools of technology _ computers, video, satellites,
videodiscs _ are revolutionizing the way modern extension staffs
deliver programs,'' Johnsrud said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 7</NOTE>
