<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-04 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0895</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge gave interested
buyers a week to submit offers for Eastern Airlines, as a new
potential bidder emerged and another carrier made a proposal to buy
Eastern's profitable Northeast shuttle.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland set a May 10 deadline
for bidders to make offers for Eastern in its entirety, or for the
shuttle at a price exceeding the $365 million that developer Donald
Trump has agreed to pay for the business.
   Separately Wednesday, America West Airlines Inc. said it had
offered to pay $726 million for the shuttle and 10 Boeing 757
airliners.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. shunned overtures from rival
direct-seller Amway Corp. and investor Irwin L. Jacobs, which have
allied and may attempt a takeover of the cosmetics company.
   James Preston, Avon chairman and chief executive officer, said
Wedneday the company had been notified that Minneapolis-based
Jacobs and Amway had acquired 10 percent of Avon's common stock.
   ``We want to make it clear that Avon is not for sale,'' Preston
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business productivity rose at an annual rate
of 0.5 percent in the first quarter, with manufacturing workers
significantly increasing their per-hour output, the government
reported.
   Overall output in non-farm business rose 3.6 percent in the
quarter while hours worked climbed 3.1 percent, leaving the
half-percent productivity gain, the Labor Department said
Wednesday. The department revised the fourth-quarter non-farm
productivity gain to an annual rate of 1 percent, up from the 0.1
percent initially reported.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy ``grew at a moderate, sustainable
pace'' in the past three months, the Federal Reserve said in a
report which analysts took as a sign that the central bank will not
boost interest rates.
   The Fed's review of economic conditions around the country,
released Wednesday, painted a picture of an economy in which the
growth rate is slowing with inflationary pressures easing.
   The central bank for the past year has been trying to engineer
such a development by pushing interest rates up to dampen demand
and thus relieve pressures on tight labor markets and factories
operating at capacity.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales by the nation's Big
Three automakers in late April dropped 3 percent compared with the
same period a year ago, when sales were moderately strong.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said
Wednesday they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate
of 41,487 during the April 21-30 period this year compared with a
rate of 42,772 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said President Bush will veto
compromise legislation worked out by the House and Senate to raise
the mimimum wage from $3.35 to $4.55 an hour by 1991.
   Reacting to Tuesday's agreement between House and Senate
negotiators on legislation to change the wage rate for the first
time in eight years, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said Wednesday that Bush continues to believe the figure is too
high.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate went on record against gasoline tax
increases as it and the House cleared roadblocks to approving
budgets that carry out a much-criticized deficit-reduction
agreement with the White House.
   The anti-gas-tax amendment, offered by Sen. Steve Symms,
R-Idaho, passed by voice vote Wednesday and expressed the ``sense
of the Senate'' that motor fuel taxes should remain dedicated to
improvements in the highway and transportation system.
   The vote was a shot across the bow to those eyeing a rise in the
gas tax, now at 9.1 cents a gallon, as part of future
deficit-reduction efforts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two lawmakers, declaring that cable television
has turned from a luxury into a ``psychological necessity'' for
millions of Americans, vowed to press for consumer protections
against fast-rising rates.
   Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., and Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., introduced legislation Wednesday to place regulations on
an industry that they say has been riding roughshod over consumers
since it began setting its own rates 2{ years ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Rakolta, the Michigan woman who captured
attention with a letter-writing campaign to advertisers on a
network show she found offensive, announced a campaign to put more
family programs on prime-time television.
   ``Our emphasis ... will be to promote private, voluntary efforts
by the advertisers and the networks to raise the standards on
network television,'' Mrs. Rakolta said Wednesday of her new
organization, Americans for Responsible Television.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted some scattered losses Wednesday in an
atmosphere of caution. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
dropped 9.16 to 2,393.70.
   The dollar firmed against most major currencies in quiet
worldwide trading although central banks intervened to push down
its value.
   A Treasury Department decision to directly issue $50 billion in
bonds to rescue the nation's savings and loans sent the price of
long-term government bonds lower.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher, cotton prices
rose, energy futures were mostly higher, livestock futures were up
and pork futures were mixed. Precious metals also were mixed.
</TEXT>
