<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-AFL-CIO     05-04 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-AFL-CIO,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders Attack Lorenzo Plan; Urge Court To Order Eastern Sold</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO urged a bankruptcy judge to order
strike-crippled Eastern Airlines sold, condemning its current
owners for treating the carrier as ``a fiscal carcass to be picked
over for the benefit of other corporate entities.''
   The 14 million-member labor federation's governing body also
promised Wednesday continued support for Eastern's striking
Machinists union and the flight attendants and pilots who have
honored pickets, saying their solidarity in the two-month strike
has ``won the admiration of the entire labor movement.''
   The statement was issued by the AFL-CIO executive council as the
bankruptcy court in New York held a hearing on whether Eastern
should be sold in its entirety. The judge set a one-week deadline
for potential buyers to make proposals.
   Eastern's owner, Texas Air Corp., has insisted none of several
offers for the airline is workable and proposed a plan to shrink
Eastern that it says would allow the airline to emerge from
bankruptcy. The plan includes selling about $1.8 billion in Eastern
assets.
   The AFL-CIO said Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo has engaged in
``systematic milking of Eastern's assets to feed other sectors of
his Texas Air Corp.'' and said his mismanagement ``has literally
run the airline into the ground.''
   Leaders of Eastern's unions briefed the executive council before
the statement was issued, and pledged to work with new management
should the airline be sold.
   The AFL-CIO has raised more than $1.2 million in strike aid for
the Eastern unions and promised to continue fund-raising and other
support efforts until the strike is concluded.
</TEXT>
