<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-Amway Bjt   05-04 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Amway, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Snubs Takeover Feelers From Amway And Jacobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmetics maker Avon Products Inc. has rebuffed
takeover feelers from Amway Corp. and investor Irwin L. Jacobs and
says it isn't entertaining any offers.
   Minneapolis-based Jacobs and rival direct selling company Amway
told the Securities and Exchange Commission on Wednesday that they
hold about 5.57 million of Avon's 53.88 million shares outstanding,
or about 10.3 percent. They also purchased options to buy 40,000
shares on April 5 for $1.25 to $2 a piece.
   Most of the shares were bought from April 3 to May 2 for prices
ranging from $23 to $32.28{ each, the partners disclosed in a
document submitted to the SEC.
   The A-J Partnership formed by the two said Avon stock seems
undervalued and they might buy more shares from time to time. The
partners may make a merger proposal to Avon but no decision has
been reached, they said in the SEC filing. In response, Avon
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James Preston issued a
statement declaring, ``We want to make it clear that Avon is not
for sale.''
   Avon stock gained $4.75 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange
trading Wednesday, closing at $36.87{ in heavy volume. The price
surpassed its previous 52-week high of $32.50.
   At that price, if the partners were to buy all Avon common stock
and equivalents they don't own, the cost would total about $2.4
billion.
   Avon is widely known as a door-to-door distributor of
toiletries, fragrances and household products made famous by its
``Avon lady'' ad campaigns of years past. But much of Avon's
revenue now comes from workplace and telephone orders; Avon has
been moving toward more direct marketing via mailings.
   The New York-based company has been realigning its operations to
focus on its beauty businesses. After a largely unsuccessful foray
into the health care services industry, Avon sold or is in the
process of selling its nursing homes, retirement living facilities
and alcohol and drug abuse treatment centers.
   Preston stated that Avon has been improving its profitability
and stockholders would be better off if Avon pursues its current
objectives. Avon had sales of $3.06 billion in 1988 and lost $404.5
million, mainly due to the cost of getting out of the health care
services industry.
   ``We believe that Avon can provide the best value to its
shareholders by remaining independent,'' Preston said. ``Our
strategies have resulted in the strong sales and profit growth of
our beauty business for the last three years.''
   Avon has been the subject of takeover talk for some time, most
recently last week after Unilever's planned acquisition of the
Faberge and Elizabeth Arden toiletries, cosmetics and fragrance
lines fell through.
   There has been speculation that Unilever, a huge European
personal products conglomerate, would turn its attention on other
cosmetics concerns and Avon has been mentioned by Wall Street
analysts as a possibility.
   Avon owns several properties that Unilever, which has said it
would like to increase its interests in expensive, or prestige,
items, might find appealing. Among Avon's prestige products are the
fragrances Red and Giorgio and actress Cher's Uninhibited scent.
   The financial markets have bid up Avon stock on the hunch that a
suitor might come calling.
   Amway, based in Ada, Mich., was founded about 30 years ago and
is closely held by Jay Van Andel and Richard DeVos. It has become
the second-largest direct sales firm after Avon and says it has
more than 1 million distributors vs. Avon's 1.475 million
independent sales representatives worldwide.
   Telephone calls to Amway seeking comment on its intentions were
not returned.
   Calls to Jacobs also went unreturned. He has had experience with
the direct sales business as the owner of Watkins Products Co., a
personal products company, which uses the door-to-door technique.
</TEXT>
