<FIRST>r f PM-SteelTalks     05-04 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Talks,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Settles, Reports Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. and the United
Steelworkers reached a tentative contract settlement that would
restore wages and benefits that union members gave up during the
last six years, according to a published report.
   An agreement would make Bethlehem the first to settle of four
major steelmakers negotiating early replacements for contracts that
expire July 31. The contracts cover 43,600 USW members.
   The Allentown Morning Call reported Wednesday that the union's
21-member negotiating committee will vote Friday on terms the USW
negotiators presented Tuesday in Pittsburgh.
   ``The framework of an agreement is coming together,'' said union
spokesman Gary Hubbard.
   He confirmed the internal union briefing Tuesday night and the
vote Friday, but he declined to comment on the Morning Call's
report that wages would rise by several dollars over the term of
the contract.
   The pact would run longer than the three-year term of each of
the two previous agreements, the Morning Call said.
   Each of the 20,500 USW members at Bethlehem also would get
$1,000 signing bonuses, and the contract would restore three paid
holidays plus premium pay for work on Sunday, the newspaper said.
   Another union official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the tentative agreement meets the union's goals of restoring
concessions made in the last six years to help Bethlehem withstand
an industry slump. He, too, declined comment on the terms published
by the Morning Call.
   If approved Friday by the negotiating committee, the Bethlehem
agreement would go to the union international executive board and
then to the rank and file.
   Contracts also expire July 31 for 11,600 USW members at Inland
Steel Industries Inc., 6,800 at National Steel Corp., and 4,700 at
Armco Inc.
</TEXT>
