<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     05-04 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incentives Working Some as Sales Rise During April</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales, Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers' incentives appear to be working some
magic, as sales during April bounced back from levels a month
before and a year earlier, but the pace may taper off in May.
   Last month's vehicle sales ran 7.6 percent ahead of last April's
pace, the eight major automakers with U.S. plants reported
Wednesday.
   But during April 21-30, the carmakers said their car and light
truck sales were down 0.7 percent, falling to an average daily rate
of 46,394, compared with a rate of 46,736 during the same time last
year.
   The industry was focused on April sales after the nation's Big
Three automakers introduced new incentive packages at the beginning
of the month that were designed to inject some adrenalin into the
sluggish sales recorded in March.
   ```March sales created fears that the market was drying up and
April sales figures reversed that,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. of New York.
   ``The results of the incentives have been gratifying for us,''
said Robert Rewey, vice president for North American sales for Ford
Motor Co.
   In April, Ford cornered 30.3 percent of the U.S.-made car
market, compared with 45.9 percent for General Motors Corp. and
13.3 percent for Chrysler Corp. In April 1988, Ford held 28.6
percent of the same market, GM had 48.3 percent and Chrysler
accounted for 14.6 percent.
   Typically, automakers let their inventories build during the
first two months of the year in anticipation of active sales during
March and April, as Americans prepare to take to the road during
summer vacations and weekend trips.
   Automakers with U.S. plants reported a sales rate of 37,708
vehicles during March of this year, 10.3 percent behind the rate
for April, giving an indication that the incentives were working.
   ``I think the incentives have spurred people in here,'' said
Jack Adler, sales manager of Galles Chevrolet-Geo in Albuquerque,
N.M.
   ``April sales reduced inventory,'' Merlis said. ``They showed
that incentives at least worked a little and there is no sign of a
downward spiral.''
   Automakers became concerned about their inventories in March
when softer-than-expected sales coupled with ambitious production
schedules expanded inventories.
   To counter that and to entice buyers, GM, Ford and Chrysler a
month ago introduced such new incentive programs as low financing
and cash rebate offers. The Ford program expires May 31, GM's runs
out June 5 and Chrysler's are in effect indefinitely.
   Despite the year-to-year sales increase in April, the rate was
disappointing to Tom Webb, a senior economist for the National
Automobile Dealers Association in McLean, Va.
   ``I think it implies that the underlying demand is much weaker
than most people expected,'' he said. ``I think they're either
going to have to do something to spur sales or (enact) further
production cuts.''
   There has been speculation that the manufacturers will take
longer than usual in the late summer and early autumn to prepare
factories for the 1990 models, some of which already are in
showrooms. Such a move could further reduce 1989 inventories.
   But Merlis said Wednesday's figures might defuse that
speculation.
   ``April sales obviate the need for wholesale production cuts,''
he said. ``Although I think we'll have a normal cyclical cooldown
this year, April suggests that sales are not falling off a cliff.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
