<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     05-04 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady in European trading late
this morning, with volume sharply cut by the Ascension day holiday
in much of Europe.
   Gold prices moved down.
   Only British, Italian and a few Swiss banks were actively
trading in the foreign exchange market.
   ``The market is in effect very lazy. There have been a few small
corporate orders, but that's about it,'' one Italian trader said.
   The dollar was supported by bullish sentiment but was capped by
fear of heavy central bank intervention, dealers said. The central
banks showed their presence repeatedly over the past few days when
the dollar made attempts to move higher, they said.
   The Japanese market was closed for a holiday.
   In London, the dollar was quoted at 133.85 yen, compared with
133.93 yen late Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8880 West German marks, down from
1.8900; 1.6810 Swiss francs, down from 1.6830; 6.3725 French
francs, unchanged; 2.1290 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1270; 1,380.00
