<FIRST>r f PM-HotDogs-Japan     05-04 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hot Dogs-Japan,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago-Style Hot Dogs Headed For Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As slogans go, ``The heartful food with a harmony
taste'' lacks the gusto of ``Drag it through the garden,'' but a
Japanese company is hoping it will strike the right chord with
Tokyo office workers hungry for a taste of Chicago.
   The product is the Chicago-style hot dog: an all-beef weiner
with tomatoes, onions, mustard, relish, cucumbers, jalapeno peppers
and celery salt in a poppy-seed bun.
   Chicago Foods Corp., a Tokyo-based company formed by the Japan
Tobacco Co., the Kitoku Rice Co. and Yonekyu, meat-processing
company, plans to open the first Chicago Hot Dogs stand in Tokyo in
July with managers trained in a Chicago-area hot-dog restaurant.
   Richard Portillo, the local entrepreneur who struck the deal
with Chicago Foods, said he hopes Chicago-style hot dogs will be as
big a hit in Japan as McDonald's hamburgers, which are available at
more than 650 locations
   ``Nobody's taken a concept like the hot dog and tried to do
something like this in Japan,'' Portillo said Wednesday in a
telephone interview from his car, which has license plates reading
TOPDOG1.
   Actually, the Japanese can already buy something called a hot
dog but it's a far cry from the hefty handful available in Chicago.
The Asian fast-food chain Lotteria sells a version consisting of
spiced meat chunks in a casing, and sausages coated with batter and
deep-fried are popular festival fare.
   But the Chicago-style dog is another breed altogether, said Paul
Chang, a Chinese-born, American-educated Chicago Foods employee who
is learning the hot dog business from Portillo.
   ``We call it a harmony taste,'' he said. ``From end to end of
bun, you can have the same flavor at any bite.''
   Chang said Chicago Foods' advertising will also reflect their
product's heritage.
   ``In the Midwest, you call this place the heartland, right? So
we call this food heartful food. Heartful food with a harmony
taste.''
   Portillo, whose 11 namesake restaurants dot Chicago's western
suburbs, reached an agreement in August to teach the Japanese
company the secrets of his success.
   He said Chicago Foods selected his company as a model after
scouring the country for a chain offering a uniquely American food.
   The Japanese company sent Chang and three other prospective
restaurant managers to the Chicago area this spring for eight weeks
of training at Portillo's restaurant in Naperville. They will
return to Japan later this month.
   If all goes well with its first two outlets in Tokyo, Chicago
Foods plans to open 70 restaurants within three years, said
Portillo, who will receive a percentage of the company's sales for
20 years.
   Portillo said he also received a ``large fee'' up front, but he
would not disclose the amount. He said his Chicago restaurants had
sales of more than $20 million last year.
   Chang said he eats hot dogs every day, usually with the works,
while the training group's leader, Takashi Kogahara, prefers only
onions, tomatoes and cucumbers.
   In Japan, he said, Chicago Foods may add grilled onions and
shredded lettuce to the list of condiments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TaxHelpers     05-04 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Helpers,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Time Pays Off For H&amp;R Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helping people figure out how much to
pay Uncle Sam paid off for H&amp;R Block Inc. this year.
   The company prepared 13,090,000 tax returns worldwide, according
to preliminary figures released Wednesday by the Kansas City-based
firm.
   That was an increase of 526,000, or 4.2 percent, from 1988. The
returns accounted for $630.9 million in taxes.
   The figures bucked a trend in the tax-preparation business, the
company said. Usually, fewer people use tax preparers in the second
year after tax-overhaul legislation is enacted, said Donald Ayers,
Block's vice president for finance.
   After the Tax Reform Act of 1986 went into effect, Block had a
record increase in the number of tax returns it prepared, Ayers
said. But the company had expected trouble this year.
   ``In the first year after tax reform we always have a boost in
business because people are confused,'' Ayers said. ``But in the
second year, the numbers decrease because many people go back to
self-preparation.''
   Block and its franchises operate more than 8,700 tax-preparation
offices worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
