<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Northwest-Airport     05-04 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest-Airport,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Officials Hope to Block Airline Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Carr and Wayne County officials
oppose a debt financed buyout of Northwest Airlines' parent
company, fearing it could ground expansion plans at Detroit
Metropolitan Airport.
   ``We're fighting for our lives,'' Wayne County Executive Ed
McNamara said Wednesday.
   Northwest and takeover specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
declined to comment Wednesday on a Wall Street Journal report that
KKR, with access to $413 million in Michigan pension funds, might
bid for the airline.
   Marvin Davis, who bid $2.7 million for the parent company, NWA
Inc., in March, has agreed to a truce in his proxy fight for
control of NWA.
   Michigan has committed $413 million to KKR from five state
employee pension funds since 1982. KKR has drawn $171 million and
the state has realized a 40 percent return on the investment, a
state Department of Treasury spokesman said.
   KKR has agreed to study any Michigan-based company trying to
resist a takeover, but has said it would emerge as a ``white
knight'' only if that would be profitable.
   KKR would have to formally request any state funds wanted for a
Northwest takeover, the Treasury Department spokesman said.
   Northwest is the largest airline at Metro Airport and would pay
the biggest share of costs of a planned expansion.
   McNamara said Wayne County lawyers will file a lawsuit Friday
aimed at blocking the sale of NWA Inc. to anyone who would finance
the acquisition with huge amounts of debt.
   A county contract with the airline bars a takeover or merger
that reduces NWA's net worth, he said.
   Carr said in Washington he would introduce a bill next week to
require the U.S. Department of Transportation to examine airline
buyouts more closely.
   The bill would prohibit the sales if high debts from the buyout
threatened to compromise safety or the carrier's ability to
operate, said Carr, a member of the House Appropriations
Committee's transportation subcommittee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
