<TEXT>
   The stock market headed lower today, continuing
its week-long pullback as traders awaited the employment report for
April.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, off 25.10 points from
Monday through Wednesday, slipped another 4.04 to 2,389.66 in the
first half hour today.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 373 up, 532 down and
528 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.87 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Wall Street attention has focused all week on Friday's scheduled
report from the Labor Department on the employment situation for
April.
   Analysts expect the data to serve as evidence of whether the
economy continued to slow last month after giving evidence of
losing some momentum in the first quarter.
   Hopes have been increasing on Wall Street that the Federal
Reserve is succeeding in its campaign to cool down inflation
without tightening credit so much as to cause a recession.
   But that belief was challenged at the start of this week when a
trade association of corporate purchasing managers reported that
business activity picked up in April.
   Advance estimates call for the employment report to show an
increase of 225,000 to 250,000 in nonfarm payrolls.
   Losers among the blue chips included DuPont, down ] at 108};
International Paper, down \ at 49\; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph,
down [ at 34{, and Coca-Cola, down [ at 54}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.16 to 172.19. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .25 at 345.08.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 9.16 to
2,393.70, bringing its loss over the week's first three sessions to
25.10 points.
   Advancing and declining issues were evenly balanced on the NYSE,
with 680 up, 690 down and 544 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 171.69 million shares, against 172.56
million in the previous session.
