<HEAD>Market Opens Mostly Higher in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade with little news to
stimulate the market.
   Analysts say gains in corn and soybeans may be limited by the
National Weather Service's 6-to-10-day outlook that calls for light
rain over the next two days in western grain states.
   Overnight rain in Kansas and unconfirmed rumors of Chinese
interest in U.S. wheat may have a dampening effect on wheat futures.
   Trading in the market may be on the quiet side, with most of
Europe and Japan on holiday.
   ``The market is treading water in the early going,'' said Frank
Kuba, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 3{ cents higher with
contracts for delivery in May at $4.41 a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.75} a bushel; oats were 1{
cents to 3 cents higher with May at $1.89 a bushel; soybeans were
2{ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with May at $7.48 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .15 cent higher with June at
72.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with May at 76.80 cents a pound; hogs were .27 cent to .07
cent lower with June at 47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.05 cent lower to .35 cent higher with May at 31.05 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled higher Wednesday, while pork futures
were mostly lower.
