<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-RetailSales     05-04 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retailers' Report Varied April Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's biggest store chains today posted varied April
sales tallies and analysts said more spring-like weather in the
latter half of the month spurred seasonal purchases, partly
compensating for earlier weakness.
   Softness in sales at several big general retailers reflected
slower economic activity due to costlier debt burdens and inflation
worries, analysts said.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said sales
on an industry-wide basis this year have barely outpaced the
inflation rate, indicating that consumer spending, a key element in
economic growth, is easing. Feiner has scaled down his forecast for
average 1989 retail sales growth to 5.5 percent from 6 percent,
based on sales results so far this year.
   Nonetheless, analysts found some signs in the April figures
indicating that shopping momentum is picking up, particularly for
women's clothing and seasonal goods.
   Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with Seidler Amdec Securities Inc.
in Los Angeles, said retail business was only so-so in the first
two weeks of April.
   But it became better once temperatures turned warm enough to
remind people they needed new spring and summer clothing,
do-it-yourself gadgetry, patio furniture and other outdoor gear.
   ``The arrival of spring weather was the main theme,'' said
Tashjian.
   Furthermore, most big retailers waited out the sluggish period
rather than engaging in widespread price cutting to attract
customers, easing the impact on their profit margins, Tashjian said.
   Today's results were from some of the biggest general
merchandise chains in the United States, plus apparel retailers.
Monthly retail sales figures from the government are more
comprehensive and include the take at other types of establishments
such as auto dealerships, supermarkets and restaurants.
   Sears Roebuck and Co., the nation's biggest retailer, said its
low-price policy introduced earlier this year continued attracting
shoppers.
   Chicago-based Sears said its sales rose 9.2 percent to $2.5
billion in the 4 weeks ended April 29 from $2.29 billion. Sales at
stores open at least a year, called same or comparable store sales,
rose 6.8 percent.
   Retailers and industry analysts consider same-store sales a more
accurate indication of a company's performance than totals that
include sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports
same-store sales.
   Sears sales through the first quarter of its financial year came
to $7.62 billion, up 11.2 percent from the 1988 first quarter
figure of $6.85 billion.
   K mart Corp., the second-largest general retailer, based in
Troy, Mich., said sales gains in the second half of April at its
outdoor garden shop, home improvement and ladies' apparel
departments only partially offset weakness in the first two weeks
of the month.
   K mart's sales in the four weeks ended April 26 totaled $2.05
billion, up 2.3 percent from April 1988's $2.01 billion. On a
same-store basis though, K mart's sales fell 1 percent.
   Sales at K mart through the first quarter came to $6.07 billion,
up 3.9 percent from $5.84 billion.
   Here are some of the other results:
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the discounter based in Bentonville, Ark.,
said its sales rose 25 percent in April to $1.98 billion from $1.58
billion. Its same-store sales were up 11 percent for the month.
   Sales at Wal-Marts through the first quarter were $5.37 billion,
up 25 percent over $4.28 billion in 1988's first quarter.
   Dallas-based J.C. Penney Co. Inc. said its sales amounted to
$1.06 billion in the four weeks ended April 29, up 9.3 percent from
$966 million a year earlier. On a comparable store basis, April
sales were up 6.7 percent.
   For the first quarter, Penney's sales came to $3.1 billion, a
4.7 percent increase from $2.97 billion in 1988.
   F.W. Woolworth Co., based in New York, said its domestic sales
increased 11.1 in April 29 to $348 million from $313 million.
Same-store sales gained 6.7 percent.
   For Woolworth's year to date, domestic sales totaled $1.12
billion, up 7.7 percent from $1.04 billion.
   Limited Inc.'s 4-week sales were $307 million, up 22 percent
from $251.1 million in the 1988 period. Comparable store sales rose
18 percent.
   For the first quarter of 1989, Limited's sales rose to $946.6
million, up 19 percent from $811.1 million. The specialty apparel
retailer is based in Columbus, Ohio.
   Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc., based in Los Angeles, reported
April sales of $190.3 million, up 3.1 percent from $184.5 million
in the corresponding 1988 period. Same-store sales rose 2.2 percent
in April.
   For the first quarter, sales were $595.3 million, up 9 percent
from $546.1 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
