<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ExxonStock     05-04 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Exxon Stock,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Permanent Fund Corp. Plans to Withhold Exxon Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The public agency that manages Alaska's
$10 billion oil-wealth savings account will send a message to Exxon
Corp. at its annual meeting by withholding 650,600 shares of Exxon
stock from voting.
   The Alaska Permanent Fund Corp. sent a letter to Exxon Chairman
Lawrence Rawl this week, informing him of the largely symbolic
action to underscore Alaska's concern over the Exxon Valdez oil
spill in Prince William Sound.
   ``This incident has brought incredible devastation to regions of
this state and will have long-lasting consequences,'' wrote Oral E.
Freeman, chairman of the Permanent Fund board.
   Freeman urged Rawl ``to take all necessary and appropriate
action to insure that the oil spill is dealt with fully and in a
timely matter.''
   The Permanent Fund is a state trust created in 1976 to ensure
that Alaska residents benefit from the state's oil wealth long
after the oil is gone.
   The fund's investment in Exxon is the second largest of its
stock portfolio and is worth more than $28.1 million. However, it
represents only a small percentage of the total shares of Exxon's
outstanding stock.
   Withholding the shares at Exxon's annual meeting May 18 in
Parsippany, N.J., will mean the votes they represent cannot be used
to establish a quorum or for any vote of the stockholders.
   Exxon spokesman Dave Parish said Exxon officials had not seen
Freeman's letter and would have no comment.
   Fund board member Byron I. Mallott, chief executive officer of
Sealaska Corp., suggested the board take the action. He said it
probably would have no major effect on the meeting other than to
make a point.
   ``This is one way that corporations speak to one another,''
Mallott said. ``We wanted to make a responsible statement without
being negative, without casting any kinds of aspersions. But we
also wanted to make it clear how seriously we consider the
circumstances that Exxon has essentially placed the state of Alaska
in.''
   Freeman said in his letter that he hopes Exxon will meet its
responsibility to clean up the spill, and that the Permanent Fund
will be able to vote its shares in subsequent annual meetings.
   The board's action Tuesday was unanimous. Mallott also said
Sealaska Corp., one of 13 regional native corporations established
under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act, was withholding its
2,600 Exxon shares from voting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-04 0106</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0109</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices in London closed higher but below
their session peaks on Thursday with British institutions showing
interest as the market again approached its post-crash highs.
   Trading volumes picked up from the low levels at the start of
the week. Despite holidays in many European capitals, London
dealers reported active trading in some leading stocks with some
strong gains in the insurance, retailing and electronics sectors.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 13.3
points, or 0.6 percent, higher at 2,119.0.
   Volume came to 540.4 million shares, compared with 411.1 million
shares Wednesday.
</TEXT>
