   The stock market gave ground today, continuing
its week-long pullback as traders awaited the employment report for
April.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, off 25.10 points from
Monday through Wednesday, slipped another 12.65 to 2,381.05 by 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 8 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 634 up, 715 down and
539 unchanged.
   Wall Street attention has focused all week on Friday's scheduled
report from the Labor Department on the employment situation for
April.
   Analysts expect the data to serve as evidence of whether the
economy continued to slow last month after giving evidence of
losing some momentum in the first quarter.
   Hopes have been increasing on Wall Street that the Federal
Reserve is succeeding in its campaign to cool down inflation
without tightening credit so much as to cause a recession.
   But that belief was challenged at the start of this week when a
trade association of corporate purchasing managers reported that
business activity picked up in April.
   Advance estimates call for the employment report to show an
increase of 225,000 to 250,000 in nonfarm payrolls.
   In the blue-chip sector, International Business Machines rose ]
to 110|; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was unchanged at 34|;
Eastman Kodak lost [ to 43\, and Procter &amp; Gamble was down | at 96\.
   Avon dropped } to 36[ after jumping 4} Wednesday on news that
Irwin Jacobs, the Minneapolis investor, and Amway Corp. have
acquired a 10.3 percent stake in the company. Avon said it did not
want to be acquired.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .29 to 172.06. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .84 at 345.67.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 111.06 million shares with two
hours to go.
