<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Western     05-04 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Western,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Savings Reports Nearly $100 Million Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Savings and Loan Association, which wiped
out the equity of its shareholders and fell below regulatory
capital guidelines at the end of 1988, on Thursday reported a $99.8
million first-quarter loss.
   The loss compares with one of $1.9 million for the first three
months of last year.
   It marks the second straight heavy quarterly loss for the
thrift, which has shrunk by $602 million in deposits and $773
million in assets since March 31, 1988.
   Chairman Robert W. Stallings, who took over April 3, said
continuing additions to real estate loan-loss reserves pushed the
thrift into another loss.
   Depositors should not worry, he said, because of the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp.'s standard guarantee on the first $100,000
of deposits in each account.
   However, he noted that the quarterly loss reduced Western's
regulatory net worth to $99 million. That is about 1.7 percent of
liabilities and less than half of what federal regulators have said
Western should maintain for stability.
</TEXT>
