<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-04 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Futures Close Mixed in Light Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed in
light trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, with the U.S.
offer of subsidized grain to the Soviet Union continuing to have a
positive effect on wheat.
   Scattered showers in the Midwest forecast for Thursday night and
Friday kept corn and soybean prices under wraps.
   Wheat prices rallied on word that the People's Republic of China
may be interested in purchasing U.S. wheat. Prices also went up
with the announcement that the Soviet Union has ordered 300,000
metric tons of wheat under the program that subsidizes the sale of
U.S. grain to foreign countries.
   The White House announced earlier this week that it has offered
the Soviets 1.5 million metric tons of grain under the program.
   Trading in soybeans were lackluster, with slow movement of the
bean to market helping May prices, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst
with LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   Forecasts for additional rain in Western crop states put
pressure on new crops as did word that the harvest of the Brazilian
soybean crop was 75 percent complete, Gidel said.
   Wheat closed 2{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in May at $4.35 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1{ cents
lower with May at $2.76 a bushel; oats were 3\ cent to 4} cents
higher with May at $1.91} a bushel; soybeans were 5{ cents lower to
2} cents higher with May at $7.49{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
