<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     05-04 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Says Two-Thirds of Prime Stock Has Been Tendered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. shareholders have tendered
more than 66 percent of the company's outstanding stock to MAI
Basic Four Inc. under a $20-per-share hostile takeover bid, MAI
said Thursday.
   The tender offer is still blocked by the U.S. District Court.
But MAI said this week it was preparing to satisfy the sole
remaining condition for ending the injunction by mailing Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.'s year-end financial statements to all Prime
stockholders.
   Judge A. David Mazzone previously ruled that the statements from
Drexel, MAI's investment bank and adviser, needed to be provided to
shareholders to comply with federal disclosure requirements. He
said he would lift the injunction 10 days after MAI certifies that
the statements have been sent out.
   MAI, based in Tustin, Calif., said it has extended its offer,
valued at about $970 million, until May 31.
   The injunction does not prevent stockholders from tendering
their shares, but it does block MAI, controlled by New York
investor Bennett S. LeBow, from taking ownership of the stock.
   Prime, based in Natick, is a minicomputer maker with the second
largest share of the market for computer aided design and
manufacturing systems. International Business Machines Corp. is the
leading CAD-CAM supplier.
   Prime's board of directors has rejected MAI's bid as too low. A
Prime spokeswoman, Paula Levis, said it is continuing to look for a
buyer willing to pay more than $20 per share.
   MAI also has announced plans to wage a proxy battle for control
of Prime's board at its June 14 annual meeting.
</TEXT>
