<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-04 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late buying spree in crude oil pushed
near-term contract prices higher Thursday and helped pull up prices
of gasoline and heating oil.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 48
cents to settle at $20.58 a barrel, after gaining 30 cents on
Wednesday. Longer-term contracts, however, were down by as much as
22 cents.
   Heating oil for June delivery ended the session up 0.73 cent at
48.59 cents a gallon. The contract had gained 0.25 cent in the
previous session.
   Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
the June contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled up 0.23
cent at 69.62 cents a gallon following Wednesday's loss of 1.86
cents. Longer-term contracts were slightly lower.
   Analysts said fear over supply pushed prices higher. They said
traders remained concerned over disruption in North Sea oil
production. Late Wednesday, Shell Exploration and Production Co.
said repairs on its Cormorant Alpha platform in the North Sea were
likely to take longer than anticipated, delaying the resumption of
operations until later this month.
   ``We're still seeing follow-through (buying) on that news,''
which broke late in the previous session, noted John Hill, vice
president at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   In addition, reports that Saudi Arabia is not exceeding its
production quota ``got the market rolling right back, recovering
all the ground it lost over the past two days,'' Hill said. Volume
was active.
   Gasoline prices showed the weakest gains. Analysts said
indications that refiners will be able to meet near-term demand
prevented gasoline from following crude prices sharply higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
