<DOCNO> AP890504-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     05-04 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.2 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 468 money market mutual
funds rose $1.2 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise to a record $304.17 billion in the seven-day period
ended Wednesday, followed a $435.5 million drop in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The latest increase puts money fund assets back on a
record-setting pace after last week's downturn, which represented
the first decline after fund assets posted new highs in each of the
previous 15 consecutive weeks.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 232 general purpose funds rose $119.8 million to $99.78
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds dropped $120.1 million to
$128.9 billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds rose $1.2
billion to $75.5 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.15 percent from 9.19 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 9.16 percent from 9.15 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 34 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.63 percent as of Wednesday from 6.62 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged from a week earlier, at 5.15 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.34
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged from the
previous week. Yields were 9.51 percent on 1-year CDs, unchanged;
9.32 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 9.32 percent; and 9.20
percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
