<SECOND>AM-Atlantis Bids,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump's Bid For Atlantis Challenged By Other Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Donald Trump's agreement to buy
Elsinore's Atlantis Casino Hotel is called into question by the
casino's state-appointed conservator, at least five higher offers
have been made to purchase the financially troubled gaming hall.
   The latest offer came Thursday from Bob Stupak, owner of Vegas
World Hotel-Casino in Las Vegas, Nev., who offered $64 million for
the Atlantis _ $1 million higher than Trump's signed agreement.
   Trump intends to close the Atlantis' casino and operate the
facility as a hotel, but Stupak said he would keep the casino open.
   Joseph M. Nolan, the conservator operating the Atlantis since
its license expired April 14, said he is accepting inquiries from
anyone who wants to submit purchase offers.
   Nolan told the state Casino Control Commission that he questions
the validity of Trump's agreement with Elsinore Corp. because it
may have been signed after he became conservator.
   All the new bids would keep the Atlantis casino intact, Nolan
said.
   Trump was not available for comment Thursday, said his secretary
in New York, Norma Foerderer.
   In Las Vegas, Stupak, 47, is known as a colorful character. He
ran for mayor in 1987 and lost in a close race. Earlier this year,
he won a $1 million bet on the Super Bowl.
</TEXT>
