<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-04 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished at varied levels against
major foreign currencies Thursday as Federal Reserve intervention
and a comment by the central bank's vice chairman sent mixed
signals to the markets.
   Gold prices ended with minor losses in U.S. trading after moving
ahead overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a troy
ounce of gold bullion at $376.70 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
Wednesday's late bid of $377.40.
   Foreign exchange dealers in the United States said the dollar
headed higher after Fed Governor Manuel Johnson indicated the
dollar's strength is not a problem as far as the central bank's
policies are concerned.
   Later, traders detected that the Fed sold dollars when the U.S.
currency was trading at 1.8960 West German marks. The intervention
did little to discourage buyers, though, and the dollar ended the
day at 1.89575 marks, up from 1.89325 on Wednesday.
   Thomas Palladino, an assistant vice president at Amsterdam
Rotterdam Bank in New York, described the Fed's action as a largely
symbolic attempt to put the currency markets on notice that the
central bank won't tolerate significantly higher dollar levels.
   Activity in the markets was held down by traders' reluctance to
establish new positions ahead of Friday's release of U.S.
unemployment figures for April, which will furnish one of the first
indications of how the economy performed last month.
   A reduction in the nation's jobless rate and an expansion in
payrolls could push the dollar higher and cause government
authorities to intervene.
   European currency and precious metals trading was lighter than
usual because many markets were closed for Ascension Day. Financial
markets in West Germany, Switzerland, France and the Netherlands
were closed.
   Japanese markets also were closed for a holiday.
   The dollar traded late in London at 133.95 Japanese yen, up from
the late London rate on Wednesday of 133.93 yen. Later, in New
York, the dollar was quoted at 134.195 yen, down from 134.295 on
Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6841 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6847. Sterling fetched $1.68125
in later New York dealing, a weakening from Wednesday's $1.6820.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared to Wednesday rates,
included: 1.69105 Swiss francs, up from 1.68705; 1.18305 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.18415; 6.4005 French francs, up from 6.3905;
and 1,384.50 Italian lire, up from 1,383.05.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.8915 West German marks, up from 1.8900;
1.6860 Swiss francs, up from 1.6830; 6.3875 French francs, up from
6.3725; 2.1290 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1270; 1,380.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,379.00, and 1.1841 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1830.
   Gold and silver turned in mixed performances in trading around
the world.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
settled at $377.70 a troy ounce, down from $378.40 on Wednesday.
   The late bid price for gold in London was $378.25 a troy ounce,
up from $377.97 late Wednesday. The market was closed in Zurich.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $378.45 bid, up from
$376.55.
   Silver bullion closed on New York's Comex at $5.613 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's settlement of $5.635. Silver bullion
traded late in London at a bid $5.66 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $5.65.
</TEXT>
