<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TrumpGame     05-04 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump Game,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheeler-Dealer Faces New Type of Board</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: `Trump The Game' is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST LONGMEADOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald J. Trump, a consummate
player in the high-stakes world of big business, was the new game
in town Thursday as he toured Milton Bradley Co. to herald new
editions of ``Trump The Game.''
   Women workers screeched as he passed by, and one cried when he
bussed her on the cheek. ``He kissed me! He kissed me!'' said a
shaky Grace Adams of Springfield, Mass., who has worked 31 years at
the company.
   The real estate mogul flew to the western Massachusetts factory
of 2,300 workers in the huge black Trump helicopter to fulfill a
promise to the company that expects ``Trump The Game'' to be the
biggest seller in its 129-year history, despite its $25 pricetag.
   ``They were intent on having me come up to meet the real
people,'' Trump said. ``These are the people doing the work. To
hell with the executives.''
   Employees clapped at each stop in the 45-minute visit, women
sighed ``Isn't he handsome?'' and men lined up for autographs on
the paper money that bears his likeness and comes in denominations
no smaller than $10 million.
   More than 2 million games are scheduled for production by year's
end. It is the No. 1 seller in the 300 stores that have received
advance copies, Milton Bradley President George Ditomassi said.
   Neither the company nor Trump will disclose his royalties, but
both said he is donating proceeds to charities for the homeless and
for research on AIDS, cerebral palsy and multiple sclerosis.
   The board game is a sophisticated battle in which players first
bid against each other _ using Trump cards, of course _ for
airlines, casinos, luxury hotels and other Trump properties, then
try to negotiate deals.
   ``If you don't do well at this game, you should stay on
9-to-5,'' Trump advised, adding that the game is tough even for a
veteran like him.
   But he resisted explaining its appeal. ``If I said it, you'd say
I have a big ego, so why say it?''
   Although several game manufacturers tried to peddle their ideas
to Trump, the one that caught his eye came from an independent
inventor from Chicago who suggested Milton Bradley as a
manufacturer.
   Trump said he settled on the nation's largest board game maker,
because ``the loyalty, decisiveness and professionalism of this
company is just unbelievable.'' As the applause died down, he
barked at workers: ``OK, get some overtime.''
   Trump later denied rumors that he planned to run for mayor of
New York, which had surfaced with a recent full-page newspaper ad
he took out supporting the death penalty.
   And he sneered at the suggestion that a new bidder for
strikebound Eastern Airlines' Northeast shuttle could affect his
$365 million offer for the service. ``It's not serious,'' he said
of Wednesday's bid from regional carrier America West Airlines. ``I
have not even heard of them.''
   Besides, Trump said, his contract with Eastern guarantees him a
lot of money even if the deal falls through. ``They'll pay me a
fairly substantial amount of money and I'll go home,'' he said.
``But I would rather get it.''
   Under the contract, Trump would receive $8 million from Eastern
if the deal isn't consummated, according to sources close to the
situation.
   Trump declined to jibe at cartoonist Garry Trudeau for the comic
series that depicted him as a mogul with an overriding ego. ``I
think it's an honor,'' he said. ``Garry Trudeau is a talented guy.''
</TEXT>
