<FIRST>r f AM-NABET-ABC     05-04 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NABET-ABC,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mediators Seeks Meeting Between ABC and Engineers Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal mediator intervened Thursday in a
dispute between Capital Cities-ABC Inc. and its engineers' union in
an effort to get both sides to return to the bargaining table.
   The workers on Wednesday rejected what the network called its
final offer.
   The National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians
wants to meet May 11 but the company says that's too late.
   The mediator, Kenneth Kowalski, said he would not call a meeting
until both sides agree on a time, place and date for it.
   The union offered to meet May 11 at 10 a.m. in Washington at the
offices of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service,
according to NABET spokesman John Krieger.
   Patti Matson, an ABC spokeswoman, said the company felt May 11
would not leave time for the union membership to vote again on the
offer.
   ABC's offer includes a 10 percent bonus in the first year of the
pact if it is ratified by May 15. The lump sum payment drops to 3
percent if it is ratified after May 15.
   Union leaders have ruled out a reconsideration vote, and so far,
the members have not authorized a strike.
