<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-04 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Throws New York Markets Off Stride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweep by federal agents through New York commodity markets
helped slow trading somewhat on Thursday, analysts said.
   Trading slowed at the New York Mercantile Exchange in
mid-session on news that the government had subpoenaed the records
of several firms and traders in connection with a criminal
investigation of trading practices at that market and other New
York futures exchanges.
   Energy futures were mixed on the Mercantile Exchange as crude
oil futures rose over increased concern with North Sea oil
production. In other markets, grain and soybean futures were mixed;
livestock prices were higher and pork futures lower, and precious
metals were mixed.
   Traders pushed crude oil prices higher on news that the full
flow of oil exports from the North Sea's Brent complex may not
resume as soon as expected. Production was disrupted in April by a
platform explosion.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 48 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in June at $20.58 a barrel;
heating oil was .03 cent lower to .73 cent higher with June at
48.59 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .05 cent lower to .23
cent higher with June at 69.62 cents a gallon.
   Trading slowed on word of criminal and civil investigations of
four of the five New York futures exchanges. Federal agents issued
subpoenas for information the markets, seized records at one firm
and subpoenaed more than 50 traders.
   Exchange and U.S. Postal Service officials said authorities were
seeking information about trading practices by firms and
individuals.
   ``Trading was well below that of yesterday, and (today's)
problems may have may have been a factor,'' Robert Baker, an
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York, said
Thursday.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed in light trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices rallied on word that the Peoples Republic of China
may be interested in purchasing U.S. wheat. Prices also were
affected by the announcement that the Soviet Union has ordered
300,000 metric tons of wheat under the program that subsidizes the
sale of U.S. grain to foreign countries.
   The White House announced earlier this week it has offered the
Soviets 1.5 million metric tons of grain.
   Soybean trading was was lackluster, with slow movement of the
crop to market helping May prices, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst
with LIT America Inc. in Chicago. Forecasts for additional rain in
western crop states put pressure on soybeans and corn, Gidel said.
   Wheat was 2{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with May at $4.35 a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 1{ cents lower with May at $2.75} a
bushel; oats were 3\ cent to 4} cents higher with May at $1.91} a
bushel; soybeans were 5\ cents lower to 3\ cents higher with May at
$7.50 a bushel.
   Precious metals were mixed on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold was $2.10 lower to .70 cents higher with May at $377.70 a
troy ounce; silver was 2.2 cents to 2.3 cents lower with May at
$5.613 cents a troy ounce.
   Livestock futures prices were mixed and pork futures were lower
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle prices were boosted by the aggressive marketing of
cattle at higher prices.
   Live hog futures were forced lower by concern over heavy
marketings and declines in cash prices, said Phil Stanley, an
independent trader, who added there also was concern prices would
continue to weaken.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .13 cent higher, with June at
72.55; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .35 cent higher with May at
76.95 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .30 cent higher
with June at 47.10 a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to
.30 cent higher with May at 30.82 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
