<FIRST>r f AM-US-SovietTrade     05-04 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Trade,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vanik, Jewish Leader Propose Easing Curbs On Soviet Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-author of a 1972 law that curbed
American trade with the Soviet Union called on President Bush and
Congress today to waive the restriction for one year to encourage
further improvements in human rights under Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``The process under way appears to be in earnest,'' said Charles
A. Vanik, a former Democratic congressman from Ohio who sponsored
the law with the late Sen. Henry M. Jackson, D-Wash., that is
designed to force increased Jewish emigration.
   Vanik's plea was endorsed by Meyer Berger, a member of the board
of the National Conference on Soviet Jewry. He said a waiver would
help stabilize U.S.-Soviet relations and ``send a message that
American Jews recognize the great change in the human rights
process under Gorbachev.''
   The board is due to take up the question of U.S. trade
restrictions at a meeting here next month. Berger, of Pittsburgh,
said he was not speaking for the board.
   The law, known as Jackson-Vanik, denied the Soviet Union the
trading privileges accorded most nations unless Jews were allowed
to emigrate freely.
   Last month, 4,557 Jews left, the highest monthly figure since
October of 1979, the year emigration reached an annual high of
51,320.
   Vanik projected an exodus this year of 38,000 to 43,000. He had
called for a waiver, which is permitted under the law, in 1979, as
well.
   Besides increased Jewish emigration, the former congressman
cited a pledge by Soviet President Gorbachev to abolish all laws
restricting religious and cultural practices.
   ``We cannot expect instant democracy,'' he said in a speech at a
luncheon sponsored by the American Committee on U.S.-Soviet
relations, a private group that seeks reconciliation between the
superpowers. ``We must measure progress in the Soviet Union from
ground zero.''
   Vanik placed himself between proponents of outright repeal of
the law and ``hardliners'' in Congress who, he said, ``will resist
any accommodation with the Soviet Union.''
   He said only about a dozen countries are denied what is known
technically as ``most-favored nation'' trading status. These
include Albania, Cuba, Czechoslovakia, Laos and Romania.
   Vanik said trade with Iran and South Africa is only partially
impeded.
   Even Colombia, the South American country Vanik said is the
major drug supplier to the United States, enjoys
most-favored-nation privileges, he said.
   Berger said a waiver would improve trade and also boost
emigration, providing Israel with skilled Russian immigrants. He
said it also might facilitate the resumption of diplomatic
relations between Jerusalem and Moscow.
   Martin A. Wenick, executive director of the Jewish group, said
at a news conference earlier that in reassessing its position on
Jackson-Vanik the board would consider various factors.
   He said these included whether visas were issued to some 600
long-term ``refusenik'' families _ Jews waiting for years for
permission to emigrate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0293 </DOCNO>
