<FIRST>r f AM-CNW-Japonica     05-04 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CNW-Japonica,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek Administration's Views On CNW Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four congressmen asked the Bush administration on
Thursday to examine a New York investor group's efforts to acquire
CNW Corp., the parent of the Chicago and North Western railroad.
   The Federal Railroad Administration, a government agency, holds
about $143 million in low-interest notes from Chicago-based CNW,
which makes CNW's business the public's business as well, the
congressmen said.
   They aired the concerns in letters to Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Richard
Darman, director of the Office of Management and Budget.
   John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Committee on Energy
and Commerce, urged Brady and Darman to talk with Skinner ``to
develop a coordinated administration approach in the event that
protection of the federal government's ... financial interest with
respect to this proposed acquisition becomes necessary.''
   The letters were also signed by energy committee member Norman
Lent, R-NY, and House transportation subcommittee members Thomas
Luken, D-Ohio, and Bob Whittaker, R-Kan.
   The railroad administration loaned CNW the money in 1977 and
1978 for repairs to the railroad's primary east-west track and
other facilities.
   The congressmen asked the Bush administration members to respond
by May 10.
   Japonica Partners, a limited partnership based in New York,
offered on April 27 to buy CNW for $44 a share, or $658 million for
all the CNW stock that Japonica does not already own. Japonica owns
about 8.8 percent of CNW's stock.
   The companies have been sparring since then, with each side
accusing the other of refusing to negotiate fairly.
   On Thursday, Japonica filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Delaware charging CNW's board of directors with refusing to
negotiate in good faith.
   CNW called the lawsuit ``baseless.''
   Japonica also is waging a proxy fight, asking CNW shareholders
to elect three of its nominees to CNW's board of directors at the
company's May 16 annual meeting.
</TEXT>
