<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DetroitNewspapers     05-04 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Executives Talk About Free Press Future</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit Free Press' parent company Thursday
affirmed its commitment to the newspaper and to pursuing a
long-stalled joint operating agreement with The Detroit News.
   ``We are firmly committed to continue to publish an excellent
and competitive newspaper in Detroit,'' Knight-Ridder Inc.
President James Batten said in a Thursday news release.
   When the U.S. Supreme Court decided Monday to hear a challenge
of the JOA, with a decision expected next year, some analysts
wondered if Miami-based Knight-Ridder would be willing to absorb
the Free Press' losses for another year.
   But the company's board of directors Thursday unanimously agreed
to continue publishing the newspaper while the appeal is pending.
   ``Although we are disappointed by the delay necessitated by the
Supreme Court's decision to review the case, we remain confident
that the court will affirm the actions of the attorney general and
the lower courts,'' Batten said.
   The Free Press and The News, the latter owned by Gannett Co.
Inc., have sought the partial merger since 1986. The papers aim to
cut costs by combining advertising, circulation and production
operations while keeping separate news and editorial departments.
   The Free Press lost $22.7 million in 1988, Knight-Ridder said in
the statement. Gannett hasn't released annual loss figures, but has
said The News lost $64.95 million from 1980 through 1987.
   While the JOA ruling is pending, the Free Press will try to keep
its losses to 1988 levels, Knight-Ridder said.
   And in concert with The News, it will reopen contract
negotiations at once with both newspapers' unions. More than 3,000
union employees have gone without contractual raises since 1986.
   Knight-Ridder has said it would close the Free Press if the JOA
were denied.
</TEXT>
