<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 1955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-US-Japan-Aid     05-04 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan-Aid,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Expertise Sought for Japanese Aid Program, Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American engineers, builders, suppliers and
development experts have an opportunity to earn some of the
trillions of yen Japan plans to pour into overseas economic aid in
the coming years, U.S. aid chief Alan Woods said Thursday.
   Japan, about to replace the United States as the world's largest
foreign aid donor, is interested in making use of U.S. expertise,
Woods, head of the U.S. Agency for International Development, told
reporters.
   Britain has already responded to the Japanese desire for expert
collaboration and ``the British have become procurement agents for
the Japanese aid agency throughout East Africa,'' he said.
   Woods announced that AID is sponsoring conferences in San
Francisco May 10-ll and Orlando, Florida, May 15-16 to help
American enterprises on the Pacific and Atlantic coasts learn about
opportunities in the Japanese overseas development program.
Officials from three Japanese aid agencies will participate in both
meetings, the first such sessions ever held, he said.
   The Japanese have only about 200 foreign aid specialists and
appear eager to draw on the experience of more than 2,000 Americans
working on AID programs, Woods said.
   There is no formal agreement on collaboration between the two
countries' agencies, Woods said in answer to a question. But
foreign participation in Japanese-financed programs outside Japan
is governed by conditions different from those for Japanese
domestic projects, where difficult negotiations were held last year
to gain access for U.S. contractors, he added.
   In Japanese foreign aid, the receiving country has the
responsibility for organizing competitive bidding on projects, it
was pointed out.
   Japan plans to spend $50 billion on overseas economic aid in the
next five years, with the emphasis on building dams, power stations
and transmission facilities, roads, railways, telecommunications,
factories and water management projects, AID officials said.
American aid in recent years has shifted from such major capital
projects to technical assistance, they said.
   Foreign firms are already increasing their share of contracts in
the Japanese aid program, but the U.S. share is dropping, strongly
suggesting ``that the competitive environment has become more
favorable but that potential America bidders are not widely aware
of it,'' an AID announcement said.
   The idea that Japanese aid is tied to the use of Japanese firms
and products is becoming obsolete, and today, ``less than half of
the total is tied,'' said Jerome Sherry, chief of AID's development
assistance staff. By contrast, about two-thirds of the current
year's U.S. aid spending of about $8.5 billion is tied to U.S.
firms and goods, he said in answer to a question.
   Japanese aid has so far have emphasized Asia. The proposed
multibillion-dollar Multilateral Aid Initiative for the
Philippines, led by the United States, Japan, West European
countries and the World Bank, is expected to be the largest program
in any single country.
   The United States and Japan have consulted on projects for
Indonesia and India and potential new progams in Africa, Weeks said.
   He said Koichiro Matsura, director general of the Japanese
Foreign Ministry economic cooperation bureau, voiced interest in
U.S. collaboration when they met in Manila last December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
