<FIRST>r f AM-BeatricePollution     05-04 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beatrice Pollution,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beatrice Denies Concealing Evidence in Pollution Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beatrice Foods Co. has denied that it conspired to
withhold engineering reports and other documents from the families
of leukemia victims who lost a 1986 lawsuit charging the
conglomerate with polluting their drinking water.
   In papers filed late Wednesday in federal court, the company and
its lawyers said they did not ``intentionally conceal'' anything
and said the families had presented no evidence of a conspiracy.
   ``Neither Beatrice nor its counsel intentionally concealed any
documents or information from the plaintiffs or engaged in any
conspiracy to conceal,'' Beatrice attorney Jerome Facher wrote.
   The filing was the latest round in a long-running legal battle
between the families and the Chicago-based food conglomerate. The
families' attorney, Jan Schlichtmann, is appealing the jury verdict
in the case and seeking a new trial.
   In a brief filed last month, Schlichtmann charged that Beatrice
and its Boston law firm, Hale &amp; Dorr, engaged in ``misconduct'' by
concealing documents that could have influenced the case.
Schlichtmann has asked U.S. District Judge Walter Jay Skinner to
find Beatrice in default.
   Under orders from the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, Skinner
is conducting an unusual post-trial hearing into the fairness of
the trial he presided over three years ago. His first task is to
determine whether Beatrice willingly concealed evidence. If so, he
will hold a hearing into whether the evidence was relevant.
   Skinner made no immediate ruling in response to Beatrice's
filing and was not expected to rule until later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890504-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Proposition103-Stocks     05-04 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Proposition 103-Stocks,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street's Verdict: Insurers Lost</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Proposition 103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides are claiming degrees of victory in
the court fight over California's insurance rate-slashing
Proposition 103, but the verdict on Wall Street was unequivocal:
The insurance companies lost.
   Stock prices for several insurers heavily committed to the
California market fell Thursday after the state Supreme Court
upheld most of the voter-approved ballot measure.
   ``We're all sitting here looking at our screens, watching the
stock drop,'' said G. Alan Zimmermann, who follows the industry for
Smith Barney, Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   Investor skittishness was most evident among smaller insurers
with significant amounts of their business in auto or property and
casualty lines in California.
   Stock in 20th Century Industries dropped $1.87{ to $23.37{ per
share; Mercury General Corp. fell $1.50 to $15 a share; Safeco fell
$2.12{ to $26.50 a share, and Fireman's Fund fell 62{ cents to
$33.62{ a share.
   Larger companies presumably are less prone to be hurt by
regulatory decisions in any one state, but stock prices declined
for at least two big insurers which do at least 10 percent of their
property and casualty business in California. Chubb Corp. was down
$1.62{ to $64.62{ and Cigna declined 37{ cents to $52.50.
   The court unanimously upheld most provisions of the measure,
which requires insurers to submit rate hikes to state regulators
for approval, outlaws territorial rating, creates an elected job of
Insurance Commissioner and requires a good-driver discount
beginning in November, the first anniversary of Proposition 103's
passage.
   But the justices weakened the most controversial of Prop 103's
provisions: An immediate rate cut to 20 percent below November 1987
level.
   Prop 103 would have spared insurers the rate cut only if they
could prove it threatened them with insolvency. The court eased
that standard, ruling insurance companies are entitled to a ``fair
rate of return.''
   The measure was triggered by dramatic increases in the price of
car insurance, but affects most property and casualty coverage as
well.
   Wall Street analysts called the ruling bad news for the
business, but noted the rollback section softened the blow somewhat.
   However, Smith Barney's Zimmerman suggested a freshly elected
insurance commissioner would be unlikely to be generous in granting
exemptions.
   Confusion in the market likely will continue because of
uncertainty in interpreting the court's ``fair return'' standard,
said A. Michael Frinquelli, an analyst at Salomon Brothers in New
York.
   ``I think the turmoil now simply shifts from the Supreme Court
to the Insurance Commissioner's office,'' Frinquelli said.
   Another analyst, Marvin Shulman of Moody's Investors Service,
suggested that any rate cuts would be delayed by appeals and
administrative filings, thus blunting any immediate effect of the
ballot measure on insurers' earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
