<FIRST>r f BC-WestPoint-Pepperell     05-04 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-West Point-Pepperell,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clothing Maker Hires Investment Firm To Study Sale Of Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. announced
Thursday it has hired Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. to look at
options for selling or reorganizing West Point-Pepperell's men's
apparel division.
   The company said Drexel will explore alternatives including the
sale of all or parts of its Cluett Peabody division, a management
buyout and other forms of reorganization.
   The Cluett Peabody division manufactures and markets men's
shirts, suits and hosiery under the Arrow, Colours by Alexander
Julian, Burberry and Gold Toe labels.
   Chicago-based Farley Industries Inc. recently completed its $3
billion acquisition of West Point-Pepperell and is now the world's
largest textile and apparel manufacturer. Farley has said it plans
to sell part of West Point-Pepperell's non-bed-and-bath business to
reduce debt associated with the acquisition.
   William Farley, chairman of Farley, announced Wednesday that the
company will invest $12 million at West Point-Pepperell plants in
Hamilton, N.C., and Lumberton, N.C., creating nearly 500 new jobs.
   ``West Point-Pepperell today reminds me of Fruit of the Loom
when Farley Industries acquired it three years ago in a leveraged
buyout,'' Farley said.
   ``Since then, we've invested $340 million to make it a better
company. That's more than seven times what was invested during the
three years before we bought it. We've also added 9,000 workers.
Fruit of the Loom now employs 22,000 American textile and apparel
workers, all in the South,'' he said.
</TEXT>
