<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Eastern-Kennedy     05-04 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Eastern-Kennedy,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carrier Suspends Maintenance Operations at JFK Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines announced Thursday that it has
temporarily suspended maintenance operations at New York's John F.
Kennedy International Airport due to concern about the work
performed there.
   Eastern said investigations by the company and the Federal
Aviation Administration have raised questions about some work
performed at Kennedy Airport before the airline's union workers
walked out March 4.
   It said several supervisors had be reassigned to other duties
pending the completion of the probes. No action was taken against
non-supervisory workers represented by the Machinists union because
those workers are not on the company payroll due to the strike.
   A company audit of all maintenance performed at JFK and
throughout its system from July 1988 to February 1989 showed all
aircraft now in service were maintained to the highest standards,
Eastern said in a statement.
   The temporary suspension of maintenance was not expected to
affect flight operations, Eastern said.
   JFK is not being served under Eastern's current reduced
schedule. The company is only flying a fraction of its pre-strike
flights as it reorganizes under bankruptcy court protection.
</TEXT>
