<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 2246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Avon 2ndLd-Writethru f0266 05-04 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0266,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animals, Not Takeovers Dominate Avon Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Preston said ...,' to CORRECT price change
in stock.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc.'s chairman reiterated at
Thursday's annual shareholders meeting that the cosmetics giant
intends to remain independent and focus on its core beauty and
direct selling businesses.
   The assertion came a day after Minneapolis investor Irwin Jacobs
and rival Amway Corp. disclosed they had amassed a 10.3 percent
stake in Avon and might seek to acquire the company.
   But talk at the Avon meeting was dominated by animal rights
issues, not takeovers, as shareholders rejected a proposal to force
the company to disclose details of animal testing used for its
products.
   Chairman and Chief Executive James Preston got prolonged
applause when he opened the crowded meeting by saying, ``I want to
make it clear that Avon is not for sale.''
   Avon is completing the divestiture of its unprofitable
health-care services operations, which include nursing homes,
retirement living facilities and substance abuse treatment centers,
making this ``the worst time to sell'' the rest of the company,
Preston said.
   In addition, ``our distribution and selling systems _ to say
nothing of our culture and values _ are enormously different from
Amway. We see more conflicts than commonalities,'' he said.
   In March 1988, Avon's board approved a ``poison pill'' stock
plan aimed at making an unwanted takeover prohibitively expensive.
The plan was designed to ``encourage prospective acquirors to
negotiate with the board (and) ... deter takeover abuses,''
according to Avon's proxy statement.
   Some 54 percent of the shares voted on Thursday favored putting
the plan to a shareholder vote, but it did not constitute a
majority of the shares outstanding needed to pass the resolution.
   Only one shareholder voiced support for a takeover, saying that
``Irwin Jacobs and Amway have done more for the share price in the
last few days than management has done in the last year.''
   Preston said Avon stock _ which rose nearly $4 a share over the
past two days _ still did not reflect the value of its basic
businesses. The stock closed down 87{ cents Thursday at $36 in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Preston forecast that Avon should grow ``at least as fast as the
beauty industry, which is about 2 or 3 percent in real terms.'' He
said the international direct selling business and retail sales of
the company's Giorgio, Red and Uninhibited fragrances should lead
sales growth.
   Preston conceded that Avon's financial condition is ``not
strong.'' He said in the next five years Avon will attempt to halve
its debt _ which should total less than $1 billion at the end of
1989 and noted that cost-cutting measures will be offset somewhat
by severance payments to employees.
   Many securities analysts attending the meeting were more
concerned about how Avon's preferred shareholders would fare in the
face of a takeover.
   Preferred shares are convertible to roughly $34 in cash or to
one share of common stock. Preston stressed he would not speculate
about what action the company would take against a takeover.
   Most of the two-hour meeting was dominated by animal rights
issues. Preston's disclosure that Avon ``has not done any testing
on animals since March 15'' did little to calm more than a dozen
animal supporters attending the meeting.
   Shareholders ultimately defeated a proposal that would have
required Avon to disclose the number of animals and their species
used each year in both in-house and contract laboratories and
procedures that involve pain.
   Of the shares that voted on the proposal, 10.1 percent supported
it, which the special interest group People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals construed as somewhat of a victory. Last year,
a similar proposal garnered 6 percent of the vote.
   Several animal rights activitsts _ including one dressed as a
rabbit _ carried placards outside the posh Pierre Hotel on Fifth
Avenue, site of the meeting.
</TEXT>
