<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Argentina-Economy     05-04 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Argentina-Economy,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Market Reopens, Austral Weakens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina's currency exchange
market, closed for five days, reopened Wednesday and the austral,
the national currency that has been battered by recent plunges in
value, fell by 11.6 percent during the day's trading.
   The country also began adjusting to a new package of economic
measures, including price freezes and utility and fuel price
increases, that took effect Tuesday in a government effort to slow
triple-digit inflation.
   Argentines bought U.S. dollars for 76 australs apiece Wednesday
morning, and 86 australs at market closing, compared with 106
australs at one point last week.
   Those who sold dollars received 74 australs in the morning and
84 australs at the closing.
   Only 17 australs were required to buy a dollar in early February.
   The opening austral-dollar quotation was similar to that of last
Thursday, the most recent day the market operated. The Central
Bank, saying it had run short of the local currency, declared an
exchange holiday on Friday and, following a long May 1 weekend,
extended it until Wednesday.
   The reopening of the exchange market followed the announcement
Monday night of a new plan by the government of President Raul
Alfonsin to control inflation, which totaled 392.8 percent for the
12 months ended March 31. April inflation was expected to be 30 to
40 percent.
   The plan, which included a 45-day freeze on prices of most goods
and services, a 20 percent hike in utility rates and 25 percent
increase in gasoline prices and early payment of an annual mid-year
bonus to workers, went into effect Tuesday.
   The new measures were meant ``to bring peace to markets, stop
inflation and protect the needy,'' said Economy Minister Juan
Carlos Pugliese in a Tuesday night speech to the nation. He
observed, however, that those objectives ``are not easy to obtain''
in current cirumstances marked by ``uncertainty over the future.''
   Uncertainty stems, in part, from national elections, scheduled
for May 14, in which Argentines will pick a successor for Alfonsin,
whose term expires on Dec. 10. Opposition Peronist Party candidate
Carlos Menem leads Eduardo Angeloz, candidate for the ruling Civic
Radical Union, in most polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
