<DOCNO> AP890504-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-89 0047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Kroger-KKR     05-04 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kroger-KKR,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Sells Kroger Holding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., which held
nearly 10 percent of the stock of Cincinnati-based Kroger Co. from
a takeover attempt, apparently dumped its shares Wednesday.
   A 7.8-million-share block of Kroger stock was sold to an
unidentified buyer at 3:45 p.m., 15 minutes before the end of
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, it was reported by the Dow
Jones news wire.
   Although the identity of the seller was not disclosed, a proxy
statement recently issued by Kroger said Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
was the only investor holding that much stock in the grocery chain.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, a New York investment firm, bought the
stock nine months ago in an attempt to buy the chain.
   By the end of the day, 8.4 million shares of Kroger stock had
traded, making the stock the most active on the exchange Wednesday.
Kroger stock closed at $11.12{ down 50 cents, Wednesday.
   The buyout firm made a profit in the neighborhood of $19 million
on the sale of the 7.8-million-share block. KKR bought its
7,875,000 shares last October at $7.63 to $9.25 per share, or a
total of about $68.5 million.
   Kroger earlier rejected KKR's purchase offers. KKR later said it
was only interested in the stock as an investment.
   Kroger, operator of supermarkets, convenience stores and
food-processing plants, is undergoing a $4.6 billion reorganization
it began last fall in part to fight off takeover bids by KKR and
Dart Group Inc. of Landover, Md.
   Kroger spokesman Paul Bernish declined comment on the stock
movement. Thomas Daly, a representative of KKR, also refused
comment.
   ``Maybe they just decided they would use their cash in something
more aggressive,'' said Kimberly Walin, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
